<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retirment Funds Hit $1.7 Trillion  </HEADLINE>
    By GENARO C. ARMAS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As state and local government payrolls grow longer,
public employees' retirement funds grow fatter.
</P>
<P>
	   Total cash and security holdings for non-federal government retirement
systems rose to an all-time high of $1.7 trillion in fiscal year 1997-98, up
$237 billion from the previous year, according to data being released Thursday
by the U.S. Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the same period, the total number of full-time state and municipal
employees rose about 300,000 to 14.5 million, Census data indicates.
</P>
<P>
	   Thank the overall good health of the American economy for padding public
employees' retirement accounts, said Steve Regenstreif, director of the retiree
program for the American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees.
</P>
<P>
	   "In recent years, the health of it is due to the rise in the stock market,"
he said. "The majority of public sector retirement systems are now either fully-
or well-funded and this is a very good development."
</P>
<P>
	   Of the $1.7 trillion, the Census Bureau reported that more than $1.2
trillion was invested in non-governmental securities, including $639 billion in
corporate stocks, $258 billion in corporate bonds, and $195 billion in
international securities.
</P>
<P>
	   State and local governments are paying more attention to the future of their
employees, and more systems are offering the option of defined contribution
accounts like 401(k) plans as options, said Dallas Salisbury, president of the
Employee Benefit Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
	   There were 2,140 public employee retirement systems in 1997 nationwide.
Illinois had the most with 374, followed by Pennsylvania, which had 343. Hawaii
and Maine each had only one system that served all of their state and local
government employees.
</P>
<P>
	   California's 66 public employee retirement funds in 1997 totaled $291
billion in assets and served over 1.6 million members -- both highs in the U.S.
The largest is the California Public Employees' Retirement System, with about
$165 billion in assets covering 1 million people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
