<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 12 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Wednesday, Feb. 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Urges Global Warming Funds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will propose a major increase in
federal spending to combat global warming and pollution, along with new tax
incentives to encourage business to invest in environmentally friendly
technology, White House officials said Wednesday. In his upcoming budget
request, Clinton will ask Congress for $2.4 billion for various initiatives
designed to reduce the harmful effect of global climate change, said Roger
Ballantine, White House environmental adviser. The mount is more than 40 percent
above what Congress approved last year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. Chief Warns of New Arms Race
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Calling efforts toward global disarmament deplorable,
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan warned Wednesday that "a dangerous new arms
race looms on the horizon." "More countries have nuclear-weapon capability than
ever before," the secretary-general said. He cited "a discouraging list" of
nuclear disarmament measures that are stalled and initiatives that haven't
gotten off the ground, including the START II accord, signed in 1993 and
ratified by the U.S. Senate in 1996. It was intended to halve U.S. and Russian
nuclear arsenals to 3,000-3,500 warheads each. But Russia's parliament has
balked at ratifying the accord.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Alaska Air Flight Recorder Recovered
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PORT HUENEME, Calif. (AP) -- One of the flight data recorders that could
hold the answer to the cause of Monday's Alaska Airlines crash off the Los
Angeles coast was recovered Wednesday night by an unmanned vehicle. The search
for survivors ended earlier today. Investigators said today they were looking
into a report that the plane had problems with a part of the tail called the
horizontal stabilizer on the flight to Mexico. Records of radio conversations
between the pilots and air traffic controllers showed the crew was struggling
with stabilizer problems before the plane nose-dived into the sea, killing all
88 aboard.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Eight Convicted in Argentina Murder
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A tribunal sentenced eight people to life in
prison Wednesday in the death of a crusading journalist, ending a case that
shocked Argentines and drew international outrage. A three-judge panel found
three former provincial police officers, a former security guard and four
civilians guilty of killing Jose Luis Cabezas, an investigative photojournalist.
A fourth police officer was sentenced to four years on a fraud charge related to
the case. The 36-year-old photographer had been shadowing Alfredo Yabran, a
camera-shy businessman whose links to government officials and vast business
empire had come under question.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pfizer, Warner-Lambert Work on Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Pfizer Inc. and Warner-Lambert Co. are working out the
details of a deal that would form the second-largest pharmaceutical maker in the
world, as Pfizer tentatively agreed Wednesday to raise its takeover bid to $85
billion, according to two people familiar with the negotiations. The companies
must now placate American Home Products, the losing suitor in a 3-month fight
for control of Warner-Lambert. American Home had signed a $59 million deal in
November to acquire Warner-Lambert before Pfizer trumped the bid.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fed Nudges Interest Rates Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve, still seeking to slow the
supercharged U.S. economy, raised borrowing costs for millions of Americans for
a fourth time since June by pushing a key interest rate up a quarter point to
5.75 percent today. The Fed action to boost its federal funds rate, the interest
that banks charge each other, was quickly followed by announcements from major
banks around the country that they were raising their prime lending rate a
similar quarter point to 8.75 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Jolt Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices ended the Thursday morning session sharply
higher amid hopes that the planned launch of several new investment trust funds
will draw more investors to the market. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock
Average ended the morning session up 217.45 points at 19,796.36 points. On
Wednesday, the average closed up 155.53 points. The Dow Jones industrial average
fell 37.85 to close at 11,003.20 on Wednesday. The Nasdaq was up 21.98 to
4,073.96.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Miss. St. Beats No. 22 LSU 68-66
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   STARKVILLE, Miss. (AP) -- Derrick Zimmerman hit a tiebreaking 3-pointer with
24 seconds left and Mississippi State overcame a 12-point deficit in the final 5
1/2 minutes to beat No. 22 LSU 68-66 Wednesday night. Tang Hamilton had 12
points of his 16 points in the second half for the Bulldogs. Robert Jackson
scored 14, all after halftime. Torris Bright led LSU (16-4, 3-4 Southeastern
Conference) with 17. Stromile Swift had 14, but just two in the second half.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS
</P>
</TEXT>
