<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anger Over Minority-Ownership Rule  </HEADLINE>
    By PETER ALAN HARPER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Leading black and Hispanic entrepreneurs are challenging a
move by a key corporate advisory group to drop a requirement that firms be 51
percent minority-owned to qualify for certain corporate contracts.
</P>
<P>
	   These leaders contend that this will lead to the end of affirmative action,
while creating fronts for white-owned firms to scoop up billions of dollars in
equity capital.
</P>
<P>
	   "If you don't think that our community is not receiving venture and equity
capital now, what makes you think this will change?" George Herrera, president
and chief executive of the Hispanic Chamber of Commerce, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   But the president of the National Minority Supplier Development Council
countered that her group had created a solution to a pressing problem: Many of
the companies that currently quality are too small to attract large investments
and instead have to rely on loans.
</P>
<P>
	   The NMSDC says that under the new rules, companies would be more attractive
to venture capitalists and other investors because they could potentially be
larger.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the 15,000 firms the NMSDC certifies, at least three-fourths have instead
had to rely on debt financing.
</P>
<P>
	   The 51 percent rule still applies, but the NMSDC created a new class of firm
that can be 30 percent minority-owned as long as 51 percent of the voting stock
is held by minorities and that they control the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, NMSDC-certified firms won more than $40 billion in contracts from
NMSDC members, a group of 3,500 companies that includes more than half of the
Fortune 500.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposed rule change, which has been under consideration for more than a
year, led to the creation of a coalition last fall of civil rights leaders from
the NAACP, the National Urban League and the National Action Network along with
Earl G. Graves, the publisher of Black Enterprise, elected officials and
Hispanic business leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   Because of the objections, the NMSDC had its 78-member advisory board vote
in private, with a majority deciding by Tuesday to change the rules.
</P>
<P>
	   The coalition fears that Congress will take its cue from the vote and end
affirmative action, which has ushered innumerable small companies into the
business world.
</P>
<P>
	   "The rules are being changed because of the proliferation of minority-owned
businesses," Herrera said.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's a thing called racism that necessitated that affirmative action
come into being. When did that go away?" Graves said. "There's not a (major)
minority contractor in construction in the New York area."
</P>
<P>
	   But Harriet Michel, the head of the NMSDC, said it's not likely there will
be majority-owned fronts because "this is going to be the most highly-controlled
investigation into certification in the country."
</P>
<P>
	   "There is no absolute," she said. "There are corporations today that accept
companies without any certification."
</P>
<P>
	   The new rules are expected to go into effect in about 90 days,
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
