<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney 2000 Accepts Rescue Package  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN PYE-
Associated Press Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The organizing committee for the Sydney 2000 Olympics
has accepted a rescue package aimed at curbing its $123 million budget blowout.
</P>
<P>
	As a tradeoff, SOCOG has surrendered some of its responsibilities as the New
South Wales State Government, which is underwriting the Olympics, seeks a ``more
hands on'' approach to hosting the event.
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG agreed to the rescue package, which still has to be ratified by the New
South Wales treasurer, during a board meeting Thursday following revelations of
an expected ticket revenue shortfall of some $48 million.
</P>
<P>
	Projected sponsorship shortfall had already reached almost $69 million.
</P>
<P>
	The package involves the Australian Olympic Committee and the International
Olympic Committee each forgoing $7 million from their respective shares of the
SOCOG budgeted surplus.
</P>
<P>
	The New South Wales Government also agreed to forgo its budgeted surplus of
$19.1 million.
</P>
<P>
	The agreement reduces SOCOG's budget deficit by $33 million. Other budget cuts
will be announced following the next SOCOG board meeting on Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG president and Olympics Minister Michael Knight, who last year predicted
record profits from the 2000 Games, downscaled his expectations Thursday, saying
that SOCOG was aiming to balance the budget.
</P>
<P>
	``There won't be a profit, we're certainly not looking for a profit, but we're
pretty confident we can deliver a balanced budget,'' Knight said.
</P>
<P>
	He said IOC coordination committee chief Jacques Rogge supported the budget
measures.
</P>
<P>
	AOC president John Coates, who is also the SOCOG vice president, said the
Australian Olympic Committee ``doesn't blame'' anyone from SOCOG for the budget
problems and insisted that the previous profit projections had been inflated.
</P>
<P>
	Under the new agreement, the Government-run Olympic Coordination Authority will
take over responsibility for operational programs and budgets for all games
venues other than the Olympic villages.
</P>
<P>
	Up to 10 SOCOG employees will also be seconded to the OCA as the groups bid to
streamline running and increase efficiency.
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG will retain responsibility for the Torch relay, technology, the workforce
and the sporting aspect of the event, while SOCOG chief operating officer Jim
Sloman will remain in charge of the overall running of the Olympic program.
</P>
<P>
	Knight said SOCOG would now focus on ``delivering sports, which is still very
much at the center of the Games.''
</P>
<P>
	He said the ticket revenue shortfall had been identified following a ``very
detailed scoping of the number of seats available'' after accounting for ``seat
kills,'' which is the number of seats lost to sporting federations and media.
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG officials said people who had already purchased tickets would be almost
assured of receiving their tickets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0012 </TRAILER>
