<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solution Sought in Northern Ireland  </HEADLINE>
   By SHAWN POGATCHNIK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Faced with a crisis over the Irish
Republican Army's refusal to disarm, the prime ministers of Britain and Ireland
are hoping to find a way to prevent the collapse of the fledgling
Protestant-Catholic administration in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
	   Tony Blair of Britain and Bertie Ahern of Ireland scheduled an emergency
summit today in a bid to save the four-party coalition, which faces suspension
or collapse just nine weeks after receiving considerable powers from Britain.
</P>
<P>
	   Leaders of the major Protestant party, the Ulster Unionist Party, insist
they had agreed to accept the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party as Cabinet colleagues
only on condition that the IRA responded rapidly by cooperating with a
disarmament commission.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the IRA promptly met the commission's chairman, Canadian Gen. John
de Chastelain, a still-confidential report from the general presented this week
to Blair and Ahern confirmed that disarmament has not begun.
</P>
<P>
	   That has left the Ulster Unionists warning they will have to resign their
Cabinet posts, probably by next week. Their party grassroots only narrowly voted
to form the Cabinet on an experimental basis and in expectation that the IRA
would respond.
</P>
<P>
	   The dilemma facing Blair and Ahern is how to keep the Ulster Unionists in
the Cabinet even though no imminent act of IRA disarmament appears to be on
offer. Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble faces a potential revolt at the
party's next internal meeting Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
	   Britain's most likely recourse -- to reverse the recently transferred
powers, leaving the Cabinet powerless but intact -- is being sternly criticized
by both Sinn Fein and the Cabinet's main Catholic-supported party, the pacifist
Social Democratic and Labor Party or SDLP.
</P>
<P>
	   Ahern and Blair were expected to meet somewhere in southwest England in the
afternoon. Blair's secretary for Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson, was expected
to then announce the government's intentions in Parliament, though this could be
delayed if the two governments couldn't agree on the strategy ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   Ahern spent two hours Wednesday discussing the prospects for IRA
disarmament, and the potential fallout from a Cabinet suspension, with a Sinn
Fein delegation led by party leader Gerry Adams. The Irish side reportedly was
pressing for an unambiguous IRA statement promising it would disarm.
</P>
<P>
	   Afterward, Adams insisted that he remained personally committed to securing
the gradual scrapping of the IRA's network of arms dumps -- a goal that the 1998
accord expected to be completed by this May -- but that the IRA wasn't inclined
to meet Ulster Unionist demands.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the consequence of requiring a start to IRA disarmament now or
suspending the Cabinet, in which Sinn Fein holds two of the 12 posts, would be
``disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Seamus Mallon, deputy leader of the SDLP and the Cabinet's top Catholic
minister, said de Chastelain had been appointed chairman of the disarmament
commission in 1997 and it was reasonable to ask the IRA that if it ever intended
to disarm, ``why not now?''
</P>
<P>
	   ``To refuse when everything else of substance within the Good Friday accord
has been implemented or put in train fuels the reasonable suspicion -- and not
just in unionist minds -- that the IRA as an organization is incapable of
renouncing violence or the threat of violence for political purposes,'' Mallon
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0136 </TRAILER>
