<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Govt. Decision Near  </HEADLINE>
   By MELISSA EDDY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Austria's president has made it unmistakably clear
he doesn't want to approve a new government including Joerg Haider's far-right
anti-immigrant party. But he admits he has little choice.
</P>
<P>
	   President Thomas Klestil is expected to confirm the coalition today, despite
a growing wave of threats and protests from abroad against a government with
Haider's Freedom party.
</P>
<P>
	   In an attempt to spare Austria international isolation, Klestil has
requested Haider and Wolfgang Schuessel, head of the conservative People's Party
and the likely new chancellor, sign a ``declaration of values of European
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
	   The first fallout came Wednesday, when Israel's Prime Minister Ehud Barak
called Haider ``dangerous'' to democracy and recalled his country's ambassador
from Vienna for an indefinite period.
</P>
<P>
	   At home, outrage over the proposed coalition spilled into the streets
Wednesday. Police said some 15,000 people rallied in the evening in front of the
People's Party headquarters to protest the coalition deal.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Prove yourself to be a patriot,'' theater producer Andre Heller told the
crowd in remarks directed to Schuessel. ``No alliance with meanness. No alliance
with right-wing radicalism.''
</P>
<P>
	   But no one seemed to be able the stop the players involved.
</P>
<P>
	   In a meeting that ended after midnight today, the executive committee of
Schuessel's Austrian People's Party adopted the coalition agreement with only
one dissenting vote. The Freedom Party had endorsed it unanimously a day
earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   Neither party has confirmed the makeup of the government under the coalition
deal reached Tuesday. The Austria Press Agency reported the posts would be split
evenly between the two parties, with Schuessel as chancellor and a Freedom Party
member as vice chancellor. Haider was not expected to take a Cabinet position.
</P>
<P>
	   The Interior Ministry would go to a member of the People's Party, the agency
said. The Interior Ministry is responsible for immigration and the police --
high priorities for the Freedom Party, which wants to restrict immigration and
has a tough law and order image.
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview published Thursday, Klestil took the unusual step of sharply
criticizing both Haider and Schuessel. Still, he said he had to follow the
results of Oct. 3 parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In a democracy, a parliamentary majority must be respected,'' Klestil
said. ``Personal sensitivities do not count.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Should I swear in this government, I wouldn't do it out of personal
conviction, because I fear that international damage will be inflicted upon
Austria,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   That fear is shared by other politicians.
</P>
<P>
	   Alexander Van der Bellen, the widely respected leader of the Greens party,
called Haider a ``stubborn repeat offender'' and expressed dismay over Haider's
``undifferentiated'' attacks against ``our friends and neighbors'' in Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   A source close to Klestil, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
president rejected some of the Cabinet nominees put forward by Haider.
</P>
<P>
	   Haider won international notoriety around a decade ago by praising Adolf
Hitler's ``orderly'' employment policies and lauding veterans of the murderous
Waffen SS as ``men of honor.''
</P>
<P>
	   Haider has also spoken out against the EU's expansion and has predicted the
new government will impose a nearly complete ban on immigration.
</P>
<P>
	   With an agreement between Haider and Schuessel in place, attention has
shifted to President Klestil, a courtly 67-year-old former career diplomat.
Although his post is largely ceremonial, the president must swear in a new
government.
</P>
<P>
	   In principle, Klestil could reject the coalition and even call new
elections, although such a move would be unprecedented in Austria's post-World
War II history.
</P>
<P>
	   In October's parliament vote, the Freedom Party took second place, closely
followed by the People's Party. The leading Social Democrats failed to agree on
a coalition with the People's Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0142 </TRAILER>
