<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Garcia Wins in MLB Arbitration Case  </HEADLINE>
   By RONALD BLUM
AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   For the first time in four years, baseball players opened salary
arbitration with a win.
</P>
<P>
	   Karim Garcia beat the Detroit Tigers on Wednesday and will get
his $700,000 request instead of the team's $470,000 offer.
</P>
<P>
	   Garcia, 24, hit .240 last year with 14 homers and 32 RBIs in 288
at-bats and made $270,000.
</P>
<P>
	   The last time players opened with a win was 1996, when they
began arbitration 4-0. Rick Shapiro argued the case for Garcia and
Houston Astros president Tal Smith for the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
	   Arbitrators Robert Light, Richard Kasher and Jack Clarke, who
heard arguments Tuesday, made the decision overnight.
</P>
<P>
	   Oakland right-hander Ariel Prieto, who hasn't pitched in the
major leagues since April 1998, was the only player to go to a
hearing Wednesday, asking for a raise from $210,000 to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
	   The Athletics countered at $300,000. A decision was expected
today from Stephen Goldberg, James Gross and Ted High. All cases
are being heard by three-person panels this year in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
	   Prieto, 30, is recovering from reconstructive elbow and shoulder
surgery and hasn't pitched in the major leagues since April 19,
1998. He was Oakland's opening day starter in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Three players who filed for arbitration agreed to contracts
Wednesday. Milwaukee right-hander Juan Acevedo got a two-year deal
worth $1,625,000, Detroit catcher Gregg Zaun got a $525,000,
one-year contract, and New York Mets pinch-hitter Matt Franco got a
$462,500, one-year deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Thirty players remain in arbitration, with hearings scheduled
through Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
	   Among free agents, the Yankees agreed to a minor league contract
with 33-year-old infielder Rafael Bournigal, who would get a
$500,000, one-year contract if he makes the team.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, he hit .274 with two homers and 14 RBIs in 95 at-bats
with the Seattle Mariners. New York has been looking for a backup
infielder to replace D'Angelo Jimenez, who fractured a bone in his
neck in a car crash last week and is not expected to play again
until the fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Outfielder Darren Bragg, released St. Louis in December, agreed
to a one-year contract with Colorado. Right-hander Julio Santana,
released by Boston in December, agreed to a minor league contract
with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, the San Diego Padres reversed course and ended their minor
league contract with outfielder Danny Tartabull, who wanted bonuses
based on games played rather than started. Instead, the Padres are
closing in on a deal with third baseman Ed Sprague.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Depending on what happens, he could find his way into the
starting lineup,'' general manager Kevin Towers said. ``He's got to
realize that he could be a role player, but (manager Bruce) Bochy's
the type of guy who's going to go with the best nine.''
</P>
<P>
	   In other baseball news, Arizona put reliever Bobby Chouinard on
waivers at the pitcher's request.
</P>
<P>
	   The 27-year-old right-hander, 5-2 last season with a 2.68 ERA in
32 appearances, faces 5-15 years in prison if convicted of charges
he choked and slapped his wife, Erica, on Christmas night and
pointed a loaded handgun at her head as she pleaded for him not to
shoot her.
</P>
<P>
	   If no team claims Chouinard by Friday, he would become a free
agent and receive $32,967, which is 30 days termination pay.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I didn't want to go into training camp with anything hanging
over heads -- for him, for us, for everyone involved,'' owner Jerry
Colangelo said. ``That's no way to go into a camp situation, so one
way or another this would have been resolved before training
camp.''
</P>
<P>
	   In the first round of the playoffs, Chouinard gave up the
game-winning grand slam to Edgardo Alfonzo in the ninth inning of
the New York Mets' 8-4 victory over the Diamondbacks in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am receiving counseling to resolve some difficult and
regrettable problems,'' he said in a statement issued by the team.
``In the best interests of my family and of baseball, I have asked
the Diamondbacks to release me so that I can concentrate on
continuing to work on my personal and family issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
