<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Feud Between Greene and Boldon  </HEADLINE>
By BERT ROSENTHAL-
AP Track Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Feud? What feud?
</P>
<P>
	The one between Maurice Greene and Ato Boldon.
</P>
<P>
	Actually, it never happened.
</P>
<P>
	The purported disagreement between the two world-class sprinters and HSI
teammates grew out of a story in the Trinidad Express.
</P>
<P>
	``I gave an interview ... to let the people of Trinidad and Tobago know about
what's happening with me,'' said Boldon, a native of that country. ``I was asked
if there would be any `tag-teaming' with me and Maurice this year.
</P>
<P>
	``I said it will be every man for himself. I will do things independently off
the track. I said sprinters have to get self-centered, because this year is all
about gold medals.
</P>
<P>
	``The story was blown out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
	It became so magnified that even Boldon's family got concerned.
</P>
<P>
	``It got to the point where my mother called, and Maurice and I were sitting on
the floor watching the Sugar Bowl,'' Boldon said.
</P>
<P>
	Greene, the world record-holder and two-time world champion in the 100 meters,
and Boldon, the 1997 world champion at 200 meters, are still very close. They
train together and socialize occasionally.
</P>
<P>
	And Friday night, they will line up side-by-side for the 60 meters at the
Millrose Games in Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
	Greene, an accomplished indoor runner who holds the 60-meter world record of
6.39 seconds, is leery about predicting another record in his season's debut.
</P>
<P>
	``I hope to put on a show like I always do at Millrose,'' Greene, the two-time
defending champion, said.
</P>
<P>
	Greene is excited about the new Mondo surface that has replaced the wooden
boards at the Garden.
</P>
<P>
	``When you set a world record, it's not necessarily the surface,'' he said.
``I'm not going in thinking about a world record. But the surface is going to
help. Mondo? Wow!''
</P>
<P>
	Boldon, less of an indoor specialist, normally would skip the Millrose Games,
but he is coming back from an injury and wants to get the feel of competition
again.
</P>
<P>
	``I've done a good job of rehabbing,'' Boldon said of the strained hamstring
that forced him to miss the latter part of the 1999 outdoor season, including
the World Championships at Seville, Spain.
</P>
<P>
	``I've tested it in practice. But there will be a difference between
competition and practice. The purpose of my running the indoor season is to get
back into competition and not get stale.''
</P>
<P>
	The injury, the first major one of Boldon's career, caused him much
trepidation.
</P>
<P>
	``I hadn't missed a meet before,'' Boldon, 26, said. ``I've been on the circuit
since I was 18. But I couldn't walk faster than average speed. It was difficult.
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it could be career-threatening because it was very painful.''
</P>
<P>
	Boldon will run 3-4 indoor meets -- all in Europe -- after Millrose, then go to
Australia, before returning to his Los Angeles training base and prepare for his
first outdoor meet, the Mount San Antonio Relays at Walnut, Calif., in April.
</P>
<P>
	Boldon already has seen the Olympic stadium in Sydney, and was dismayed by the
intense wind.
</P>
<P>
	``The wind is all wrong,'' he said. ``It blows directly down the straight where
we run. It's similar to Barcelona because of the wind. I'll run to win. Time
will matter the least.''
</P>
<P>
	Greene, who had a full 1999 season, will compete once in Europe, then join
Boldon in Australia. Unlike Boldon, who will not compete in Australia, Greene
plans to run a couple of races, mainly to get used to the surroundings and
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
	``Last year was great, but I have to do even better this year,'' said Greene,
who set the world 100-meter record of 9.79 in 1999 and won gold medals in the
100, 200 and 400 relay at the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
	Greene also then will compete at Mount SAC, as he and Boldon step up their
preparations for a possible showdown at Sydney.
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to try and impress the world even more this year,'' Greene said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
