<DOCNO> APW20000203.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Catfish Farmers Go High-Tech  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TCHULA, Miss. (AP) -- Mississippi catfish farmers are investing in computer
chips and other high-tech gear to track fish-eating birds from satellites
orbiting Earth.
</P>
<P>
	   The battle against the double-crested cormorants has escalated once again.
The species was once nearly decimated by agricultural chemicals and other
poisons.
</P>
<P>
	   But the birds have bounced back to bite fish farmers in Mississippi and
neighboring states, with the population in interior North America now increasing
by an average of 29 percent a year to up to 1 million birds or more.
</P>
<P>
	   "They are breeding in areas where they have never nested before," said Tommy
King, a biologist at the National Wildlife Research Center in Starkville, an arm
of the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
	   The first cormorant nests in more than 50 years were found in Mississippi in
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Fish farmers and sport-fishing interests to the north are demanding more
controls on cormorant numbers.
</P>
<P>
	   The information the biologists are collecting will be used to prepare a
nationwide management plan, so any controls can be minimized. To do that, more
must be known about the birds' habits, including where they travel through the
year and how much time they spend in certain places.
</P>
<P>
	   Understanding more about cormorants will lead to more reasonable, publicly
acceptable controls, federal biologists say.
</P>
<P>
	   "The American public demands that we take ecological approaches," said Mark
Tobin, who supervises King and other USDA biologists trying to mediate the
cormorant dispute.
</P>
<P>
	   "Nobody wants to kill all the birds," said Sterling Withers of Tunica,
president of the Catfish Farmers of Mississippi, an industry group. "The more
information we have, the better decisions we can make. There's a degree of
balance we need."
</P>
<P>
	   The northern-nesting cormorants have flown south each winter for easy
pickings at the catfish ponds. More than 60,000 cormorants spend each winter in
the Mississippi Delta.
</P>
<P>
	   Two years ago, fish farmers in Mississippi and other states won federal
permission to shoot an unlimited number of cormorants on farms. Producers say
the shooting is not putting much of a dent in the cormorant population.
</P>
<P>
	   Farmers also have tried to drive away the birds with noise-making pistols.
Lately, biologists are testing devices that aim harmless laser beams into the
nighttime roosts to flush the birds.
</P>
<P>
	   This winter, 25 of the cormorants are being fitted with satellite-tracking
devices so their movements between Great Lakes-area breeding grounds and winter
haunts in the South can be traced.
</P>
<P>
	   King's team has attached 15 transmitters so far. They plan to outfit birds
in Mississippi, Alabama, Arkansas and Louisiana. Counting the expense of
retrieving data from satellites, tracking each bird for a year will cost about
$4,400.
</P>
<P>
	   The cormorants, which travel in flocks by the hundreds, seem to eat whatever
fish they can catch by diving in the ponds.
</P>
<P>
	   King is not surprised solving the cormorant conflict demands the use of
satellites and other high-tech tools. He thinks the birds can recognize
"individual vehicles" around fish ponds that may be a threat to them.
</P>
<P>
	   Outsmarting the cormorants, King said, will take smart weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0209 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Morris' Agent Denies Bam Wrongdoing  </HEADLINE>
    By DOUG TUCKER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Retired running back Bam Morris is claiming
innocence in his latest involvement in a drug case.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris, who unexpectedly announced his retirement from the Kansas City
Chiefs last month, and teammate Tamarick Vanover were mentioned in an affidavit
filed last week in connection with drug distribution charges lodged against a
Kansas City man, Gregory Burns.
</P>
<P>
	   "If I thought my client was involved in criminal activity, we wouldn't be
talking to the press," Morris' agent, Terry Lavenstein, said Wednesday from his
Baltimore office. "I'd like to get his name cleared as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
	   Vanover's representative didn't return calls from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   The affidavit said the distribution ring stretched from Missouri to
California and Mexico. Burns, described in the affidavit as a personal assistant
to Vanover, was named as a major supplier of marijuana and cocaine in the Kansas
City area.
</P>
<P>
	   Neither Morris nor Vanover, who won a game against Denver for the Chiefs
this season with an 80-yard punt return, has been charged.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, authorities at the University of Kansas said they would contact
federal officials to discuss a report that one person had been denied bail
because he was supplying drugs to Jayhawks football players and fraternities.
</P>
<P>
	   FBI agents said that Chad M. Pollard "has supplied members of the Kansas
University football team with drugs since 1996 as well as various Kansas
University fraternities," according to documents quoted by The Kansas City Star.
</P>
<P>
	   Athletic director Bob Frederick said he met Wednesday with chancellor Robert
Hemenway and that neither man knew anything about the claims.
</P>
<P>
	   Frederick said he asked Ralph Oliver, the school's director of public
safety, to contact the FBI for further information.
</P>
<P>
	   "The university is not an investigative body," Frederick said. "Ralph said
he probably wouldn't be able to be very successful."
</P>
<P>
	   Amy Perko, the associate athletic director who oversees Kansas' mandatory
drug-testing program, said athletes are subject to "a significant number of
tests throughout the year."
</P>
<P>
	   "The results of those tests are all confidential," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris, who spent 89 days in a Texas jail in 1998 for violating probation
from a 1995 drug case, was mentioned once in the affidavit filed in connection
with the arrest of Burns. Vanover was mentioned several times.
</P>
<P>
	   The Chiefs, already reeling from a one-car accident on Jan. 23 that left
star linebacker Derrick Thomas paralyzed from the chest down, were taking a
wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
	   "Nobody here knows anything about it," team spokesman Bob Moore said. "If
something happens, it happens. But our people are not rushing back from (the Pro
Bowl in) Hawaii because of this."
</P>
<P>
	   Pollard and Logan Gearheart, from Kansas City, Kan., were charged early last
month with drug trafficking. Both pleaded innocent at hearings and Gearheart was
released on bond.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris, who unexpectedly retired from the NFL less than two weeks ago, twice
was suspended by the NFL for substance abuse while with the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
	   "Bam, unfortunately, will continue to have to live with the mistake he made
in 1995," Lavenstein said. "Any time an NFL player is involved in some type of
criminal activity, no matter how slight, the Bam Morris incident is going to be
brought up. That's something we have to live with, no matter how unfair that may
be."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
