<HEADLINE> Marriage Penalty Tax Relief Urged  </HEADLINE>
   By CURT ANDERSON AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans are forging ahead with a bill that would cut
income taxes for millions of married couples by $182 billion over 10 years, but
Democrats say it represents a warmed-over tax cut that was already rejected.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton will not go along with the House GOP strategy of dividing
last year's vetoed $792 billion tax cut into pieces like the ``marriage
penalty'' bill, all in an effort to put Democrats in a difficult political spot
-- even though Clinton has a smaller marriage penalty proposal of his own.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You can change the tactics, you can change the packaging, but if the
overall goal is to do a trillion-dollar tax cut to squeeze Social Security and
Medicare, we're going to oppose it,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
	   Nevertheless, the House Ways and Means Committee voted along party lines
Wednesday to clear the bill for floor vote as early as next week, just in time
for Valentine's Day on Feb. 14. Republicans accused Democrats of playing games
on tax cuts to forestall any GOP legislative victories in this election year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's either too big, or it's too early, or it's too late, or it's too
risky,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, the Ways and Means Committee chairman.
``There's always some excuse.''
</P>
<P>
	   About 25 million couples, most of them with dual incomes, pay more income
taxes than they would if single. Millions more couples in which one spouse is
the main breadwinner get a marriage bonus through current tax law. The GOP bill
would cut taxes for all of them.
</P>
<P>
	   At an estimated cost of $182.3 billion over 10 years, the Republican bill
would consume about 10 percent of the projected budget surplus not dedicated to
Social Security, according to congressional estimates.
</P>
<P>
	   Much of the cost comes from gradual enlargement, between years 2003 to 2008,
of the bottom 15 percent tax bracket so that it applies to more income for
married couples. If that were in effect today, married couples would pay the 15
percent rate on their first $52,500 of taxable income, instead of $43,850.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, the GOP bill would increase the standard deduction for joint
tax filers to double that of single filers beginning in 2001 and expand the
earned-income tax credit for lower-income married people.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's proposal, estimated at $45 billion over 10 years, includes similar
provisions to boost the standard deduction and on the earned-income credit --
both geared more toward people with modest incomes -- but does not adjust the 15
percent bracket, which generally would help higher-income couples.
</P>
<P>
	   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said the legislation came far
too early in the year, before a budget framework has been worked out on how to
treat Social Security, Medicare, payment of debt and key spending priorities.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is no budget. We don't know how this fits into any larger picture,''
Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
	   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers told lawmakers he would recommend a
presidential veto of the GOP bill.
</P>
<P>
	   Senate Republicans are divided about pushing individual tax relief bills, in
part because Senate rules make it more difficult. Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., told reporters he supports the thrust of the House approach but may try
to combine the tax bills into a big single measure later in the year. ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITORS NOTE: The bill is HR6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0211 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0053 </DOCNO>
