<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Convicted in Argentina Murder  </HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN GRAY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- It was a case that had all the makings for a
crime novel page-turner: allegations of government corruption, rogue police
officers, a powerful businessman accused of being a crime boss, and a crusading
photojournalist hoping to unmask it all.
</P>
<P>
	   Ending a three-year-old national saga, an Argentine tribunal sentenced eight
people to life in prison Wednesday for the mafia-style killing of Jose Luis
Cabezas, an investigative journalist whose shocking murder is one of the most
notorious homicides in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
	   The eight included three former provincial police officers, four civilians
and the former security guard of a prominent business mogul suspected of crime
links whom Cabezas had photographed.
</P>
<P>
	   A fourth police officer was sentenced to four years in prison on a fraud
charge related to the case.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm comfortable with the decisions handed down by the tribunal,'' Cabezas'
mother, Maria Cristina Robledo said, leaving the courthouse. ``My son can now
rest in peace.''
</P>
<P>
	   The 36-year-old Cabezas was found dead Jan 25, 1997, in the glitzy Atlantic
coast resort of Pinamar, 250 miles south of Buenos Aires. He had been
handcuffed, beaten, shot in the head, doused in gasoline and torched.
</P>
<P>
	   The slaying shocked Argentines and was eerily reminiscent of the work of
military death squads from the country's 1976-83 dictatorship. Argentine
journalists condemned the killing as evidence of an increasing threat against
freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
	   International press organizations rallied around the case as an example of
the risk Argentine journalists and others in Latin America run investigating
organized crime and political scandals.
</P>
<P>
	   Nationwide protests ensued as demonstrators cried out for justice. Posters
with the photographer's picture and the slogan ``Don't forget Cabezas'' can
still be seen in many parts of Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
	   Cabezas was killed while working on assignment for Noticias magazine, a
weekly newsmagazine known for its hard-edged delving into alleged wrongdoing by
politicians, police officers and labor leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   He had been shadowing reclusive businessman Alfredo Yabran. In 1995, former
Economy Minister Domingo Cavallo accused Yabran of heading up an extensive crime
network and employing former ``dirty war'' military officers to control
government officials, judges, and several business entities. No formal charges
were ever lodged against him.
</P>
<P>
	   Cabezas had taken some of the few published photographs of Yabran, who
immediately became a prime suspect in the photographer's death, along with his
chief security guard, Gregorio Rios.
</P>
<P>
	   Rios was among those given life in prison late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Yabran repeatedly denied allegations he was involved in the killing. Wanted
by authorities last year for questioning, he went on the run and became the
focus of a nationwide manhunt. He committed suicide by shooting himself in the
mouth as police closed in on him at his country resort last May. A handwritten
note left by his side professed his innocence.
</P>
<P>
	   But the damage to Yabran's public image was already done. To everyday
Argentines, frustrated by a judicial system they deride as sluggish, corrupt and
protective of the rich, Yabran had become a symbol of impunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0215 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Guards Charged in Inmate Death  </HEADLINE>
   By RON WORD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STARKE, Fla. (AP) -- Four prison guards spent a night in jail after being
charged with second-degree murder in the fatal beating of an inmate sent to
death row for killing a prison guard in 1987.
</P>
<P>
	   Capt. Timothy Thornton and Sgts. Jason Griffis, Charles A. Brown and Robert
W. Sauls were to make their first court appearances today in Bradford County
Circuit Court.
</P>
<P>
	   All were named in an indictment issued Wednesday by an Alachua County grand
jury. The indictment was expected to be unsealed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   If convicted, they face up to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm genuinely shocked that he was indicted,'' said Hank Coxe, a
Jacksonville attorney representing Griffis. ``I look forward to finding out
why.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a travesty of justice,'' said Gloria Fletcher, Thornton's attorney.
``The man didn't do anything. He was doing his job.''
</P>
<P>
	   The four men were among nine guards suspended after Frank Valdes died on
July 17 during a confrontation inside a disciplinary area at Florida State
Prison near Starke.
</P>
<P>
	   Guards said Valdes, 36, had severely injured himself by throwing himself off
his bunk onto the concrete floor of his cell. But an autopsy showed he was
beaten to death. A medical examiner said Valdes had boot marks on his body, his
ribs were broken and his testicles were swollen.
</P>
<P>
	   Thornton, 34, Griffis and Brown, both 26, turned themselves in Wednesday at
the Bradford County Jail. Sauls, 37, was arrested at his girlfriend's house in
Jasper, about 75 miles away. Each was being held on $100,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
	   Valdes was sentenced to death for the fatal shooting of a prison guard while
attempting to help a fellow inmate escape in 1987.
</P>
<P>
	   Another prison guard, Sgt. Montrez Lucas, 30, was accused of assaulting
Valdes on July 16, the day before the inmate died. Lucas, an instructor at the
guards' training academy, is free on $50,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
	   The other guards suspended were Sgt. Andrew W. Lewis, Officer Dewey Beck,
Officer Donald Stanford and Officer Raymon C. Hanson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
