<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Ask For 2-Year Budget  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM ABRAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. David Dreier says the ``stars are beginning to
align'' this year for adoption of legislation that would end the annual budget
crunch and put Congress on a two-year budget cycle.
</P>
<P>
	   Dreier, R-Calif., was joined Wednesday by Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.,
chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, and Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn.,
chairman of the Governmental Affairs Committee, in urging action this year on a
biennial budget.
</P>
<P>
	   Supporters of the biennial budget, which would give Congress more time to
oversee the spending bills it passes, have for years failed to overcome the
resistance of appropriations committee members and others reluctant to give up
their annual shot at influencing government spending.
</P>
<P>
	   But last fall, Dreier, who heads the House Rules Committee, got 245
signatures, more than a majority, on a non-binding resolution saying the House
should take up the issue this year. President Clinton supports the concept and
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., on Tuesday said he was ``very much
for biennial budgeting'' and thought it could be acted on this year.
</P>
<P>
	   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas., has also said he likes the idea
but has doubts about legislation moving in this second year of the congressional
session.
</P>
<P>
	   Several bills introduced in the House and Senate would follow the example of
some 20 states by having Congress pass a budget the first year of the session
and devote the second year to oversight of spending programs.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Congress spends more than half of its time each year voting on the
government's annual budget,'' Domenici said. ``Biennial budgeting would be a
dramatic improvement in the way Congress does business.''
</P>
<P>
	   As an example of the inefficiencies of the current system, he noted that the
Army Corps of Engineers produced eight volumes, 2,000 pages, as part of its $3.7
billion budget proposal for 2000. He said in many cases 90 percent of the budget
requests are unchanged from previous years.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Joe Lieberman of Connecticut, the ranking Democrat on the Governmental
Affairs Committee, said the biennial budget would alleviate ``the gridlock so
often caused by our annual confrontations over budget and appropriations.''
</P>
<P>
	   Critics of the two-year budget, in addition to warning that it would weaken
congressional controls over the process, argue the biennial budget lacks the
flexibility to cope with sudden economic changes, wars or disasters. Supporters
counter that supplemental budgets can be passed to handle emergencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0219 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
