<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf War Illness Questions Remain  </HEADLINE>
   By JANELLE CARTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A lack of coordination among government agencies has
contributed to lingering questions about Gulf War illnesses nine years after the
war, a federal investigator told Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   ``While federally sponsored studies have resulted in some descriptive
information concerning veterans symptoms, many basic questions remain,''
Kwai-Cheung Chan of the General Accounting Office, Congress' investigative arm,
told a House government reform subcommittee Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   For instance, Chan said, a Research Working Group created to focus on
research planning, review and dissemination, ``has not endorsed any case
definition or set of such definitions that might focus federal research.''
</P>
<P>
	   Chan's comments came during a hearing to examine $121 million of federal
research and investigation in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The findings ``validate our initial assessment, and confirm our worst fears
about the pace and prospects of the search for answers for sick Gulf War
veterans,'' said Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We still don't know how many veterans are suffering unexplained illnesses.
We still don't know how their illnesses progress and we still don't know if they
are getting any better,'' Shays said.
</P>
<P>
	   Various government officials, including the Veterans' Affairs and Defense
Departments, testified about their efforts, saying studies were underway to
learn more about the illnesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Up to 30,000 veterans of the war have complained of mysterious maladies such
as fatigue, joint pain and memory loss they claim are related to their service
in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These remaining questions do not reflect scientific indifference; instead
they reflect the complexity of assessing and predicting the health impact of
military deployments,'' said Dr. Drue H. Barrett, who serves as the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention liaison to the Health and Human Services
Department on Gulf War issues.
</P>
<P>
	   But Chan identified several problems.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Most of the sponsored studies are ongoing or in review,'' Chan said. Of 20
reports due to the Office of the Special Assistant for Gulf War Illnesses, only
six had been publicly released at the time of the investigation. Fourteen had
been in draft or review status for a year or longer.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, the various agencies involved have had trouble coordinating, Chan
said, adding that contracting errors caused the improper awarding of $20 million
worth of task orders.
</P>
<P>
	   Shays said officials are mindful of the time research requires, but
``patience is no excuse for a lack of vigilance.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We must be certain all federal research into Gulf War illnesses is well
designed, vigorously pursued and keenly focused on the most promising
hypotheses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0222 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Skips Calif. GOP Convention  </HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT LINDLAW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- When California Republicans meet this weekend to
size up presidential candidates, there will be a very conspicuous absence: Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, who is skipping the gathering for the third straight time.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush will be in Michigan when the convention opens Friday, and will spend
most of the weekend resting in Texas after an 18-day sprint through Iowa and New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   But while Bush's brother, Jeb, the Florida governor, plans to speak on his
behalf, Sen. John McCain will speak for himself in hope of generating momentum
in the nation's largest state after his decisive win over Bush in the New
Hampshire GOP presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
	   Jon Fleischman, executive director of the state GOP, said he didn't take the
Texas governor's absence as a snub.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If nobody was speaking at our convention representing George W. Bush, the
silence would be deafening,'' Fleischman said. ``The fact that we have his
brother there is huge.''
</P>
<P>
	   But by missing the convention, Bush risks alienating the more than 1,500 GOP
activists on hand, said Barbara O'Connor, director of the Institute for the
Study of Politics and the Media at California State University, Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Were I him, I'd be at the California Republican convention shaking
hands,'' she said. ``Snubbed once, they'll forgive you; twice, maybe they'll
forgive you; three times, they're going to dance with someone else.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, R-Ariz., will mix with the party faithful and give a speech, as will
Steve Forbes. Alan Keyes also plans to attend; Gary Bauer declined an
invitation.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker did not return two telephone calls Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The California Republican Party holds conventions twice annually. A year
ago, Bush passed on the gathering, saying he would make no public appearances
outside Texas until lawmakers there finished considering his education plan. (He
attended nine California fund-raisers in the year leading up to the convention.)
</P>
<P>
	   In his absence, McCain stole the show with a speech imploring Republicans to
take the high road in the upcoming campaign, and gaining exposure in the news
media.
</P>
<P>
	   When the state GOP held its fall convention, Bush again took a pass, instead
attending the Ryder Cup golf tournament and a Hispanic gathering.
</P>
<P>
	   Keyes accused the Texas governor of ``cowering in the bushes'' by skipping
the September convention, but bypassing the meetings has caused Bush little if
any damage.
</P>
<P>
	   In three January polls, he led McCain among California Republicans by
margins ranging from 33 to 45 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
	   Each survey was conducted before the Arizona senator's smashing victory over
Bush in New Hampshire on Tuesday -- a win some political analysts say could
change the race here.
</P>
<P>
	   The senator has long said California will be one of four crucial states,
along with New Hampshire, South Carolina and his home state. Bush, too, has said
he will compete aggressively here. He last visited Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
	   The California Republican Party convention will showcase McCain, Forbes and
Keyes before California's most committed GOP activists, many of whom find Bush
too moderate and may be shopping for another candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   GOP and Bush campaign officials say there is no bad blood between them, and
note that Bush helped the state party raise nearly $2 million at a fund-raiser
last fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Relations have been rocky in the last year, however.
</P>
<P>
	   The party, which is dominated by conservatives, delivered a slap to Bush
last June when it voted to change the GOP presidential primary from
``winner-take-all'' to a free-for-all system that would award delegates to the
nominating convention to multiple candidates. The move was later blocked in the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, California Republican Party conventions are perennial
battlegrounds for abortion fights, which Bush has resisted being drawn into.
Bush says he opposes abortion, but would allow it for cases of rape, incest or
when the mother's life is at risk.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue is certain to surface Sunday when the party votes on a platform,
said Bob Larkin, a party activist advocating removal of anti-abortion language.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush campaign leaders in California are seeking to stifle such a battle to
``make sure the convention headlines are nonacrimonious,'' said a state GOP
leader who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's a dynamic at play from the Bush campaign where they don't want to
see controversy at the convention, they don't want to see abortion stuff in the
papers,'' the leader said. ``They're putting a lot of pressure on the Larkins of
the world to sit down and shut up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0225 </TRAILER>
