<HEADLINE> Japan Co. To Have License Repealed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- The government said Thursday it has decided to repeal the
operating license of the company that caused Japan's worst nuclear accident.
</P>
<P>
	   JCO Co. will have an opportunity to appeal the decision at a hearing on
March 13, said Shigeaki Shiraishi, deputy director of nuclear safety at the
Science and Technology Agency.
</P>
<P>
	   After the hearing, the Ministry of International Trade and Industry will
issue a final decision on whether to bar the nuclear fuel processor from
business, said Shiraishi. But he added it was too early to say when that will
happen.
</P>
<P>
	   "We want to carry out this disciplinary measure as quickly and smoothly as
possible," said Shiraishi. "We don't expect the company to put up a fight."
</P>
<P>
	   JCO plans to obey the government decision, said company spokesman Shuji
Noguchi.
</P>
<P>
	   The Sept. 30 accident occurred when two workers mixed too much uranium with
nitric acid to make fuel, triggering the reaction.
</P>
<P>
	   The amount of uranium used, 37 pounds, was almost seven times the approved
limit, said Shiraishi. The company has suspended operations since the accident,
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hisashi Ouchi, one of the workers, died in December, becoming the first
fatality from an accident at a Japanese nuclear facility.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, the government increased its estimate of the number of people
exposed in the accident to 439, far more than the previous figure of 90.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
