<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wide Gaps Divide Barak, Arafat  </HEADLINE>
   By SARI BASHI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Only 10 days before a crucial deadline in peace talks, a
senior Israeli official said today the gap between Palestinian and Israeli
positions was still so wide that a Camp David-style summit was not realistic at
this point.
</P>
<P>
	   Cabinet Minister Haim Ramon spoke just hours before Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat were slated to meet to try to
find a way to iron out the differences in the last phase of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
	   The two leaders have committed to produce a framework agreement for a final
peace treaty by Feb. 13, but officials from both sides said the chances of
reaching understandings by then were remote.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a formidable task,'' U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross said after
meeting separately with Barak and Arafat until the early hours today to try to
bridge the gaps.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States has said that once sides made significant progress, it
would invite the leaders to Washington for an intensive negotiating session
under President Clinton's close supervision.
</P>
<P>
	   Similar negotiations at Camp David in 1978 lead to the breakthrough peace
treaty between Israel and Egypt. But Ramon said such a session was not realistic
at this time.
</P>
<P>
	   ``With the current situation, going to a summit in the United States when
the gaps are still so wide is not the correct thing to do,'' Ramon told Israel
radio.
</P>
<P>
	   The framework deal is to address the thorniest issues between Israel and the
Palestinians -- final borders, the fate of Palestinian refugees and the future
of Jerusalem, which is claimed by both sides as their capital.
</P>
<P>
	   The first four of 10 days of marathon discussions aimed at hammering out a
framework agreement yielded little progress. Arafat aide Tayeb Abdel Rahim on
Wednesday dismissed Israel's proposal for a final border as ``nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Palestinians were unlikely to be much happier with Israel's map for an
overdue troop withdrawal from 6.1 percent of the West Bank, which Barak's
Cabinet approved Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   In today's summit, Barak and Arafat are also expected to discuss the latest
withdrawal, originally set for Jan. 20 and now slated for next week, and the
opening of a travel route for Palestinians between the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
	   The withdrawal outlined does not include the Jerusalem suburbs that the
Palestinians are demanding, Israeli settlers who were shown the map Wednesday
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the land to be given back is in the sparsely populated southern West
Bank, near Hebron, said settler spokesman Yehoshua Mor-Yosef. Smaller swaths of
land near the West Bank town of Jenin and near the Gush Etzion settlement bloc
were also included, he said, accusing Barak of isolating settlements.
</P>
<P>
	   The Palestinians have flatly rejected Israel's proposal for a final border
because it would leave Israel with territory captured in the 1967 Mideast War.
They have not budged from their opening position demanding that Israel withdraw
from all of the West Bank, Gaza Strip and east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
	   One potential obstacle in negotiations was lifted Wednesday when the PLO's
policy-making Central Council recessed with Chairman Salim Zanoun saying the
body would postpone a vote on whether to unilaterally declare a state.
</P>
<P>
	   Barak is not opposed to a Palestinian state, but wants it to be created
through negotiations. Both sides have promised not to prejudice the outcome of
the negotiations before a September deadline for a final peace treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0229 </TRAILER>
