<DOCNO> APW20000203.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stock Prices Close Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks extended gains Thursday amid hopes that new
investment trust funds will draw more investors into the market. The U.S. dollar
fell against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average finished up 207.51 points, or
1.06 percent, at 19,786.42. On Wednesday, the average closed up 155.53 points,
or 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the U.S. dollar was trading at 108.18
yen at 3 p.m. (0600 GMT), down 0.32 yen from its level of 108.50 yen late
Wednesday and below 108.26 yen overnight in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan's benchmark stock index rose for a second day, buoyed by hopes for
several large-scale investment trusts set to be launched over the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   The funds, many of which are targeting shares in technology companies, are
expected to encourage more individual investors to come into the market.
</P>
<P>
	   But some traders cautioned that the Nikkei's rise was based largely on
market sentiment rather than economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
	   "For now, the market is supported merely by investor hopes for good demand
for investment trust funds," said Hidenori Karaki, general manager at Tokyo
Mitsubishi Personal Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   Nomura Asset Management, a subsidiary of Japan's biggest brokerage house,
raised about 800 billion yen (dlrs 7.4 billion) on Wednesday, the launch day for
its "Big Project-N" fund. The fund has a 1 trillion yen (dlrs 9.26 billion)
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
	   Brokerage shares in general finished higher.
</P>
<P>
	   Overnight in New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 37.85 points,
or 0.3 percent, to close at 11,003.20.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-rich Nasdaq Composite Index rose 21.98 points, or 0.54
percent, to finish at 4,073.96.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all first-section companies was up
17.62 points, or 1.02 percent, at 1,729.48. On Wednesday, the index rose 14.71
points, or 0.87 percent, to 1,711.86.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency markets, traders sold the greenback to take profits after buying
up dollars on anticipation of interest rate hikes by the U.S. Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
	   Speculation of an increase was confirmed Wednesday when the Fed announced it
had decided to raise key rates. Investors then decided to cash in on their
dollar holdings.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders said, however, the outlook for the U.S. currency remained strong,
since the increase in interest rates makes the dollar more attractive to
Japanese investors because it leads to a higher yield on dollar-denominated
assets.
</P>
<P>
	   Japanese government officials repeated their concerns about an excessively
strong yen.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice Finance Minister for International Affairs Haruhiko Kuroda told
reporters Thursday morning that the ministry's foreign exchange stance remained
opposed to a higher-valued yen.
</P>
<P>
	   An excessively strong yen hurts export-based Japanese companies, as it
decreases their profitability when dollar earnings are repatriated back into
Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro traded at 105.30 yen, above its level of
104.77 yen yen late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.8450
from its close at 1.8350 Wednesday. Its price fell 0.09 point to 98.68.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
