<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: No English on Malay TV  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- In an effort to keep the national language
pure, Malaysia's state-run television and radio will no longer allow programs
that mix English or other foreign words with Malay, news reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Deputy Information Minister Khalid Yunus said a committee had been set up at
the government-owned Radio-Television Malaysia to scrutinize all scripts to
ensure producers were minding the language rule.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are firm in the usage of proper Bahasa Malaysia,'' or the Malay
language, Khalid was quoted as saying in The Star newspaper. He said that the
rule, which was in effect before but never enforced, was part of an effort to
protect the national language from being polluted and tarnished.
</P>
<P>
	   Spoken Malay is often a mixture of the languages used by the country's
different ethnic groups. Bind together the multilingual nation, it is a modern
language scripted in English and Arabic, and many words have their roots in
Persian, Arabic, English and Sanskrit.
</P>
<P>
	   In the nation of 22 million ethnic Malays, Chinese and Indians, English is
also widely spoken as a vestige of its former colonial rulers. But it is often
unrecognizable because of the local slangs attached to almost every sentence.
</P>
<P>
	   Khalid added that even Cabinet ministers speaking on news shows would have
to comply with the rule. Exemptions would be made only where no Malay words
existed, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 0245 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
