<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 03:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Feb. 3, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Wide Gaps Divide Barak, Arafat
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Only 10 days before a crucial deadline in peace talks, a
senior Israeli official said today the gap between Palestinian and Israeli
positions was still so wide that a Camp David-style summit was not realistic at
this point. Cabinet Minister Haim Ramon spoke just hours before Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat were slated to meet to
try to find a way to iron out the differences in the last phase of the peace
process. The two leaders have committed to produce a framework agreement for a
final peace treaty by Feb. 13, but officials from both sides said the chances of
reaching understandings by then were remote.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Co. To Have License Repealed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The government said Thursday it has decided to repeal the
operating license of the company that caused Japan's worst nuclear accident. JCO
Co. will have an opportunity to appeal the decision at a hearing on March 13,
said Shigeaki Shiraishi, deputy director of nuclear safety at the Science and
Technology Agency. After the hearing, the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry will issue a final decision on whether to bar the nuclear fuel
processor from business, said Shiraishi. But he added it was too early to say
when that will happen.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Witnesses Describe Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PORT HUENEME, Calif. (AP) -- Moments before it crashed, Alaska Airlines
Flight 261 started "tumbling, spinning, nose-down" as it hurtled toward the
Pacific Ocean, a federal investigator said Wednesday. The MD-83 jetliner was in
one piece and there were no signs of fire or smoke when it hit the water,
killing all 88 people aboard, witnesses told investigators with the National
Transportation Safety Board. As it passed over Anacapa Island, just off the
Southern California coast, a witness heard several popping sounds, watched the
plane turn, then plunge into the Santa Barbara Channel, NTSB member John
Hammerschmidt said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Austria Govt. Decision Near
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Austria's president has made it unmistakably clear
he doesn't want to approve a new government including Joerg Haider's far-right
anti-immigrant party. But he admits he has little choice. President Thomas
Klestil is expected to confirm the coalition Thursday, despite a growing wave of
threats and protests from abroad against a government with Haider's Freedom
party. In an attempt to spare Austria international isolation, Klestil has
requested Haider and Wolfgang Schuessel, head of the conservative People's Party
and the likely new chancellor, sign a "declaration of values of European
democracy."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Eight Convicted in Argentina Murder
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A tribunal sentenced eight people to life in
prison Wednesday in the death of a crusading journalist, ending a case that
shocked Argentines and drew international outrage. A three-judge panel found
three former provincial police officers, a former security guard and four
civilians guilty of killing Jose Luis Cabezas, an investigative photojournalist.
A fourth police officer was sentenced to four years on a fraud charge related to
the case.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Seeks Anti-Pollution Funds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will propose a major increase in
federal spending to combat global warming and pollution, along with new tax
incentives to encourage business to invest in environmentally friendly
technology, White House officials said Wednesday. In his upcoming budget
request, Clinton will ask Congress for $2.4 billion for various initiatives
designed to reduce the harmful effect of global climate change, said Roger
Ballantine, White House environmental adviser. The mount is more than 40 percent
above what Congress approved last year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Small Babies May Earn Less Later
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) -- Babies born smaller than normal tend to have lower incomes
as adults but are just as likely as those of normal birth weight to be employed,
married and satisfied with their lives, researchers say. A study in Wednesday's
Journal of the American Medical Association linked the lower incomes to lower
achievement in school, which led to lower-paying, blue-collar jobs. Previous
studies have linked low birth weight to problems with brain development in
children.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stock Prices Close Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei gained 207.51 points to close at 19,786.42.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Heat 105, Celtics 103
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BOSTON (AP) -- Alonzo Mourning made a hook shot from the lane with 15.7
seconds left on Wednesday night to give the Miami Heat a 105-103 victory over
the Boston Celtics. Mourning and Jamal Mashburn each had 23 points for Miami,
which snapped a season-high three-game road losing streak. Antoine Walker scored
35, but he missed a 3-pointer in the final seconds that would have won the game
for Boston.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
