<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mostly Higher; Dow Up 38.79  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks are mostly higher this morning as an optimistic
profit forecast from Amazon.com and a rally in the bond market have prompted a
wave of buying.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 38.79 at 11,041.99.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 7.97 at 1,417.09, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 82.11 at
4,156.07.
</P>
<P>
	   Online retailer Amazon.com led the Nasdaq, rising 9 7/16 from its 4 p.m.
close to 78 7/8. The company said late Wednesday that while it posted its worst
losses ever during the fourth quarter of 1999, sales more than doubled.
Investors today were also enticed by the company's claim that losses will narrow
significantly by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks also benefited from a continued rally in the bond market. Long-term
Treasury prices, which have been edging higher for more than a week, soared on
Wednesday after the government said it would sell fewer bonds as part of the
Clinton administration's long-term plan to pay off the national debt.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond stood at 6.13 percent, down
from 6.28 percent late Wednesday. As recently as Jan. 18, the yield on the
long-term bond was at a 2 1/2-year high of 6.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields move in the opposite direction of prices. Rising bond yields are
generally bad for stocks, because more lucrative returns on bonds can present
investors with an appealing alternative to stock investing.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said the market also drew some support from the Federal Reserve's
widely anticipated decision Wednesday to raise interest rates by a
quarter-point, its fourth hike since June.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-4 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 145.10 million shares, well ahead of
Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.94 to 515.83.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.1 percent. In afternoon
trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.8 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down
0.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 2.7 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1026 </TRAILER>
