<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 65.77; Nasdaq Up 57.01  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks were mostly higher today as an optimistic
profit forecast from Amazon.com prompted a wave of buying, but blue-chip shares
lost early momentum and turned lower.
</P>
<P>
	   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was down
65.77 at 10,937.43.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators fared better. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
slipped 0.66 to 1,408.46, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 57.01 at
4,130.97.
</P>
<P>
	   Online retailer Amazon.com led the Nasdaq, rising 11 9/64 from its 4 p.m.
close to 80 37/64. The company said late Wednesday that while it posted its
worst losses ever during the fourth quarter of 1999, sales more than doubled.
Investors today were also enticed by the company's claim that losses will narrow
significantly by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Other large-capitalization technology stocks also advanced. Cisco Systems
rose 1 11/16 to 115 9/16 and Intel rose 2 1/16 to 102 1/8.
</P>
<P>
	   "The action and performance is still being placed on the shoulders of the
heavily indexed stocks," said Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at
George K. Baum &AMP; Co. Those companies -- the market's best performers in 1999 --
are now so widely held and so coveted that investors see them as the safest bets
for 2000 as well.
</P>
<P>
	   Weakness in old-fashioned industrials derailed the Dow. Alcoa fell 2 3/8 to
72 3/16 and Exxon Mobil fell 3 5/16 to 80 1/2.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks also benefited from a continued rally in the bond market. Long-term
Treasury prices, which have been edging higher for more than a week, soared on
Wednesday after the government said it would sell fewer bonds as part of the
Clinton administration's long-term plan to pay off the national debt.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond stood at 6.13 percent, down
from 6.28 percent late Wednesday. As recently as Jan. 18, the yield on the
long-term bond was at a 2 1/2-year high of 6.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields move in the opposite direction of prices. Rising bond yields are
generally bad for stocks, because more lucrative returns on bonds can present
investors with an appealing alternative to stock investing.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said the market also drew some support from the Federal Reserve's
widely anticipated decision Wednesday to raise interest rates by a
quarter-point, its fourth hike since June.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan won Senate confirmation today
for a fourth term as head of the nation's central bank. Greenspan was praised as
a key architect of the current 107-month long economic expansion, the longest in
history.
</P>
<P>
	   On the New York Stock Exchange, advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an
8-to-5 margin. NYSE volume came to 491.49 million shares, well ahead of
Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 7.05 to 516.94.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1224 </TRAILER>
