<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading heavily
today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said it expects to report fourth-quarter earnings of 50 cents to
51 cents per share, below analysts' estimates of 57 cents a share. Ann Taylor
said it used aggressive price cuts to sell off its fall and holiday inventory,
which cut into profits.
</P>
<P>
	   Mannesmann AG officials were meeting today to reassess a buyout bid by
Vodafone. Several news reports said the two giant wireless companies have
reached a friendly resolution to Vodafone's hostile takeover effort.
</P>
<P>
	   Sprint affiliate Alamosa PCS made its initial public offering Thursday.
Alamosa is the personal communication services affiliate for Sprint in the
southwestern and midwestern United States. Analysts said Alamosa's relationship
with Sprint drew attention to the IPO.
</P>
<P>
	   The company earned 34 cents per share in its fiscal second quarter, up from
28 cents per share in the second quarter of 1998. ResMed makes medical equipment
for the diagnosis and treatment of sleep-disordered breathing.
</P>
<P>
	   The company posted its worst losses ever, losing $185 million, or 55 cents a
share, for the quarter ended Dec. 31. But Amazon.com executives pleased Wall
Street analysts by saying that losses should narrow significantly by year's end.
</P>
<P>
	   AT&AMP;T Wireless has agreed to take a major stake in Metrocall, a paging and
wireless company. Three other companies -- investment firm Hicks Muse Tate &AMP;
Furst Inc., PSINet Inc. and an unnamed technology company -- will make
investments that will bring Metrocall about $51 million in new capital.
</P>
<P>
	   VA Linux Systems Inc. plans to acquire Andover.Net for about $1.04 billion.
Andover.Net runs Web sites that provide software and information on Linux
technology. VA Linux makes software and computers based on Linux, an operating
system that is seen as a potential rival to Microsoft's dominant system.
</P>
</TEXT>
