<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PBS Takes Tour of Maine Town  </HEADLINE>
    By FRAZIER MOORE AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- In tiny Belfast, Maine, they check their lobster traps at
the crack of dawn. They press trousers at the laundry. They make doughnuts and
take ballet.
</P>
<P>
	   They study "Moby Dick" in school. They go to church. They plead guilty in
court to stealing firewood.
</P>
<P>
	   And on it goes. In his wondrous new documentary, "Belfast, Maine," Frederick
Wiseman takes us on a private tour of this coastal community for four keenly
observed hours. A presentation of Thirteen/WNET, it premieres on PBS Friday at 9
p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
	   In Wiseman's film, we see a social worker picking nits out of a woman's hair
while the woman bounces a baby in her lap. We see men talk logging over their
breakfast at Goose River Groceries. We see a rehearsal for a local production of
"Death of a Salesman." We see an infant christened.
</P>
<P>
	   What do we learn? Wiseman makes no grand pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've tried to capture some aspects -- although obviously not all, you'd
never get it all -- of what constitutes daily life in Belfast," he says. "And
that's it."
</P>
<P>
	   He even downplays the idea that his film might shed light on other small
towns. "I don't know," he declares. "I haven't made a survey."
</P>
<P>
	   "Belfast, Maine" is Wiseman's 30th documentary, his 30th look at social
institutions in a career that has produced such films as "High School,"
"Welfare," "Hospital," "Basic Training" and his first, "Titicut Follies," which
in 1967 brought viewers into the State Prison for the Criminally Insane at
Bridgewater, Mass.
</P>
<P>
	   For his labors, Wiseman has received three Emmy awards and a Peabody, as
well as a MacArthur Foundation Fellowship. A retrospective of all 30 films is
under way this month at the Lincoln Center Film Society, which has brought him
from his home in Cambridge, Mass., to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
	   The subject of "Belfast, Maine," he tells a reporter during his visit, "is
normal behavior, different aspects of contemporary life. Frequently, that's very
complicated. I try to include in the film reflections of the complexity I
observe."
</P>
<P>
	   Maybe that's why Wiseman spent eight weeks among the 6,474 residents of
Belfast in the fall of 1996, and shot a copious 110 hours of film. Maybe that's
why it took him 14 months at the editing table to shape that raw footage into
episodes of real life, unfolding as if in real time.
</P>
<P>
	   And maybe that's why he resists the simple answers, the easy conclusions.
That just wouldn't be his style.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't like to make didactic films," he says. "I don't want to fall victim
to ideological blinders, so that I'm only seeing one thing."
</P>
<P>
	   A soft-voiced man with soulful eyes and a mouth that curls into a
mischievous smile, Wiseman has the heedful detachment of a psychotherapist,
gently turning a question back on itself to find the truth.
</P>
<P>
	   Consider the sequence at the tin-roofed factory that churns out baked
stuffed potatoes. This eight-minute interlude begins with a fork-lift truck
hefting great sacks of spuds, and concludes with the grocery-ready product being
packed into boxes.
</P>
<P>
	   In between, some 70 shots add up to what might seem a steamy, clanging
purgatory. Or might not -- particularly to these Penobscot Frozen Foods
wage-earners, whose county suffers Maine's highest unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
	   So which is it? What is Wiseman trying to say with the scene? What was he
thinking when he shot it?
</P>
<P>
	   "This may seem like I'm giving you an evasive answer," he admits. "But what
I think is what you see in the movie. My point of view is expressed --
indirectly and obliquely -- by the way I edit individual sequences, and by the
way I link them together.
</P>
<P>
	   "The film is my report on what I found."
</P>
<P>
	   With his cameraman John Davey, director-soundman Wiseman found a group of
seniors in a flower-arranging class. He found a man who traps, puts down and
skins a coyote.
</P>
<P>
	   He found prison inmates getting instruction about HIV: "If it's warm,
slippery and not yours -- don't touch it," they're advised.
</P>
<P>
	   "My technique, when it works, places viewers in the middle of the events,"
says Wiseman, "and asks them to think through their own relationships with what
they're seeing and hearing."
</P>
<P>
	   At the Belfast Coin Laundry, we see and hear a washer leaking sudsy water
onto the floor. A woman kicks the washer, then kicks it again.
</P>
<P>
	   "Weird," she murmurs, passing judgment in a way that Wiseman's films never
would.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
	   'CEO EXCHANGE': CNN political analyst Jeff Greenfield takes a break from the
presidential race to moderate "CEO Exchange," a new series of monthly specials
for PBS. Premiering this weekend (check local listings), the program takes
advantage of the CEO-as-celebrity phenomenon, putting two corporate leaders
before an audience of business school students and letting viewers get up close
and personal with these business titans. Asked how he feels about his new beat,
Greenfield said, "I hope over 25 years, I've learned that just because you don't
know the answer doesn't mean you can't ask good questions." First up: Netscape's
Jim Clark and Excite@Home's Tom Jermoluk, on the topic, "Creating the CEO for
the 21st Century."
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore@ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1303 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
