<DOCNO> APW20000203.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capitol Police Investigate Liquid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A section of the Capitol was closed for two hours Thursday
after a woman was seen pouring an unidentified liquid down a grate, a Capitol
Police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Dan Nichols said the building was reopened after police confirmed that
no hazardous materials were released.
</P>
<P>
	   Nichols said a police response team was called in after a building employee
reported that a woman had poured a vial of liquid down an ornamental grate just
off the center of the building on the first floor. He said the woman left the
scene and her whereabouts were not known. The nature of the liquid was not
known.
</P>
<P>
	   Nichols said Capitol Police had strengthened its biological-chemical
response capability after the sarin attack in a Tokyo subway in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1350 </TRAILER>
