the Navy's 5th Fleet, based in Bahrain, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   State Department spokesman James Foley said U.S. officials have been in
regular contact with Russian authorities for almost a month about the activities
of Russian vessels in the gulf.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russians have said the detained ship was was privately owned and that an
investigation is under way, the spokesman said. He said the last time a Russian
vessel was boarded because of suspected smuggling activities occurred in August
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Foley added that illicit oil exports via the Persian Gulf averaged about
50,000 barrels a day for much of 1998 but increased sharply last fall and now
average about 100,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
	   The Navy said the Russian vessel was boarded for inspection in accordance
with ``standard operating procedure as a result of its last port of call and
failure to respond to routine inquiries regarding its intentions.''
</P>
<P>
	   The captain of the tanker has been cooperating, and if the oil is found to
