<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 122.53; Dow Up 24.82  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks were sharply higher today as an
optimistic earnings forecast from Amazon.com and a continuing rally in the bond
market prompted a wave of buying.
</P>
<P>
	   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Nasdaq
composite index was up 122.53 at 4,196.49.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 24.82 at 11,028.02, and the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 13.36 at 1,422.48.
</P>
<P>
	   Online retailer Amazon.com led the Nasdaq, rising 15 5/16 from its 4 p.m.
close to 84 3/4. The company said late Wednesday that while it posted its worst
losses ever during the fourth quarter of 1999, sales more than doubled.
Investors today were also enticed by the company's claim that losses will narrow
significantly by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Henry Blodget, Merrill Lynch's influential Internet analyst, raised his
near-term rating on the stock from "accumulate" to "buy."
</P>
<P>
	   Other large-capitalization technology stocks also advanced. Cisco Systems
rose 4 to 117 7/8 and Intel rose 3 3/4 to 103 13/16, leading a wave of strong
gains by semiconductor makers. Texas Instruments gained 10 1/4 to 129 5/8.
</P>
<P>
	   "The action and performance is still being placed on the shoulders of the
heavily indexed stocks," said Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at
George K. Baum &AMP; Co. Those companies -- the market's best performers in 1999 --
are now so widely held and so coveted that investors see them as the safest bets
for 2000 as well.
</P>
<P>
	   Weakness in old-fashioned industrials derailed the Dow. Alcoa fell 2 9/16 to
72 and Exxon Mobil fell 2 13/16 to 81.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks were benefiting from a continued rally in the bond market. Long-term
Treasury prices, which have been edging higher for more than a week, soared on
Wednesday after the government said it would sell fewer bonds as part of the
Clinton administration's long-term plan to pay off the national debt.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond stood at 6.16 percent, down
from 6.28 percent late Wednesday. As recently as Jan. 18, the yield on the
long-term bond was at a 2 1/2-year high of 6.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields move in the opposite direction of prices. Rising bond yields are
generally bad for stocks, because more lucrative returns on bonds can present
investors with an appealing alternative to stock investing.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said the market also drew some support from the Federal Reserve's
widely anticipated decision Wednesday to raise interest rates by a
quarter-point, its fourth hike since June. Today, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan won Senate confirmation for a fourth term as head of the nation's
central bank.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks were pressured at midday by rumors that the Federal Reserve bank of
New York had called an emergency meeting to discuss market volatility. The
Nasdaq pared much of its early gain, and the Dow fell as much as 160 points.
</P>
<P>
	   After a spokesman for the bank denied the rumors, stocks recovered.
</P>
<P>
	   On the New York Stock Exchange, advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an
8-to-5 margin. NYSE volume came to 893.35 million shares, well ahead of
Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 9.37 to 519.26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1526 </TRAILER>
