<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Electing New Beauty Queen  </HEADLINE>
   By BART JONES Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela, arguably the beauty queen capital of
the world, has decided to hold a special national pageant to solve a dilemma:
Its regular beauty queen was in such demand this year that she caused confusion
in international pageant regulations.
</P>
<P>
	   To fix the problem, organizers are putting together a last-minute pageant to
pick a representative to send to the Miss Universe contest in May. The new queen
will be selected Feb. 26 and will be crowned Miss Bolivarian Republic of
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
	   Venezuela usually has one major national pageant. The runner-up goes to the
Miss World contest and the winner represents her nation in the Miss Universe
contest.
</P>
<P>
	   But last year, Miss World officials insisted that Venezuela send its winner
to them, too. It did, and the Venezuelan contestant, 24-year-old Martina
Thorogood, was named first runner-up in the contest in London in December.
</P>
<P>
	   Thorogood was also to have competed in the Miss Universe pageant in Cyprus.
But Miss Universe officials objected, saying Thorogood wasn't eligible because
she can't be both Miss Universe and Miss World at the same time. That could
happen if the current Miss World were to abdicate her crown.
</P>
<P>
	   Given Venezuela's record in past beauty contests, preparing for a Venezuelan
victory in any pageant is smart thinking. Venezuela has won 11 top international
beauty titles in the last two decades, more than any other nation.
</P>
<P>
	   Organizers are handpicking about 15 outstanding former Miss Venezuela
contestants to compete for Miss Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
	   From now on, pageant organizer Osmel Sousa said, Venezuela will hold two
beauty pageants every year -- a Miss Universe Venezuela and a Miss World
Venezuela. Many other nations also hold two contests.
</P>
<P>
	   Sousa said the new pageant's name coincides with Venezuela's new name,
pushed through by President Hugo Chavez, a former military coup leader whose
idol is 19th century independence hero Simon Bolivar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1528 </TRAILER>
