<HEADLINE> Fox Reaches Agreement on Ethnicity  </HEADLINE>
    By LYNN ELBER AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Fox announced an agreement with civil rights groups
Thursday to promote ethnic diversity in its TV shows and inside the company.
Among other things, it will hire a vice president of diversity.
</P>
<P>
	   CBS was expected to announce its own agreement with groups including the
NAACP later in the day, becoming the last of the four major broadcast networks
to strike a deal.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreement with Fox differs from that reached with NBC and ABC in its
stipulation that an executive be hired to direct Fox's efforts. The network also
agreed to expand minority employee development programs.
</P>
<P>
	   Fox will also consider racial diversity as a "highly significant factor"
when the next opening comes up on the Fox Entertainment Group board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
	   "We feel it's enormously important, it's very good for business, and most of
all it's the right thing to do," said Fox Entertainment President Doug Herzog.
</P>
<P>
	   Fox's lineup includes such programs as "The Simpsons," "Ally McBeal," "The
X-Files" and "Malcolm in the Middle."
</P>
<P>
	   The networks opened negotiations with the coalition after the NAACP last
summer floated the threat of a TV boycott because of the lack of minority actors
on the fall 1999 schedule of new shows.
</P>
<P>
	   As with the other network agreements, Fox's focuses on making changes in
minority representation throughout the company with the expectation that will
affect what viewers see on the air.
</P>
<P>
	   "This agreement we're about to sign represents change. Real, meaningful,
lasting change," said Kweisi Mfume, president of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
	   The end result, Mfume said, should be television that the public can feel
good about and new opportunities in the entertainment industry for minorities.
</P>
<P>
	   Also attending the news conference were representatives of the National
Latino Media Council, the Asian Pacific American Media Coalition, and American
Indians in Film and Television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
