<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One year later: Life goes on  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The "Donny and Marie" show drones on at the nail salon;
Spanish-language soap operas pulsate through the laundromat.
<P>
	   A vigil will be held in the place where Amadou Diallo lived - and where, one
year ago Friday, he died. But in this Bronx neighborhood, called Soundview, the
workaday world goes on.
</P>
<P>
	   Outward appearances refract the horror that erupted in the tiny vestibule,
no bigger than two phone booths, of the two-story brick building where Diallo
lived.
</P>
<P>
	   Some bullet holes remain just below the four mail slots; but most have been
covered with plaster. The outside door lock doesn't work, making it easy for
people to come in and scribble odes to Diallo on the vestibule's yellow walls.
</P>
<P>
	   "It isn't good to stay in a white, racist country too long," wrote one
person. "Rest in peace, Amadou," wrote another.
</P>
<P>
	   The shooting of Diallo, an unarmed, African immigrant, by four white police
officers churned up the bile of suspicion in New Yorkers who feel that people of
color are often unfairly targeted. Police said it was a tragedy that occurred as
they sought to keep all people safe.
</P>
<P>
	   Police officials tried to quell accusations of brutality by meeting with
black leaders to discuss reforms. A committee now oversees diversity training at
the Police Academy.
</P>
<P>
	   For months, residents at 1157 Wheeler Avenue, including Diallo's roommate at
the time of the shooting, were besieged by unwanted attention. They try hard now
to keep to themselves.
</P>
<P>
	   "I am trying to sleep," pleaded the roommate, Abdou Diallo - no relation -
when awakened at noon Wednesday, the day the trial began. "I need to sleep."
</P>
<P>
	   Abdou Diallo told the New York Post recently that he wakes up screaming and
shaking from nightmares.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not easy living with a pain in your heart; it never goes away," said
Abdou Diallo, 25, who comes from the same village in Guinea as Diallo. "Every
day, I wake up screaming and I have headaches."
</P>
<P>
	   He is further reminded of the shooting every time he must pass through the
vestibule.
</P>
<P>
	   The neighborhood is made up of working class people - mostly minorities -
who also keep to themselves. Many have not lived in the area for long.
</P>
<P>
	   On the day of the shooting, most residents interviewed said they had never
met Diallo or heard the barrage of 41 bullets aimed at him. An elevated subway
track runs along the neighborhood's main thoroughfare and trains rumble by at
all hours.
</P>
<P>
	   This week, shops were busy on neighboring Westchester Avenue, and the street
bustling with people. Residents knew the trial had started, but most didn't know
it was on television.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not sure we get Court TV," said Belinda Evans, a hairdresser at
Ashley's Beauty Touch. "A few customers talk about Diallo, but it's mostly
business as usual here."
</P>
<P>
	   Further down the street, none of the TVs at Cam Electronics were tuned into
the trial. But owner Tony Rojas remembers.
</P>
<P>
	   He remembers meeting Diallo two nights before the shooting. "He came in to
buy an iron for his mother," Rojas said. "He was very nice."
</P>
<P>
	   In Diallo's other world, the lower Manhattan street where he sold scarves,
hats, socks and videotapes off a folding table, his fellow vendors had closed up
shop for the winter.
</P>
<P>
	   But a convenience store worker, reading a newspaper story on the trial,
recalled Diallo.
</P>
<P>
	   "He worked hard every day so he could have a better life in America," said
Jose Ramirez, who came to New York from the Dominican Republic six years ago. "I
hope the city will remember him and all the other hard-working immigrants
tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
	   An "Interfaith Service for Healing," featuring Islamic, Christian, Jewish,
Hindu, Buddhist and Native American observances, will be held at 2 p.m. Friday
at Cathedral of St. John the Divine.
</P>
<P>
	   Diallo's relatives and their supporters were planning a vigil for him in
Soundview on Friday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-03-00 1604 </TRAILER>
