<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Placido Domingo: Bridging catastrophe and splendor with music  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - On this night, Placido Domingo co-starred with a
3-year-old girl. And it was a love story.
<P>
	   The tenor and other Metropolitan Opera stars sang for Sophia Forshtay, a
smiling waif of a child suffering from the monstrous "living statue" disease
that freezes the body by turning tissue into bone.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's very important to find a solution quickly. We are here singing for
love," Domingo said at the Waldorf-Astoria benefit Wednesday for research on FOP
- fibrodysplasia ossificans progressiva.
</P>
<P>
	   Sophia's mother, Constance Green, is a member of the Met chorus whose voice
has accompanied Domingo's for decades.
</P>
<P>
	   After the child was diagnosed at 14 months, "Placido asked me, 'What can I
do?"' said the soprano.
</P>
<P>
	   What he did Wednesday was to lead a star-studded cast in "Songs for Sophia"
- a medley of Broadway and opera tunes delivered by some of the world's most
beautiful voices, including Welsh baritone Bryn Terfel and sopranos Federica von
Stade and Heidi Grant Murphy.
</P>
<P>
	   Sophia was stiffly romping around the golden Waldorf ballroom, a smiling,
delicate child in a pink silk gown getting cranky in a crowd, and impishly
telling Domingo as he hummed her a song, "No singing!"
</P>
<P>
	   The evening was an encounter of splendor and catastrophe, linked by those
fighting the incurable disease that affects one out of 2 million people.
</P>
<P>
	   With tickets starting at $500 and individual contributions reaching $25,000,
several hundred guests - including Ivana Trump - contributed about a quarter of
a million dollars for the University of Pennsylvania Medical Center's FOP
research team.
</P>
<P>
	   "With this disease, we know what the bomb looks like, but we don't know what
triggers the bomb. We have to disarm it," said Dr. Fred Kaplan, head of the
university's world-class Division of Metabolic Bone Diseases and Molecular
Orthopedics.
</P>
<P>
	   They are challenging a disease that turns the body's connective tissue to
bone. Kaplan's team is trying to create drugs that would inhibit the
bone-forming protein that produces the wild growths that invade the body inch by
inch.
</P>
<P>
	   Sharks could hold the key to a treatment, says the doctor, who is testing a
new drug made from cells in the sea creature.
</P>
<P>
	   He said that solving the mystery of FOP could lead to progress in treating
more common bone-linked conditions such as osteoporosis, arthritis and
degeneration of the heart valves.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, for Sophia and her mother, it's a daily struggle at home in Fort
Lee, N.J. "The lumps appeared on her head," says Green. "She woke up one morning
not able to move the right arm, and another morning she couldn't move the left
arm, then it was the head."
</P>
<P>
	   Sophia almost died last fall, when the tissue around her neck began
swelling, threatening to strangle her.
</P>
<P>
	   But on Wednesday night, her biggest fear was the massive chandeliers over
her tiny head that she eyed suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
	   During the 90-minute show, as Domingo offered "Yours is my heart alone" from
the operetta "Land of Smiles," Green's eyes gleamed with tears in the light of
hundreds of candles illuminating the ballroom.
</P>
<P>
	   Then Sophia's mother got up and sang, "Grace for the Moment."
</P>
<P>
	   And later, she shared a different kind of hope: "This disease points up how
the spirit is separate from the body. You see an intact human being inside, and
you realize there is something more than just this body."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-03-00 1615 </TRAILER>
