<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Airlines Adding Legroom  </HEADLINE>
    By MICHELLE MITTELSTADT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Even the cheapest seats on American Airlines will offer
passengers several more inches of legroom under a $70 million fleet overhaul
announced Thursday by the air carrier, the first such major airline upgrade
benefiting everyone who flies coach class.
</P>
<P>
	   American, the nation's second-largest airline, will eliminate two rows of
coach-class seats from every plane in its 700-jet fleet to give each coach
passenger 3 to 5 inches more legroom.
</P>
<P>
	   "American is going to be able to provide more room for more coach passengers
than any other airline anywhere," Chairman Don Carty said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
	   Business rivals and Wall Street analysts alike suggested the carrier's move
may put pressure on the rest of the industry to do the same, giving travelers
frustrated by cramped quarters the relief for which they've long clamored.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think the whole industry is going to have to follow suit," said Ray
Neidl, an aviation analyst for ING Barings. "It is a competitive item."
</P>
<P>
	   The head of the Air Travelers Association, a passenger advocacy group,
welcomed American's action as "a very significant development for passengers."
</P>
<P>
	   "We hope that will be a bellwether change that all airlines with follow
through with," said David Stempler, the association's president.
</P>
<P>
	   American plans to remove 7,200 seats from its fleet -- representing 6
percent of its coach capacity -- in an overhaul that began this week. It should
be completed by November for domestic flights and by mid-2001 for international
flights.
</P>
<P>
	   While American said no fare increases will result directly from the move,
some suggested a reduction in airline capacity ultimately may translate into
higher ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
	   "Fares may drift up a little bit," Stempler said. "And that may be the price
you have to pay. We are at historically low pricing in terms of airline fares."
</P>
<P>
	   American's announcement came with an unusual mea culpa from American
executives, who acknowledged the industry has long ignored passengers'
complaints about cramped quarters.
</P>
<P>
	   "To some degree, this is an industry that has lately been in denial," Carty
said. "In an environment where many customers are questioning the value of air
travel, we hope this effort tells loudly and clearly that American listens and
American responds to its customers."
</P>
<P>
	   Carty conceded, however, that American's interest in improving passenger
conditions resulted from congressional interest last year in imposing mandatory
changes on the industry. "We came to the conclusion that we weren't as focused
as we needed to be on our customers," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   American posted the industry's second highest rate of customer complaints
over everything from mishandled bags to flight delays last year, according to
Transportation Department figures issued this week.
</P>
<P>
	   Coach seats will increase from the industry standard of a 31- or 32-inch
seat pitch, which represents the amount of living space, to a minimum 34 inches
and as much as 36 inches depending on the plane model, American said.
</P>
<P>
	   The carrier touted its new legroom campaign by bringing a mockup of a coach
cabin to Washington to show members of Congress and the media what the extra
seat room will look like. The 6-foot-3 Carty's knees were firmly wedged against
the seat back under the current configuration but had a few inches of legroom
with the expanded arrangement.
</P>
<P>
	   Convinced the added legroom will give American a competitive advantage over
its rivals, the airline will roll out a print and TV advertising blitz beginning
Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   American executives said their program goes well beyond rival United
Airlines' announcement of an "economy plus" program last year, which offers
seats with added legroom in the front third of domestic coach cabins to
full-fare passengers and the most frequent fliers.
</P>
<P>
	   But United, the nation's largest airline, accused American of playing
catch-up.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not sure where they were last year when we launched 'economy plus',"
said Graham Atkinson, United's senior vice president for marketing. "We are sort
of somewhat amused in American's spin of events today."
</P>
<P>
	   Atkinson acknowledged that American's move "changes the geography of
competition a little" -- and didn't rule out the possibility that United would
extend legroom throughout its coach cabins.
</P>
<P>
	   "I wouldn't for a minute say we won't look at this, we won't respond,"
Atkinson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
