<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State GOP leaders eye surrender in anti-McCain effort  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Top New York Republican leaders, backing Texas Gov.
George W. Bush's candidacy, appeared ready Thursday to wave the white flag of
surrender in their battle to keep John McCain off the state's presidential
primary ballot.
<P>
	   Keeping the pressure on, McCain sent letters to Gov. George Pataki and state
GOP Chairman William Powers calling for them to "do the right thing for New York
Republicans."
</P>
<P>
	   "The system that is responsible for this sad situation cannot be defended
any longer," McCain added. "It is an embarrassment to a wonderful state, a
disappointment to a proud party and an affront to the people."
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, appearing in Dover, Del., said "put him on the ballot."
</P>
<P>
	   The apparent shift came after Bush, stung by McCain's big New Hampshire
primary win Tuesday and unhappy about handing McCain an issue tailor-made for
his "outsider" campaign, signaled his New York supporters their fight to keep
McCain off primary ballots in more than one-third of the state's congressional
district had gone far enough.
</P>
<P>
	   Karl Rove, one of the Texas governor's top strategists, told the top
echelons of the party in New York on Wednesday that Bush would prefer his
supporters not appeal if McCain wins a federal court challenge, said a Bush
adviser who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   A top adviser to Pataki and Powers, also speaking on condition of anonymity,
said "they're leaning toward not appealing."
</P>
<P>
	   The judge in the case said Thursday that no ruling would be issued before
Monday, at the earliest. Lawyers on both sides said they expect it to be a
victory for McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   In Delaware, Bush said he didn't think his campaign would be hurt by a court
ruling in New York for McCain. "I'd be happy for him to be on the ballot if the
judge so decides," Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   There was talk Thursday that the McCain camp and the state GOP were in
discussions that might lead to a settlement of the case and the delay until
Monday for a possible court ruling seemed in line with that.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's New York campaign manager, Staten Island Borough President Guy
Molinari, said he knew nothing about that.
</P>
<P>
	   There was no immediate comment from Powers, but one of his lawyers, Lawrence
Mandelker, said, "there obviously is enormous political pressure for a
settlement. I'm not involved in those discussions. They are several pay grades
above me, as we used to say in the military."
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has repeatedly criticized the Texas governor for not calling off the
effort to block his access to the New York ballot for the March 7 primary
because he lacked enough petition signatures.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki, who has been mentioned as a possible Bush runningmate, has also come
under widespread criticism.
</P>
<P>
	   "If they're smart, they just throw open the door and let McCain come
crashing through now," Nelson Warfield, a veteran political operative who worked
on Bob Dole's 1996 campaign, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   "Here's Governor Pataki trying to build a national image and now he runs the
risk of being seen as that governor who's pro-choice on abortion and anti-choice
for president," Warfield said.
</P>
<P>
	   And, in the wake of McCain's New Hampshire victory, New York Republicans who
backed Bush are getting nervous, Republican operative Jay Severin said.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are a lot of people in the last 24 hours not sleeping well on the
Republican side in New York," Severin said.
</P>
<P>
	   The controversy took another twist Wednesday when Bush's delegate slate was
knocked off the ballot by a state judge in one of the state's 31 congressional
district. Lawyers for Powers conceded there were fraudulent signatures on Bush
petitions in the district. They had been challenged by lawyers for millionaire
publisher Steve Forbes, who is also on the New York ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   "As you sow, so shall you reap," McCain supporter Molinari, a former
congressman, crowed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker, while confirming Rove had discussed
the McCain lawsuit with New York party leaders, said any decision about an
appeal is "not a decision for us to make."
</P>
<P>
	   Jeffrey Buley, general counsel to New York's the state Republican committee,
said Thursday that the party had not decided how it would react to a loss in
court. "No decision will be made until we read the (judge's) decision," Buley
said.
</P>
<P>
	   New York's rules require presidential candidates to gather party members'
signatures in each of the state's 31 congressional districts to get their
delegate slates on the ballot. McCain is battling in federal court to get back
on the ballot in 12 districts. He has qualified in the others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
