<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Closely Watching Austrian Gov't  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States will keep a close watch on Austria's new
coalition government, which includes Joerg Haider's extreme right-wing Freedom
Party, a State Department spokesman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``While it's premature to talk about our actions at this stage, we will
determine what steps are appropriate based on what happens,'' James Foley said.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States remains concerned even though Haider and his coalition
partner, Wolfgang Schuessel of the centrist Austrian People's Party, renounced
the nation's Nazi past and promised to respect European values.
</P>
<P>
	   Any suggestion ``our concerns would evaporate simply on the basis of a
statement is not credible,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
	   He repeated Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's statement from Wednesday
that the Austria people have the right to choose their own government.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But the international community has its own rights and obligations to be
on the watch, to be concerned about the fate and future of democracy in a fellow
democracy in Austria,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Albright expressed the U.S. position in a telephone conversation Wednesday
with Schuessel and rebutted suggestions that Schuessel had ignored her and
joined Haider in a coalition.
</P>
<P>
	   Foley said statements Haider made in the past ``have caused deep concern.
... The words may indicate the direction people may take in practice. The
international community has to be vigilant when things are said which can
trivialize what happened 50, 60 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
	   About a decade ago, Haider praised Adolf Hitler's ``orderly'' employment
policies and lauded veterans of the Waffen SS as ``decent people of good
character.'' He also has opposed the European Union's expansion and urged a near
halt on immigration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
