<HEADLINE> Mexican Students Charged in Skirmish  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Prosecutors have filed criminal charges against 174
radical student leaders of a strike that has shuttered Latin America's largest
university for the last nine months, local news media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The strikers face a variety of charges -- including rioting, sabotage,
terrorism and assault -- stemming from a Tuesday skirmish in which they fought
anti-strike students and security forces at a university-affiliated high school.
Some could be sentenced to as much as 40 years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
	   The students and 76 minors also arrested Tuesday were being detained. Fellow
strikers, who remain in control of the National Autonomous University of
Mexico's huge main campus, have added the release of their comrades to their
list of demands for ending the strike.
</P>
<P>
	   The minors' fate has yet to be decided. They are being held at a juvenile
detention facility and cannot be charged as adults, but they could be sent to
reform facilities.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Thursday, prosecutors requested arrest warrants for another 430 members
of leftist ``community groups'' who have joined student strikers in occupying
the sprawling main campus, local media reported. Prosecutors said they want to
arrest the leftists on illegal-occupation charges. It was unclear whether courts
would grant the request.
</P>
<P>
	   The strike at the university began in April to protest the university's
plans to raise annual tuition from a few cents to $140. Administrators withdrew
the fee increase, but students later demanded sweeping policy changes. They
refuse to reopen the university until officials meet their demands for
guaranteed admissions and a loosening of academic standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
