<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer upgrades would cost up to $75 million  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - State Comptroller Nancy Wyman and Gov. John G.
Rowland said Thursday they want to spend between $60 million and $75 million to
upgrade the state's computer system.
<P>
	   The three-year plan was announced seven months after Rowland nixed his $1.5
billion plan to privatize Connecticut's computers. Rowland said in late June he
was not convinced that better service could be guaranteed if the state turned
its operations over to Texas-based Electronic Data Systems Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   Wyman and state workers had opposed the 7-year privatization plan, which
they said would not meet its efficiency targets and could cost state jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's no secret that the governor and I had a little disagreement last
summer over how to handle this issue," Wyman said. "But even though we differed
on the solution, the governor and I always agreed on the scope of the problem."
</P>
<P>
	   Under the new proposal, improvements will be targeted for the accounting,
payroll and personnel tracking systems. Wyman said the upgrade will allow the
state to track how tax dollars are spent and make it easier for companies to do
business with the state.
</P>
<P>
	   The upgrade will effect every state agency.
</P>
<P>
	   "We will be replacing the complicated maze we have now with a simple,
integrated system that will deliver services in a more effective and efficient
manner," Wyman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Rowland wants to use about $8 million of the state's $240 million surplus to
start the upgrades.
</P>
<P>
	   "If we have more surplus dollars throughout the year, we perhaps could use
more of that this year or next year," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The bulk of the remaining costs - including buying software and hardware,
system setup and training - would be paid for through bonding, Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
	   That spending plan likely will win approval in the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
	   "The price tag is pretty impressively low," said Senate President Pro
Tempore Kevin Sullivan. "It's a perfectly legitimate expenditure out of the
surplus."
</P>
<P>
	   While outside vendors will be needed to get the new system in place, Rowland
and Wyman said their plan is a far cry from privatization.
</P>
<P>
	   "We believe we could do most everything in-house with our state employees,"
Wyman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
