<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury selected for second Louima case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A jury that is racially mixed but dominated by women was
chosen on Thursday for the federal court trial of three police officers accused
of conspiring to obstruct justice in the Abner Louima police-torture case.
<P>
	   Testimony is to begin next Monday before U.S. District Judge Eugene
Nickerson, who has said the trial - the second in the racially charged case -
should last about four weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury of six blacks, five whites and one Hispanic, was chosen from an
original pool of 500 citizens, winnowed down to 75. Six alternates were added
later.
</P>
<P>
	   Overall, women dominated the panel eight to four, with the alternates split
evenly as to gender. The alternates were five whites and one Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense lawyers declined to comment on the jury's makeup. "Twelve people,
tried and true, U.S. citizens. We're ready to go," said Ron Fischetti, the
attorney for ex-officer Charles Schwarz. "It looks like a jury that can be fair.
That's all both sides want."
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz's wife, Andra, said she would have preferred more male jurors.
</P>
<P>
	   "I wish it was a lot more even, between women and men," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   She added that after a long wait, her husband is "very anxious to get going,
very anxious to have the statements heard that were not heard in the first
trial. There is a lot more to this case than was first thought."
</P>
<P>
	   The trial stems from the 1997 incident in which Louima, a Haitian immigrant,
was brutalized by officers at a Brooklyn precinct house after his arrest on a
minor charge.
</P>
<P>
	   Defendant Schwarz already faces a possible life sentence after conviction
last year for violating Louima's civil rights. The key witness is expected to be
former officer Justin Volpe, who is serving 30 years after pleading guilty on
the civil rights charge. He now claims Schwarz did not take part in the attack.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Schwarz said the case was "never about race in the first place," but
was triggered by Volpe's anger.
</P>
<P>
	   "People can see clearly that it was an act of rage and not race," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Nickerson earlier questioned would-be jurors closely on their knowledge of
the highly publicized case, their experiences with racism and their views toward
the so-called "blue wall of silence" by which cops supposedly shield each other
from allegations of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury will remain anonymous and escorted to and from the courthouse by
federal marshals, but not sequestered in a hotel, as is the case in some high
tension trials.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers, all of whom are white, face five years in prison on the
conspiracy charge. Louima is black.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz, 35, Thomas Wiese, 37, and Thomas Bruder, 34, are accused of
conspiring to obstruct justice by concealing Schwarz's purported role in the
assault on Louima, who was beaten and sodomized with a broom handle by Volpe.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz was convicted last year of holding Louima down during the attack.
Volpe has said since that Wiese, not Schwarz, was in the bathroom in Brooklyn's
70th Precinct.
</P>
<P>
	   Stuart London and Joseph Tacopina, attorneys for Bruder and Wiese,
respectively, say their clients contend that Schwarz was never in the bathroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
