<HEADLINE> Anheuser-Busch Earnings Rise Again  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Higher prices and continued strong beer sales helped push
the profits of Anheuser-Busch Cos. up 13 percent in the fourth quarter, matching
Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   The world's largest brewery -- the maker of Budweiser, Bud Light and other
beers -- said Thursday that it earned $190.6 million, or 41 cents a share, in
the October-December period, compared with $168.6 million, or 35 cents a share,
a year earlier. That matched the expectation of analysts surveyed by First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales rose 4.2 percent to $2.72 billion in the fourth quarter from $2.61
billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   In late afternoon trading, shares in Anheuser-Busch were priced at $67.75,
down $2.06 1/4 or nearly 3 percent, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   "Anheuser-Busch had a great year in 1999, selling over 100 million barrels
of its beer brands worldwide -- the first time in history this has been
accomplished," company president and chairman August A. Busch III said.
</P>
<P>
	   The company's share of the domestic beer market for 1999 was 47.4 percent,
an increase of 0.6 percentage point from 1998. Busch said that price increases
are being implemented in much of the United States on brands and packages
representing about 40 percent of volume.
</P>
<P>
	   For all of 1999, Anheuser-Busch earned $1.4 billion, or $2.94 per share, up
from $1.23 billion, or $2.53 a share, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales were $11.7 billion, up 4 percent from $11.25 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Worldwide, Anheuser-Busch's beer volume was essentially level for the fourth
quarter and up 1.2 percent for the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
