<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mattel CEO Jill Barad Resigns  </HEADLINE>
    By RACHEL BECK AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mattel Inc.'s embattled chief executive Jill Barad resigned
Thursday after coming under fire for months for failing to revive falling sales
and profits at the world's biggest toymaker.
</P>
<P>
	   Her departure comes as the El Segundo, Calif.-based Mattel reported a steep
loss for the fourth quarter, disappointing Wall Street analysts for the third
time in the past four quarters.
</P>
<P>
	   Barad, one of the highest ranking women in business, was under intense
pressure from investors and Mattel's board of directors to explain big losses at
the company's newly acquired Learning Company software division and other
troubles at Mattel.
</P>
<P>
	   With her resignation, the board of directors will take charge of the company
to oversee operations and search for a new CEO. The board appointed two of its
own members to leadership rolls, picking William Rollnick as acting chairman and
Ronald Loeb as acting CEO.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think they need to look themselves in the eyes, look at what the problems
are with this company and really try to figure them out," said Sean McGowan, a
toy analyst at the investment firm Gerard Klauer Mattison.
</P>
<P>
	   For the quarter ended Dec. 31, Mattel reported a net loss of $18.4 million,
or 4 cents a share, compared with profits of $86.7 million, or 22 cents a share,
in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had expected the company
to earn 25 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales for the quarter were $1.77 billion, down from $1.82 billion a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Mattel shares, which surged 14 percent Wednesday on speculation that Barad
was on her way out, slipped 6 1/4 cents Thursday to $11.75 on the New York Stock
Exchange. Word of the resignation came in the final moments of trading on the
Big Board.
</P>
<P>
	   Disappointing results have pushed Mattel's stock down by more than 60
percent from its high of $30.31 1/4 in April.
</P>
<P>
	   Barad joined Mattel in 1981 as a product manager in the novelty toy unit,
and took the helm in 1997. With a flashy style and an aggressive marketing
savvy, Barad helped make Mattel into the dominant toymaker in the world.
</P>
<P>
	   Under her supervision, Barbie was transformed from a tired, $200 million
product line into one of the most recognized brands of all time with $1.9
billion in sales last year.
</P>
<P>
	   She also was able to recognize the changing desires of techno-literate kids
today, who learn to use a computer in pre-school. Mattel's has stepped up its
software and online offerings, and looked to new avenues to capture shoppers.
</P>
<P>
	   Barad was also considered a pioneer of women in corporate America. She was
only one of four women CEOs heading Fortune 500 companies. The others include
Andrea Jung is CEO of Avon, Carleton S. Fiorina of Hewlett-Packard and Marion D.
Sandler of Golden West Financial.
</P>
<P>
	   But Barad, in the last 14 months, has fallen out of favor with the
investment community. Shareholders and analysts have been calling for some kind
of shakeup at the company, many saying they wanted to Barad out.
</P>
<P>
	   Her troubles began in December 1998 when Mattel announced a $500 million
shortfall for the year after the company ignored an announcement by Toys R Us
that it planned to reduce its inventory during the year, and the prospect that
other retailers would do likewise.
</P>
<P>
	   That came only weeks after Barad assured analysts that Mattel would meet its
projections.
</P>
<P>
	   Her bigger problem, however, has come from Mattel's $3.6 billion purchase of
the Learning Company, a software manufacturer that it bought last May as part of
an effort to tap the growing market for interactive toys. The Learning Company's
software titles include Carmen Sandiego, Riven and Myst.
</P>
<P>
	   That deal was supposed to immediately add $50 million annually to Mattel's
bottom line. Instead the company lost $105 million in the third quarter due to a
number of problems with the software division, including a loss of a key
distribution deal and an unexpected high return of unsold products from
retailers.
</P>
<P>
	   And the problems with the Learning Company haven't stopped. During the
fourth quarter, the division's sales plunged 40 percent to $165 million, mostly
due to slower CD-ROM sales and competitive pricing.
</P>
<P>
	   Also problematic for Mattel was a slump in its business overseas, with sales
abroad falling 8 percent from a year ago. The company has also lost many of its
top executives in recent months, including its president and chief financial
officer, who will retire in March.
</P>
<P>
	   While such problems have plagued Mattel, its core domestic business has
remained somewhat strong. Barbie sales climbed 11 percent in the fourth quarter,
while the Fisher-Price line, which includes the Sesame Street license, rose by
48 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The company's day-to-day operations will be managed by a newly formed office
of the chief operating officer, comprised of executives who manage Mattel's
major brands. That team will report to Loeb.
</P>
<P>
	   Loeb, a lawyer, has been a member of Mattel's board since 1970. Rollnick,
who is retired as chairman and a director from Genstar Rental Electronics, has
been on the board since 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1703 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FTC, Talent Scouts Settle Case  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ARNOLD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The operators of a model and talent operation that did
business from Connecticut to Florida have been banned from selling their
``screen test services'' as part of a settlement with the Federal Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
	   They also will pay $972,000.
</P>
<P>
	   The FTC said Screen Test U.S.A. misled consumers into believing they stood a
better chance of catching on with talent agencies by buying the firm's services.
The firm's founder, Fred Vanore, of Wayne, N.J., spearheaded the scam, the FTC
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Vanore has an unlisted phone number and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Another defendant in the case was American Child Actor and Modeling
Association of Wayne, which the FTC said was a sham corporation created by
Vanore to add credibility to Screen Test U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
	   The association was promoted as a ``leading independent, nonprofit
organization formed to protect consumers from unethical business practices.''
</P>
<P>
	   The FTC has filed a string of charges against what it says are phony talent
scouts that use the promise of modeling deals to coerce people into paying for
expensive classes and photo shoots.
</P>
<P>
	   It accused Screen Test U.S.A., through offices in New Jersey, Connecticut,
Pennsylvania, New York and Florida, of using a screen test for children to con
parents into buying company products.
</P>
<P>
	   Parents who saw television, radio or Internet ads and called the company
were told to bring their children in for a $45 screen test. After the company
informed parents that their children had passed the screen test, scouts put
pressure on the families to buy packages of photographs ranging from $495 to
$795.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, a federal court in New Jersey temporarily halted the company's
operations and froze its assets.
</P>
<P>
	   Other defendants in the case were Premier Marketing Inc. and Alice McManus,
based in Kenilworth, N.J.; R.J. Ims Corp., Richard J. Ims, Jr. and Angela Ims,
based in Bala Cynwyd, Pa.; Premier Marketing Inc., Show Biz Central of
Westchester Inc. and John Yannielli, based in Cheshire, Conn.; Tomorrow's Stars
Inc., Edward J. Bauer and Helen J. Bauer, based in Boca Raton, Fla.; Jeffrey C.
McManus and JCM Marketing Inc., based in Miami; and Thomas J. Yannielli of New
York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1704 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0186 </DOCNO>
