<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank: Oil Prices Will Drop  </HEADLINE>
    By HARRY DUNPHY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The World Bank said Thursday it expects oil prices that
have been edging close to $30 a barrel to decline to under $20 later this year,
which would be good news for motorists.
</P>
<P>
	   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries is scheduled to meet March
27 to decide whether to continue production cuts imposed last February that have
boosted crude oil prices from a low of $10.80 a barrel in December 1998. OPEC
has hinted the cuts might be extended, but the World Bank is predicting
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
	   "The market needs more oil, and if it's not forthcoming, the prices will go
up," said Shane Streitfel, a bank energy economist. "We're anticipating that
(OPEC) will raise production at its March meeting."
</P>
<P>
	   A decline in the price of oil would also be good news for the Clinton
administration, which has expressed concern at the steep increase and has been
under pressure to ask OPEC members such as Saudi Arabia and Venezuela to boost
production.
</P>
<P>
	   The World Bank's forecast on oil prices was contained in the latest issue of
Global Commodity Markets, which is published four times a year.
</P>
<P>
	   "Stocks will continue to decline throughout the winter, and in the absence
of higher production prices could soar," the report said. "At some point OPEC
will raise production and prices are expected to eventually settle back below
$20 a barrel."
</P>
<P>
	   If prices remain high, the report said, this "would dampen demand and
stimulate development of competing supplies, making it more difficult for OPEC
to raise production in the future."
</P>
<P>
	   The report said demand is likely to pick up starting in April as refiners
replenish depleted stocks and prepare for the summer driving season.
</P>
<P>
	   "Thus the combination of high prices, low stocks and strong demand is
expected to bring forth higher OPEC production," the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   The challenge for OPEC, the report continued, "is to raise production in a
coordinated manner" so that prices stay just above the $20 a barrel level its
members say they want to maintain.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of a barrel of oil on the New York Mercantile Exchange closed
Thursday at $28.23
</P>
<P>
	   Using projections from the International Energy Association, the bank said
world oil demand in the first three months of 2000 will exceed supply by around
2.5 million barrels a day, provided OPEC production remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
	   Even if OPEC boosts production, demand for oil is expected to increase in
2000, surpassing last year's 1.2 million barrels a day, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1720 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spice Conglomerate Settles With FTC  </HEADLINE>
    By SHEILA HOTCHKIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BALTIMORE (AP) -- McCormick &AMP; Co. said Thursday that the spice and food
conglomerate had settled a price discrimination complaint with the Federal Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
	   The FTC had accused the company of violating the Depression-era
Robinson-Patman Act, which requires manufacturers to offer all retailers the
same fees and discounts unless they are trying to match prices by the
competition. The agreement was signed by the company on Wednesday, but still
requires final approval by the FTC, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreement is not an admission of guilt.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the agreement, the company agrees not to violate the price
discrimination section of the Robinson-Patman Act and to provide detailed
documentation of all the reasons for making an offer under the "meeting
competition" defense.
</P>
<P>
	   The company will not incur any fines or penalties under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   McCormick vice president Robert Skelton said he was uncertain about how long
it would take for the FTC to sign the deal, but did not anticipate any problems.
</P>
<P>
	   "From an investment standpoint, this certainly makes (McCormick) more
attractive to investors -- this was sort of a black cloud hanging over the
company," said Kurt Funderburg, an analyst with Baltimore-based investment
banking firm Ferris, Baker Watts Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency began investigating the Sparks-based company in 1996, following a
price war with Burns Philp Food Inc. that stretched through the early 1990s.
McCormick successfully fended off the Australian company during the early 1990s,
reportedly spending millions of dollars to secure its place in grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
	   The FTC questioned three contracts the company negotiated in 1994 and 1995,
during the height of the price war, Skelton said.
</P>
<P>
	   Company officials have denied wrongdoing, arguing that the contracts are
covered by the section of the Robinson-Patman Act that allows them to meet their
competition's offers to specific retailers. But they said the investigation has
hurt the company and a settlement was in the company's best interests.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of McCormick rose $1.25 to $26 in afternoon trading on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
