<DOCNO> APW20000203.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money flows early in Senate race, Giuliani criticizes first lady's  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani attacked Hillary
Rodham Clinton's air travel on Thursday, saying newly released campaign finance
records show the first lady has not fully reimbursed taxpayers for her travel on
Air Force jets she uses while campaigning.
<P>
	   The Clinton camp paid the federal government $34,000 for dozens of trips to
New York in recent months related to her U.S. Senate campaign, the records show.
Giuliani's campaign said that is well below the actual costs of travel.
Estimates place the cost of Air Force C-20's, like the one Clinton uses to
travel to New York, at about $20,000 per trip.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'd like that deal," Giuliani said in Brooklyn. "If you can get that deal
for you and your family, take it, because Disneyland, here I come!"
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's campaign is required by law to reimburse the government at the
rate of first-class commercial travel, spokesman Howard Wolfson has said. The
Secret Service advised the first lady to continue to use government jets for her
travel for security reasons, Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Given the fact that he's running his campaign out of City Hall at taxpayer
expense it's hard to take his latest tantrum seriously," Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
	   The voluminous campaign reports, which run thousands of pages and together
measure more than a foot high, also showed that both candidates spent a huge
amount on direct-mail fund-raising efforts. Giuliani, whose mailers have taken
shots at the first lady by calling her "leader of the ultra-left wing," spent
about $1.3 million on six Virginia-based companies for direct-mail services. The
largest amount, more than $800,000, went to American Target Advertising, a
Manassas, Va.-based firm. It is operated by Richard Viguerie, who is renowned
for his fund raising on behalf of conservatives such as Sen. Jesse Helms of
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton spent more $500,000 on direct mailing of her own and close to $1
million on political and fund-raising consultants.
</P>
<P>
	   All total, Clinton raised $8 million over six months and has $4.7 million
cash on hand. She spent $3.3 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani took in $8.8 million in the last six months, which combined with
the money he had already raised brought him to $11.5 million. He has $7.4
million cash on hand and he spent $4.3 million last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Individual donors to each candidate read like a who's who list. In a sign of
the clear national interest in the race, contributions poured in from all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton drew heavily from Hollywood types - Tom Cruise, Sean "Puffy" Combs,
Barbara Streisand and Tom Hanks were among her contributors. Giuliani's donor
list was a bit less star-studded but contained business heavyweights such as
General Electric Chairman Jack Welch and Revlon billionaire Ronald Perelman.
</P>
<P>
	   Individual donors may contribute up to $2,000 each.
</P>
<P>
	   Both campaigns benefitted from political action committees that can give up
to $10,000. Giuliani received $245,311 and Clinton $219,925.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani received lots of checks from the financial services industry which
call New York City home, including Arthur Anderson, Chase Manhattan, Keycorp and
PriceWaterhouseCoopers. He also took in a hefty amount of cash from the
pharmaceutical industry. Pfizer, Bristol-Myers Squibb and Glaxo Wellcome all
contributed thousands of dollars. Log Cabin Republicans, a group supporting gays
in the GOP, gave Giuliani the maximum $10,000.
</P>
<P>
	   The mayor, who had supported an unsuccessful attempt to have gambling on
Governor's Island, also drew large contributions from the gambling industry on a
fund-raising jaunt to Las Vegas. Mirage Resorts donated $9,870 and Harrah's
chipped in $2,500.
</P>
<P>
	   Through leadership committees, Republican lawmakers also padded Giuliani's
bank accounts. Former New York Sen. Alfonse D'Amato gave the mayor $2,000.
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott gave him $1,000 and Republican National
Senatorial Committee Chairman Mitch McConnell chipped in $5,000.
</P>
<P>
	   The bulk of Clinton's PAC money came from a laundry list of unions. Giving
the maximum $10,000 were the Amalgamated Transit Union, the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers and the Communication Workers of America. Also
contributing were the American Federation of State, County and Municipal
Employees; the AFL-CIO and the National Association of Letter Carriers.
</P>
<P>
	   The Association of Trial Lawyers also gave Clinton the maximum $10,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the Democratic lawmakers donating to Clinton's campaign were
Connecticut Sen. Christopher Dodd, who gave $1,000 and New York Reps. Gary
Ackerman and Carolyn Maloney, who each donated $1,000. Clinton has held fund
raisers for both New York lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
	   Both the Giuliani and Clinton campaigns got money from General Electric and
Ernst and Young. GE gave $4,225 to Giuliani and $2,500 to Clinton. Ernst and
Young gave $10,000 to each.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton is set to formally enter the Senate race Sunday and kick off her
campaign with a tour around the state. It is unclear when Giuliani will
officially enter the race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
