<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday, Feb. 3, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   Mannesmann, Vodafone Set To Merge
</P>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- Mannesmann AG of Germany is poised to accept a
sweetened takeover bid of $180 billion from Britain's Vodafone
Airtouch PLC, forming the world's No. 1 wireless company in the
biggest buyout ever. Mannesmann head Klaus Esser, speaking today
alongside Vodafone chief executive Chris Gent in their first
side-by-side appearance, said he would recommend that the company's
supervisory board accept the deal at a meeting on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Mattel CEO Jill Barad Resigns
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mattel Inc.'s embattled chief executive Jill
Barad resigned today after coming under fire for months for failing
to revive falling sales and profits at the world's biggest
toymaker. Her departure comes as the El Segundo, Calif.-based
Mattel reported a steep loss for the fourth quarter, disappointing
Wall Street analysts for the third consecutive quarter. With her
resignation, the board of directors will take charge of the company
to oversee operations and search for a new CEO. For the quarter
ended Dec. 31, Mattel reported a net loss of $18.4 million, or 4
cents a share, compared with profits of $86.7 million, or 22 cents
a share, in the same period a year ago. Analysts surveyed by First
Call/Thomson Financial had expected the company to earn 25 cents a
share. Shares of Mattel were at 11 15/16, up  1/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Nasdaq Ends Up 137.06; Dow Up 10.24
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks bounded higher today as
investors decided that those companies are growing quickly enough
to dodge the threat of rising interest rates. Old-fashioned
blue-chip shares were little changed. The tech-dominated Nasdaq
composite index rose 137.06 to 4,211.02, its third biggest point
gain in history. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 10.24 to
11,013.44. Broader indicators were also modestly higher. A day
after the Federal Reserve imposed its fourth interest-rate increase
since June 1999, investors poured money into shares of technology
companies to the exclusion of all other sectors. Analysts said
investors are shaking off suggestions that the often slim profits
of growing technology companies may be squeezed by rising interest
rates.
</P>
