<P>
	   Greenspan Wins 4th Term at Fed
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate confirmed Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan for another four-year term today by a vote of 89-4.
The approval came a day after the Fed raised a key interest rate a
quarter of a percentage point to stave off harmful inflation as the
economy continues record growth. Greenspan, 73, got bipartisan
support. But a small group of liberal senators opposed the
nomination on grounds the Fed is too secretive and Greenspan has
been overly worried about inflation and insensitive to the impact
higher interest rates have on American families.
</P>
<P>
	   Factory Orders Surge 3.3 Percent
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- New orders to American factories had their
biggest increase in seven years in December, up 3.3 percent, the
Commerce Department said today. The rise helped make all of 1999
the strongest year manufacturers have seen since 1995. Greater
demand for airplanes and electronic helped the rise. Meanwhile,
retailers said better than expected December sales rounded out what
has been the strongest fiscal year for the nation's retailers since
the early 1990s. Wall Street analysts raised their fourth-quarter
earnings estimates for many retailers, including Neiman Marcus and
May Department Stores.
</P>
<P>
	   Colgate-Palmolive Earnings Up in 4Q
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Colgate-Palmolive Co., the nation's top seller
of toothpaste and a leader in the dishwashing soap market, said
today its profits rose 11 percent in the fourth quarter, beating
Wall Street forecasts. The New York-based company said net income
was $260.6 million, or 41 cents a share, in the final three months
of 1999. The figure beat analysts' estimates by a penny. Sales in
the final quarter of 1999 totaled $2.34 billion, up 2.3 percent.
</P>
