	   Ads Boost New York Times Earnings
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Strong advertising growth and lower newsprint
costs drove fourth-quarter profits sharply higher at The New York
Times Co., the company reported today. Excluding one-time gains and
losses, earnings rose 24 percent to $108.4 million, or 61 cents a
share, compared to $87.3 million, or 47 cents per share, in the
same period a year ago. The results easily beat analysts'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford Workers To Get PCs, Web Access
</P>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. is offering Hewlett-Packard
personal computers to its 350,000 employees worldwide for their
home use. The three-year deal, being coordinated by PeoplePC Inc.,
of San Francisco, also includes a Hewlett-Packard color ink jet
printer and Internet access, all for $5 a month. ``This program
keeps Ford Motor Company and our worldwide team at the leading edge
of e-business technology and skills,'' said Ford president and
chief executive officer Jac Nasser in announcing the deal today.
</P>
<P>
	   European Central Bank Raises Rates
</P>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The beleaguered euro rebounded sharply
after European interest rates were raised one-quarter percentage
point today, but the central bank's president said the weak
currency was just one contributing factor in the inflation-fighting
move. The euro was trading just below 99 U.S. cents this afternoon
in the United States, up from its late New York rate yesterday of
97.57 cents and the record low of 96.68 cents reached Tuesday. The
strong bounce came in part because many analysts did not expect the
European Central Bank to act so quickly to raise rates.
</P>
<P>
	   Nissan May Sell Aerospace Division
</P>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Ailing Japanese carmaker Nissan Motor Co. said
today it is in talks to sell its aerospace division as part of the
company's efforts to restructure and return to profitability. A
spokeswoman for the automaker, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
confirmed media reports that it is negotiating a sale, but declined
to give details. The Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's main business
daily, reported that Nissan is expected to sell the aerospace unit
to Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy Industries Co. for 40 billion yen
($370 million).
</P>
