<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State GOP leaders surrender on anti-McCain effort  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki, George W. Bush's top New York
backer, waved the white flag of surrender Thursday in the battle to keep John
McCain off the state's presidential primary ballot.
<P>
	   "I believe that John McCain should be on the ballot," Pataki said in a
statement. "This should be a campaign about ideas and issues, not
technicalities. I'm confident that George Bush will win that campaign."
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki said Bush agreed with him.
</P>
<P>
	   With growing signs that New York's GOP hierarchy was ready to buckle, McCain
had sent letters to Pataki and state GOP Chairman William Powers earlier
Thursday calling for them to "do the right thing for New York Republicans."
</P>
<P>
	   "The system that is responsible for this sad situation cannot be defended
any longer," McCain wrote. "It is an embarrassment to a wonderful state, a
disappointment to a proud party and an affront to the people."
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, appearing in Dover, Del., had said "put him on the ballot."
</P>
<P>
	   The shift came after Bush, stung by McCain's big New Hampshire primary win
Tuesday and unhappy about handing McCain an issue tailor-made for his "outsider"
campaign, signaled his New York supporters their fight to keep McCain off
primary ballots in more than one-third of the state's congressional district had
gone far enough.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, top New York Republicans were told that Bush would prefer his
supporters not appeal if McCain won a federal court challenge to open up the New
York ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge in the case said Thursday that no ruling would be issued before
Monday, at the earliest. Lawyers on both sides said they expect it to be a
victory for McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki spokeswoman Zenia Mucha said that if the judge happened to rule
against McCain, Pataki was then ready to "take the appropriate steps to ensure
that (McCain) is on the ballot." Mucha said she could not elaborate on what
those steps would be.
</P>
<P>
	   In Delaware, Bush said he didn't think his campaign would be hurt by a court
ruling in favor of McCain. "I'd be happy for him to be on the ballot if the
judge so decides," Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   There was talk Thursday that the McCain camp and the state GOP were in
discussions that might lead to a settlement of the case and the delay until
Monday for a possible court ruling seemed in line with that.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's New York campaign manager, Staten Island Borough President Guy
Molinari, said he knew nothing about that.
</P>
<P>
	   There was no immediate comment from Powers, but one of his lawyers, Lawrence
Mandelker, said, "there obviously is enormous political pressure for a
settlement. I'm not involved in those discussions. They are several pay grades
above me, as we used to say in the military."
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has repeatedly criticized the Texas governor for not calling off the
effort to block his access to the New York ballot for the March 7 primary
because he lacked enough petition signatures.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki, who has been mentioned as a possible Bush runningmate, has also come
under widespread criticism.
</P>
<P>
	   "If they're smart, they just throw open the door and let McCain come
crashing through now," Nelson Warfield, a veteran political operative who worked
on Bob Dole's 1996 campaign, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   "Here's Governor Pataki trying to build a national image and now he runs the
risk of being seen as that governor who's pro-choice on abortion and anti-choice
for president," Warfield said.
</P>
<P>
	   And, in the wake of McCain's New Hampshire victory, New York Republicans who
backed Bush are getting nervous, Republican operative Jay Severin said.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are a lot of people in the last 24 hours not sleeping well on the
Republican side in New York," Severin said.
</P>
<P>
	   The controversy took another twist Wednesday when Bush's delegate slate was
knocked off the ballot by a state judge in one of the state's 31 congressional
district. Lawyers for Powers conceded there were fraudulent signatures on Bush
petitions in the district. They had been challenged by lawyers for millionaire
publisher Steve Forbes, who is also on the New York ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   "As you sow, so shall you reap," McCain supporter Molinari, a former
congressman, crowed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   New York's rules require presidential candidates to gather party members'
signatures in each of the state's 31 congressional districts to get their
delegate slates on the ballot. McCain is battling in federal court to get back
on the ballot in 12 districts. He has qualified in the others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-03-00 1735 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State: Fatal Ocean City roller coaster crash caused by faulty  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A faulty replacement brake installed on an Ocean
City roller coaster caused a crash in which a New York woman and her 8-year-old
daughter were killed last year, state investigators said Thursday.
<P>
	   Officials with the state Department of Community Affairs also cited problems
with a safety restraining bar that allowed the victims to be hurled from the car
as it sped backward down an inclined track after coming loose from a chain that
was pulling it toward the summit.
</P>
<P>
	   William Connolly, director of the Division of Codes and Standards, said the
state has fined the Italian manufacturer of the Wild Wonder roller coaster
$30,000 and the owners of Gillian's Wonderland Pier $25,000 for safety
violations.
</P>
<P>
	   He also proposed legislation giving the state authority over amusement ride
manufacturers, and a 10-fold increase in fines for safety violations.
</P>
<P>
	   A five-month investigation into the Aug. 28 accident centered on the brake,
called an anti-rollback device, that's designed to prevent the roller coaster
cars from moving backwards on the ride's track.
</P>
<P>
	   The car on the ride, which had just opened to the public on July 1, came
loose from the chain that was dragging it up a steep incline, where it was to be
released at the top and glide down the other side, powered by gravity.
</P>
<P>
	   The anti-rollback device was designed for just such a situation, meant to
keep the car from rolling backward by applying brakes with sharp steel teeth
that bite into the rails and prevent slippage.
</P>
<P>
	   But on the night of the accident, the teeth on the device were badly worn.
They were made of steel that was much weaker than the hardened metal that was
supposed to be used, Connolly said.
</P>
<P>
	   The park's owners had replaced the original part on Aug. 17 with a new one
made by a metal shop in neighboring Somers Point, but did not get permission
from the state to make the switch, Connolly said. He also said the device was
improperly installed, riding slightly off-center along the rails, which
contributed to its inability to grip the rail and stop the car from sliding
backward.
</P>
<P>
	   When the device failed, the car in which Kimberly Bailey of Pomona, N.Y.,
and her daughter, Jessica were riding hurled backward down the track and around
a sharp curve.
</P>
<P>
	   The extreme centrifugal force of the curve, the speed of the descent (about
30 mph) and an improperly adjusted restraint bar that flew open caused the pair
to be thrown from the car. They died shortly afterward from internal injuries.
</P>
<P>
	   The restraint bar's locking mechanism was improperly adjusted and had a weak
part, Connolly said. But that flaw was not visible to state inspectors who
examined the roller coaster on July 21.
</P>
<P>
	   The park's general manager, Jay Gillian, did not return a telephone message
left at his office Thursday afternoon. A woman who answered the telephone at his
home said Gillian was not present, and refused to take a message for him.
</P>
<P>
	   The coaster was built by an Italian company, Zamperla, specially for
Gillian's. Connolly said anti-rollback devices on other roller coasters in New
Jersey use more secure technology that should not be subject to the same
failure.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ocean City park wanted the manufacturer to design a device that was
quieter than the brakes and chains on most roller coasters that produce a
"clack-clack-clack" sound as the cars are pulled up the incline, Connolly said.
</P>
<P>
	   "This device was unique to the Wild Wonder," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Zamperla was fined $30,000 for, among other things, failing to provide
maintenance schedules and other information to the amusement park owners. The
park owners were fined $25,000 for making the unauthorized repairs and
modifications to the ride and for the incorrect lap bar adjustment.
</P>
<P>
	   The fines are civil penalties. Connolly said the Department of Community
Affairs has forwarded the results of its investigation to the Cape May County
Prosecutor's Office. But Acting Prosecutor David Blaker said there is no
criminal probe into the crash.
</P>
<P>
	   "It appears to be a tragic accident that may or may not have been caused by
negligence," he said. "Certainly it does not rise to the level of recklessness
required for a criminal prosecution."
</P>
<P>
	   Connolly said New Jersey's 1,700 amusement rides are generally safe, and
noted that accidents resulting in serious injuries have been steadily declining
in recent years. Of an estimated 100 million rides taken last year, 12 resulted
in serious injuries, down from 15 in 1998 and 24 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   "You're safer on the ride than you are driving to the amusement park," he
said. "You're safer on the ride than you are on the stairs of your own home."
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, Connolly called for legislation giving the state authority over
ride manufacturers. New Jersey currently has authority only over ride operators.
Oversight of manufacturers would enable the state to review design and safety
specifications of equipment and parts before they are installed at parks.
</P>
<P>
	   He also called for a 10-fold increase in fines for violating ride safety
regulations, to $50,000 per incident. The current $5,000 fine was increased from
$500 just two years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-03-00 1739 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regulators To Protect Financial Data  </HEADLINE>
   By MARCY GORDON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators on Thursday proposed new rules
spelling out how consumers' personal data will be protected as barriers between
banks, investment firms and insurance companies come down.
</P>
<P>
	   The rules, proposed by the Federal Reserve and a Treasury Department
division, will make it tougher for financial companies to share even seemingly
innocuous information, such as customers' names, addresses and telephone
numbers, with outside marketing firms.
</P>
<P>
	   The regulators take the view that such basic information is ``non-public''
information when it is taken from sources such as customer lists -- even if the
names and addresses also are available from a telephone book.
</P>
<P>
	   As ``non-public'' information, the names and addresses -- as well as more
personal financial data such as account balances -- cannot be shared with
outside telemarketers if customers expressly ask their banks, brokerages or
insurance companies not to do so.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the onus is on consumers. They must ask, in a letter or standard
form, financial companies with whom they do business not to share or sell their
data.
</P>
<P>
	   Furthermore, under the new law, banks, brokerages and insurers that join
together under the same corporate roof are entitled to share customers' personal
financial data with each other. In that case, customers do not have the right to
block such sharing.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumer groups and privacy advocates have said the new law's privacy
protections fall short.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is not good enough for consumers, who won't get real privacy
protection,'' said Ed Mierzwinski, consumer program director U.S. Public
Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
	   Catherine Pulley, a spokeswoman for the American Bankers Association, said
the group will ``look more closely at these regulations.''
</P>
<P>
	   Some bankers privately objected to the new rules, saying they took an overly
broad interpretation of privacy protection.
</P>
<P>
	   Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, who won Senate confirmation Thursday for a
fourth term, expressed approval of the new privacy rules at an open meeting at
which he and the other central bank governors voted to propose them for 60 days
of public comment.
</P>
<P>
	   ``So far, so good,'' Greenspan told the Fed staff attorneys, who had drafted
the rules and negotiated with other federal agencies to make the regulations
consistent for different financial industries and sectors.
</P>
<P>
	   While most people think of the Federal Reserve as regulating the nation's
money supply and controlling interest rates, the central bank also oversees some
categories of banks, including those organized in a holding company structure.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed is among a group of agencies that have been drafting privacy rules
for the industries and sectors they regulate, because of legislation enacted in
November that allowed banks, investment firms and insurance companies to get
involved in each other's businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   The other agencies include the Securities and Exchange Commission; the
Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, the Treasury Department division that
regulates national banks; the Office of Thrift Supervision and the National
Credit Union Administration.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Trade Commission is writing the rules for insurance companies
and agents and a panoply of other businesses outside of banks and securities
firms -- including travel agencies, mortgage companies, tax preparation
services, check-cashing outlets, credit bureaus and department stores that issue
credit cards.
</P>
<P>
	   The agencies have been working under a tight deadline. Under the new law,
final regulations must take effect by November.
</P>
<P>
	   The Comptroller's office also published its rules Thursday, and the other
agencies are expected to follow in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a very important advance in privacy protections for consumers,''
Julie Williams, the agency's chief counsel, said in a telephone interview.
``This is a winning situation for consumers and potentially a new competitive
(feature) for banks'' that offer strong privacy protections.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the rules, financial companies will have to disclose their privacy
policies to customers at least once a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1743 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
