<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ad Growth Boosts New York Times  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Strong advertising growth and lower newsprint costs drove
fourth-quarter profits sharply higher at The New York Times Co., the company
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Excluding one-time gains and losses, earnings rose 24 percent to $108.4
million compared, or 61 cents per share, to $87.3 million, or 47 cents per
share, in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   The results easily beat analyst expectations of 57 cents per share, as
reported by First Call/Thomson Financial, sending the company's shares up $1.75
to $47.62 1/2 in trading at 5:15 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   The quarterly profits did not include charges of $5.3 million in 1999 and
$5.4 million in 1998 for work force reductions. Including the charges, net
income rose 25 percent to $105.3 million from $84.3 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Revenues rose 13 percent to $882.5 million from $782.2 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Ad growth in the company's newspaper division, which also includes The
Boston Globe and several regional newspapers, jumped 19 percent during the
quarter, the highest quarterly growth rate in more than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said in a release that its two main newspapers had strong ad
growth from technology businesses, Internet companies and ads for the online
businesses of established companies.
</P>
<P>
	   Revenues from its own Internet operations in the newspaper division more
than doubled to $12.5 million from $5.1 million. In addition to a news site for
its main newspaper, nytimes.com, the company also operates nytoday.com, a city
guide for New York, and Boston.com, an offshoot from The Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
	   Hoping to take advantage of the high valuations that investors bestow on
Internet stocks, the New York Times announced plans last week to issue separate
shares to track its online operations. The company hopes to raise at least $100
million with the sale.
</P>
<P>
	   For the full year, income before special items rose 13 percent to $319.1
million from $282.6 million. Overall, net income rose 11 percent to $310.2
million from $278.9 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Revenues for all of 1999 rose 9 percent to $2.25 billion from $2.07 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
