<HEADLINE> Soybeans Down on Brazil Rains  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean prices tumbled Thursday on the Chicago
Board of Trade as timely rains continued to pelt southern Brazil
during a key period for crop moisture. Grains also fell.
</P>
<P>
	   Soybeans retreated to their lowest level since mid-January as
forecasts called for more rain into next week in leading growing
regions of South America.
</P>
<P>
	   Weekly export sales figures that were up sharply from last week
helped limit the drop. Soybean sales were 391 metric tons for the
week, up from 166 metric tons.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat futures also declined sharply under pressure from soybeans
and from wet weather forecasts for much of the U.S. winter wheat
belt.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn prices were marginally down but avoided the bigger losses
endured by other agricultural commodities.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for March delivery fell 3 1/2 cents to $2.53 3/4 a bushel; March
corn fell 2 3/4 cents to $2.18 a bushel; March oats fell 1 1/4 cent to
$1.10 a bushel; March soybeans fell 6 1/2 cents to $5.01 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Beef futures rose on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while pork
futures were mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   April live cattle rose .45 cent to 72.42 cents a pound; March
feeder cattle rose .45 cent to 85.22 cents a pound; April lean hogs
rose 1.15 cent to 60.92 cents a pound; March pork bellies fell .25
cent to 91.80 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
