<HEADLINE> Ohio Congressman Expects Indictment  </HEADLINE>
   By M.R. KROPKO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Campaign appearances usually include the candidate
extolling his virtues and accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
	   For U.S. Rep. James Traficant Jr., recent stops on the trail to re-election
include pronouncements about possible indictment.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democrat said last weekend he is sure the Justice Department wants to
link him to organized crime and an indictment appears inevitable.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But as much as they want to, they have been unable to link me in any way
to organized crime or any criminal acts,'' he said in a statement. ``The reason
why they have not been able to tie me to any illegal activity is very simple: I
have done nothing wrong. End of story.''
</P>
<P>
	   The congressman refuses to be put on the defensive by a federal corruption
probe that may be targeting him, even though he faces a strong challenge in the
March 7 primary in his district in northeast Ohio.
</P>
<P>
	   Traficant told a Democratic club in Niles, a Youngstown suburb, that the
FBI, the Treasury and the Justice departments had put themselves on the spot by
investigating him just before an election, and ``they'll have to come up with
something.''
</P>
<P>
	   Assistant U.S. Attorney Craig Morford, who has headed the probe of
mob-linked corruption in the Youngstown area, said Thursday he could not confirm
or deny a Traficant investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   The organized crime probe has resulted in more than 50 convictions. Among
the defendants was Charles O'Nesti, of Youngstown, former district director for
Traficant who in 1998 pleaded guilty to perjury and racketeering conspiracy
charges.
</P>
<P>
	   But O'Nesti's conviction hasn't slowed Traficant, who has fought federal
charges before.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1983, a federal jury acquitted Traficant of charges that he took $163,000
in mob money as Mahoning County sheriff.
</P>
<P>
	   He served as his own attorney -- even though he is not a lawyer -- and
argued he took only money he intended to use as evidence in making criminal
cases against mobsters. Traficant rode a wave of popularity from his
self-defense to election to Congress in 1984.
</P>
<P>
	   Political observers in his home district say he remains a legendary figure.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He's a cat with nine lives,'' said William Binning, a former Mahoning
County Republican chairman who is now a political science professor at
Youngstown State University.
</P>
<P>
	   Two other well-known public figures in Youngstown are challenging Traficant
in the primary: state Sen. Robert F. Hagan and Mahoning County Auditor George
Tablack.
</P>
<P>
	   They have tried to portray Traficant as an outdated politician who has
failed to bring this blue-collar region back from rash of steel plant closings
in the late 1970s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1755 </TRAILER>
