<DOCNO> APW20000203.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State suspends license of doctor who carved initials in mom, fines  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The state has taken away the license of an obstetrician
who carved his initials in a patient's abdomen, fined Beth Israel Medical Center
$14,000 for seven violations and required that the hospital make changes in its
reporting procedures, Health Commissioner Dr. Antonia C. Novello said Thursday.
<P>
	   The news came as the state released the findings of its investigation into
the hospital's conduct surrounding a Sept. 7, 1999 incident in which Dr. Allan
Zarkin carved the letters "A" and "Z" into 31-year-old Liana Gedz, whose baby he
had just delivered by Caesarian section.
</P>
<P>
	   "The state Health Department has now obtained the permanent surrender of Dr.
Allan Zarkin's license to practice the art of medicine. Dr. Zarkin signed the
surrender order yesterday and the chairman of the board for professional medical
conduct signed it today," Novello told reporters. "It is my hope that Dr. Zarkin
will not practice medicine in the state of New York ever again."
</P>
<P>
	   "The failure of Beth Israel was not reporting the incident as required," she
said. "We found that there were clear signs (before the incident) that Dr.
Zarkin's behavior was totally inappropriate ... There were many moments in the
system when this could have been halted."
</P>
<P>
	   A year before the incident, nurses and physicians at the hospital reported
incidents in which Zarkin, 61, "screamed" at staff members and the fathers of
newborns and pulled the arms of newborn babies, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   "There was no quality assurance documentation or follow up, and Beth Israel
hospital failed to take appropriate action with respect to Dr. Zarkin's
practice," Novello said, noting that $2,000 per violation of public health law
and the state hospital code is the highest monetary penalty allowable under
state law.
</P>
<P>
	   Beth Israel is required to come up with a "plan of correction" describing
how each of the identified deficiencies will be addressed and what corrective
action will be taken. For one year, the hospital must submit quarterly reports
to the health department detailing the corrective measures and their
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, the hospital is required to hire an independent consultant
group acceptable to the health department to analyze the management and
oversight of the hospital's obstetrics and gynecology department and provide a
detailed report of problems and suggested solutions within 60 days.
</P>
<P>
	   A consultant also must complete a hospital-wide study of quality assurance
and credentialing within 120 days.
</P>
<P>
	   Once these findings have been reported and approved by the department of
health, they must be implemented within 30 days, Novello said.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement later Thursday, the medical center said it "again expresses
its deep regret over the egregious incident involving a former staff member, Dr.
Allan Zarkin. We will continue to work cooperatively, as we have from the
outset, with the patient, her family and her representatives."
</P>
<P>
	   With regard to the health department's report, it said, "We will implement
promptly all of its recommendations."
</P>
<P>
	   Zarkin's lawyer, Kenneth Platzer, declined to comment on the health
department's findings.
</P>
<P>
	   Zarkin, his private practice New York Gyn/Ob Associates, and the hospital
are being sued by Liana Gedz for $5 million. In addition, Gedz's husband is
suing Zarkin for $500,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Platzer has said Zarkin suffers from a frontal-lobe disorder called Pick's
disease, a progressive form of Alzheimer's-like dementia characterized by
personality changes and inappropriate behavior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
