<HEADLINE> Patients' Rights Debate Coming  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ESPO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional negotiators intend to begin formal talks
next week on a compromise patients' rights bill, possibly including a provision
to permit lawsuits of HMOs, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think everything's on the table,'' Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., told
reporters after key GOP lawmakers met privately to discuss widely different
versions of legislation passed last year by the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   Both bills offer new rights to patients, but differ in important areas.
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate bill, drafted by Republicans and passed on a largely party-line
vote, applies to an estimated 61 million individuals with insurance, and does
not permit lawsuits in state courts for denied care.
</P>
<P>
	   The House-passed measure, backed by the White House and supported by
Democrats with some GOP backing, would apply to all 161 million Americans with
insurance and enable them to seek damages in state courts.
</P>
<P>
	   Frist said he hoped a final bill could be placed on President Clinton's desk
this spring.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't see any intransigence on anybody's part on any issue,'' he said,
although he added he didn't want the measure to become a ``litigation lottery''
that trial lawyers would love.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans reached out quickly this week to St. Paul Mayor Norm Coleman
after learning that veteran Democratic Rep. Bruce Vento plans to leave Congress
at the end of the term. But Coleman, a Democrat-turned-Republican, passed the
word that he's not interested in a race for the House. ``Mayor Coleman loves his
job,'' said his spokesman, Mike Zipko.
</P>
<P>
	   Vento, who is in his 12th term, disclosed on Wednesday that he has lung
cancer and will not run again so he can devote his energies to treatment.
</P>
<P>
	   He is the seventh Democrat to announce plans to step down at the end of his
term, compared with 23 Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
