<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investigators focus on collapse of steel arch  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   MILFORD, Conn. (AP) - State and federal investigators on Thursday were
trying to determine the sequence of events that brought an 80-foot steel arch
crashing down at a construction site, killing two workers and injuring two
others.
<P>
	   Inspectors from the state Department of Public Safety, including fire
marshals, crane inspectors, building inspectors and state troopers toured the
site, as did inspectors and engineers from the U.S. Occupational Health and
Safety Administration.
</P>
<P>
	   They drew up maps and reviewed witness accounts of the accident to come up
with a clearer picture of what happened when. The investigation was expected to
take some time.
</P>
<P>
	   "Out of the respect for the victims and the safety of future workers, we
will make sure we cover all the bases before calling it quits with this
investigation," Deputy Public Safety Commissioner George Luther said.
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators confirmed that the arch, made out of several hundred tons of
steel, crashed down onto a crane that was sitting nearby.
</P>
<P>
	   Some witnesses initially told investigators that it looked like the crane
collapsed and took the steel arch with it. Part of the latticed arm of the crane
ended up on top of the heap.
</P>
<P>
	   The feet of the arch remained where they were when the arch was upright,
bolted into concrete. Some bolts were broken and some of the 18-inch steel beams
were bent along the length of the structure.
</P>
<P>
	   Killed in the accident Wednesday morning were Kevin Winslow, 43, of
Newington and Wayne Most, 38, of West Hartford, both boilermakers on the
construction job.
</P>
<P>
	   The crane operator, Robert Fitch, 62, of North Branford, survived being
pinned in the wreckage for eight hours. His legs were severely crushed, and
doctors Thursday amputated one leg just above the knee - an operation necessary
to save his life, Bridgeport Hospital spokesman John Cappiello said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Previous surgical attempts failed to restore blood flow to the desired
level making amputation necessary," Cappiello said.
</P>
<P>
	   Fitch, who was in critical condition after the surgery, improved to serious
condition Thursday evening. With steady improvement, Fitch's doctors expect he
could leave the hospital within a week.
</P>
<P>
	   Another injured worker, George Scrivner, 36, of East Haddam, was treated at
the Hospital of St. Raphael in New Haven and released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The 544-megawatt plant was being built by Houston-based El Paso Energy Corp.
and Power Development Co. of Auburn, Mass., with El Paso having a 95 percent
stake in the plant. Construction of the $235 million plant started in March and
was scheduled to be completed in the first half of 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   Black &AMP; Veatch, the consulting engineering firm that was overseeing the
project, said in a written statement Thursday that it was fully cooperating with
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   "Black &AMP; Veatch places a high importance on the safety and health of its
employees and the employees of its subcontractors during performance of work.
Our safety records support the commitment to excellence in the industry," the
Kansas City, Mo.-based company said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
