<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thursday's Commodities  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVE CARPENTER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Heating oil and crude oil futures surged Thursday on the New York Mercantile
Exchange as a cold snap in the Northeast revived prices in a skittish, tightly
supplied market.
</P>
<P>
	   In other commodity markets, platinum and palladium pushed to new highs and
soybeans fell.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said the rally in most energy futures resulted from a general sense
that the previous day's pullback was overdone. Freezing or near-freezing
temperatures in much of the East also supported prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Heating oil for March delivery rose 2.37 cents to 77.90 cents a gallon,
while March crude rose 48 cents to $28.03 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
	   With new data showing U.S. crude supplies tighter than they've been since
1976, the oil market remains highly volatile and prices could skyrocket if
anything disrupts the dwindling supplies, said energy analyst Phil Flynn.
</P>
<P>
	   "All the pieces are in place for crude to make a dramatic rise," said Flynn,
of Alaron Trading Corp. in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a very delicate balance. With supplies that tight, if one little thing
goes wrong it's going to tip the applecart and apples are going to fly all over
the place," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   March unleaded gasoline rose 1.88 cents to 76.68 cents a gallon. March
natural gas fell 10 cents to $2.659 per 1,000 cubic feet in a day of
rollercoaster price swings affected by forecasts for above-average temperatures
ahead for much of the northern and central United States and speculation about
changes in OPEC production levels.
</P>
<P>
	   On London's International Petroleum Exchange, March Brent crude from the
North Sea rose 73 cents to $26.66 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
	   Platinum and palladium extended their historic rally on the New York Merc on
continued demand in a fast-tightening market for both metals.
</P>
<P>
	   April platinum rose 2 percent, settling up $8.60 to $474.80 an ounce, a 9
1/2-year high for the second straight day. March palladium jumped 3 percent,
climbing $11.80 to finish at its latest all-time high, $514.05 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
	   Both metals' prices continue to be driven higher by Russia's strategic
absence from the market. Russia supplies about two-thirds of the world's
palladium, used heavily in automobile catalytic converters, and 25 percent to 30
percent of platinum, which is currently in big demand by jewelers.
</P>
<P>
	   "In the absence of any metal from Russia, there isn't much likelihood of the
(platinum) price going down," said Tim Gardiner, head of precious metals trading
for Mitsui &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Russia hasn't made any platinum exports since April, and has supplied only
limited amounts of palladium.
</P>
<P>
	   Soybean prices sank on the Chicago Board of Trade as timely rains continued
to pelt southern Brazil during a key period for crop moisture. Soybeans fell
back to their lowest level in two weeks as forecasts called for more rain into
next week in top growing regions of South America.
</P>
<P>
	   March soybeans fell 6 1/2 cents to $5.01 a bushel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 1811 </TRAILER>
