<DOCNO> APW20000203.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls in Jittery Market  </HEADLINE>
    By PETER ALAN HARPER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) --The dollar fell broadly Thursday as turbulent markets and
rising interest rates made holders of the U.S. currency skittish.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar was quoted at 107.71 yen in trading late Thursday in New York,
down from 108.26 yen Wednesday. The euro was quoted at 98.95 cents, up from
97.57 cents late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The euro has fallen more than 17 percent from its peak the day it was
introduced a year ago January. Central bankers have maintained for most of the
year that they weren't worried about the fall of the new currency that replaces
those of 11 nations.
</P>
<P>
	   But the euro has endured several new lows in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   The European Central Bank raised interest rates Thursday, a day after the
U.S. Federal Reserve raised rates.
</P>
<P>
	   ECB president Wim Duisenberg said the quarter percentage point interest rate
rise was needed to tamp down the risk of inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   "The developments in the exchange rate of the euro are becoming a concern
with regard to price stability," he said in a speech explaining the ECB's rate
hike.
</P>
<P>
	   Kathy Jones, a currency analyst at Prudential Securities, praised Duisenberg
for giving a speech that was more effective than the actual rate hike.
</P>
<P>
	   She added that the dollar's fall came about due to a combination of events
Thursday that were more important than the rate increases.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq composite index had its third biggest point gain in history,
although blue-chip stocks were little changed. Bond prices surged for the second
day in a row on news about a shortage of bond in the near future as the U.S.
government makes fewer bonds available for sale.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar also was quoted at 1.6245 Swiss francs, down from 1.6514, and
1.4394 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4395 late Wednesday. The British pound fell
to $1.5949 from $1.6064.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the countries participating in the euro are no longer traded
separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. Based on the euro's rate,
the dollar was worth: 1.9752 German marks, down from 2.0047; 6.6245 French
francs, down from 6.7236; and 1,955.43 Italian lire, down from 1,984.70.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
