<DOCNO> APW20000203.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long-Term Bond Prices Soar  </HEADLINE>
    By DUNSTAN PRIAL AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The new investment landscape for U.S. government securities
was apparent Thursday as traders for a second straight day bid up the price of
the no-longer benchmark 30-year Treasury bond as if it were an Internet stock.
</P>
<P>
	   The long-term bond held its strongest rally in two years amid fears of a
supply crunch in the wake of the U.S. government's decision to pay off the
national debt, reducing the number of Treasury bonds in circulation.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 30-year bond soared 2 1/32 points, or $20.31 1/4 per $1,000
in face value. The surge came atop Wednesday's gain of 1 27/32 points.
</P>
<P>
	   Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, fell to 6.13 percent
Thursday from Wednesday's 6.28 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   As recently as Jan. 18, the yield on the long-term bond was at a 2 1/2-year
high of 6.75 percent. With the latest rally, yields on 30-year Treasurys are
below 1-year Treasury bills, which closed at 6.14 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 10-year bond, which many are now viewing as the replacement
bellwether government security, also soared Thursday, climbing 29/32 point, or
by $9.06 1/4.
</P>
<P>
	   The Treasury Department's pay-down program could eventually remove the
extremely popular 30-year bond from the market entirely.
</P>
<P>
	   "Folks are kind of shocked. Treasuries have become a scarce commodity," said
Gary Hunt, a mutual fund manager who oversees bond portfolios for Nationwide
Insurance in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's 'wild, wild stuff,' as Johnny Carson used to say. It's definitely a
new environment for everybody. We're all trying to figure out what this means
for the future," Hunt added.
</P>
<P>
	   Thursday's rally came on top of similarly spectacular gains on Wednesday,
when the Treasury Department announced it would scale back by $5 billion the
amount of intermediate and long-term bonds it will sell at next week's auction.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, the Treasury also said it would sell fewer 30-year bonds at its
next auction in August.
</P>
<P>
	   "The bellwether issue is no longer a bellwether," said Robert Parks, a
long-time Wall Street economist, author and finance professor at Pace University
in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Parks said the 30-year bond is probably the most liquid -- meaning the
easiest to trade -- low risk, fixed income securities contract available to
investors.
</P>
<P>
	   "These highly attractive instruments are becoming scarcer and scarcer so
people are rushing to get these things," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   But not to worry. Should the government pay off the 30-year bond debt
altogether, investors seeking long-term, low risk investments can always switch
to other types of government-backed debt, including bonds from mortgage market
companies such as Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.
</P>
<P>
	   Reducing bond sales is part the federal government's strategy to make use of
the huge budget surplus to pay down the national debt. Treasury officials said
they plan to buy back up to $30 billion of the national debt this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Adding to Thursday's mayhem was a widespread rumor that the dramatic decline
in bond yields had wiped out a large unnamed financial institution and that a
rescue meeting was being held at the Federal Reserve Bank of New York. The rumor
prompted a statement from the New York Fed denying there was a meeting to
discuss market volatility.
</P>
<P>
	   Prices of short-term Treasury securities were up  1/8 to  1/4 point, while
intermediate maturities rose 9/16 to 29/32 point, according to Bridge Telerate
news service.
</P>
<P>
	   In other trading Wednesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.60
percent, with the discount falling 0.03 percentage point from late Wednesday to
5.44 percent. Six-month yields were 5.84 percent as the discount fell 0.06
percentage point to 5.59 percent. One-year yields finished at 6.14 percent, with
the discount dropping 0.06 percentage point to 5.78 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, rose
to 5.75 percent from 5.50 percent late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bond Buyer index of municipal bonds rose 23/32 point to 92 5/32. The
yield was 6.24 percent, down from Wednesday's 6.30 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
