<DOCNO> APW20000203.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Has old DMV privatization encouraged auto 'title laundering'?  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - As Gov. Christie Whitman struggles with the
problems caused by her decision to use a private firm to conduct auto
inspections formerly operated by state workers, the governor's first effort at
motor vehicle privatization is also coming under fire.
<P>
	   State officials said Thursday they have stepped up efforts to cut down on
automobile "title laundering." But they played down published comments from the
nation's leading expert on odometer fraud that New Jersey has become an emerging
mecca for dishonest auto brokers since Whitman switched nearly two dozen DMV
offices to private control four years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Richard Morse, chief of odometer fraud investigations for the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration, told The Star-Ledger of Newark that motor
vehicle offices are so lax in spotting altered documents that fraud rings from
around the Northeast use this state to pass off forged vehicle titles.
</P>
<P>
	   "New Jersey has become a title-laundering state," Morse told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   Tim Hurd, a spokesman for the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, on Thursday said Morse was ill and not available for comment.
Hurd would not comment about Morse's remarks, only saying that "such fraud cases
are a difficult problem for consumers."
</P>
<P>
	   Morse told the newspaper that since the state turned over about two dozen
Motor Vehicles offices to private operators in 1995, New Jersey no longer had a
uniform system of detecting sham vehicle documents. Another two dozen stations
were already under private control when Whitman took her action.
</P>
<P>
	   Out-of-state wholesale used car dealers from throughout the Northeast now
use New Jersey DMV offices to obtain new titles reflecting altered odometer
readings. It is happening because the newly privatized DMV staffs have been lax
in spotting forged titles from other states, Morse said.
</P>
<P>
	   Even when staffers have rejected a title, the dealers sometimes just take
the document to another DMV office until one accepts it, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Vehicles can be sold for thousands of dollars more after crooks fraudulently
change mileage readings, especially if the figure is reduced by 100,000 miles.
Laundering, in the case of titles, means that a new title reflects the lower
reading. Therefore, anyone who buys the vehicle is handed a state government
document confirming a false count.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal investigators have targeted five major New Jersey wholesale auto
dealers suspected of laundering more than 1,000 titles annually, the newspaper
reported, citing law enforcement sources it did not name.
</P>
<P>
	   State officials said they are aware of such problems, but deny that
conditions are worse in New Jersey than in other states, or that Whitman's
privatization is to blame.
</P>
<P>
	   "We reject the notion that privatization is somehow to blame for title fraud
problems," said Department of Transportation spokesman John Dourgarian. "The
controls that were in place before privatization remain in place after
privatization. This is a national problem, and we recognize that."
</P>
<P>
	   Dourgarian said federal officials had not provided statistics to back up any
claims that title fraud is worse in New Jersey, or that it became worse after
the DMV offices were privatized. However, he also could provide no statistics
that would dispute the claims.
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, the state has recently taken action to look into such problems.
</P>
<P>
	   A New Jersey State Police unit has begun a major investigation of fraudulent
odometer readings and titles.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are always going to be individuals who attempt to wash licenses or
registrations, who attempt to get documents that they cannot get normally
through the legitimate process," said State Police spokesman John Hagerty.
"These are not new scenarios. But certainly the State Police response is due to
the recognition of a problem."
</P>
<P>
	   Dourgarian said DMV officials have instituted new rules. He said beginning
this month, used-car dealers presenting out-of-state titles are no longer able
to get new titles over the counter. From now on, new titles will be mailed after
officials review the old title closely. He said DMV officials will improve
training.
</P>
<P>
	   The Whitman administration is currently struggling with problems with long
lines after privatizing centralized inspection lanes. The privatization of the
two dozen DMV offices several years ago was bitterly opposed by state employee
unions. Whitman then pitched it as an example of "smaller, smarter government."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
