<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Head Warns on Corruption  </HEADLINE>
    By MICHELLE RAY ORTIZ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CANCUN, Mexico (AP) -- World Bank President James Wolfensohn warned a
gathering of financial ministers Thursday not to ignore the lessons of last
year's protests in Seattle, pointing in particular to Latin America's poverty
and corruption,
</P>
<P>
	   Finance ministers from across the Americas here for an economic summit
continued to offer strong support for free trade, and International Monetary
Fund managing director Michel Camdessus forecast a growth rate of nearly 4
percent for Latin America this year, "almost one point above our projections a
year ago."
</P>
<P>
	   But Wolfensohn told the 34 ministers gathered in this Mexican resort town
that they can't afford to ignore underlying social problems that limit growth.
</P>
<P>
	   The protests during the World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle were
"not something which is just a group of radicals that have been pulled together
from a training camp to come and disrupt our meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is something that is playing on the fears of people. Without
addressing the issue of poverty, there is no way we can have long-term growth
because social instability will kill it."
</P>
<P>
	   Wolfensohn said progress has occurred on several fronts: Life expectancy in
the region has grown to 69 years from 60 years in 1970; literacy is at 88
percent; infant mortality has fallen from 84 to 31 deaths per 1,000 births.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet the "persistent problem of poverty" remains a challenge, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the last 20 years, the number of poor has risen by 40 million to 175
million, equaling 36 percent of the total population, he said. Of those, 15
percent live in extreme poverty, unable to afford even a basic daily diet.
</P>
<P>
	   The poverty rate is 80 percent among the region's 30 million indigenous
people, who are concentrated in Bolivia, Ecuador, Guatemala, Mexico and Peru.
"This is not a record that any of us is proud of," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   To address the problem, Wolfensohn said governments can no longer think only
in terms of money, but must systematically work with churches, non-governmental
organizations, trade unions and the private sector. The "inner resources" of the
poor also must be put to use, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Increased trade is also a solution, he added.
</P>
<P>
	   "We must not let radicals in Seattle scare us from the task of adjusting to
globalization and giving greater opportunities to our people," Wolfensohn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
