<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whale researchers propose new gear over fishermen's objections  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   BOSTON (AP) - Tired of watching right whales die from fishing gear
entanglements, several prominent whale researchers are pushing for new
mammal-friendly fishing technology.
<P>
	   Fishermen and lobstermen, however, say the proposals are unrealistic and
unworkable - another onerous burden for an already struggling industry.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have the collision between two endangered species - the fishermen of the
New England and Mid-Atlantic coasts and the right whale, both clearly in a
precarious position," said Charles "Stormy" Mayo, a whale specialist at the
Center for Coastal Studies and one of the authors of a report calling for new
regulations.
</P>
<P>
	   With an estimated population between 300 and 350, the right whale is
hovering close to extinction. Researchers at Woods Hole have predicted the
species could be wiped out in 191 years if nothing improves.
</P>
<P>
	   With a population this small, the right whale can't afford to lose any
animals to unnatural deaths. But in the last year alone, three of the
slow-moving mammals have perished, almost certainly from man-made reasons.
</P>
<P>
	   Staccato, a longtime favorite of whale researchers, died last summer after
colliding with a ship. And two other whales, known by numbers rather than names,
are believed to have died after becoming entangled in gear.
</P>
<P>
	   One of them perished off the New Jersey coast in October. She was virtually
cut in half by fishing line that dug into her bones.
</P>
<P>
	   Another dead female was spotted off Rhode Island last month. She was seen
with fishing gear wrapped around her, but scientists can't say for certain what
killed her because her carcass was never found.
</P>
<P>
	   Researchers know of 31 entanglements since 1970, at least three of which
were fatal. Eleven other entanglements were believed to have contributed to
death. The New England Aquarium estimates 62 percent of right whales have scars
indicating fishing gear entanglements.
</P>
<P>
	   A task force was convened by the National Marine Fisheries Service in 1997
to try to reduce the number of right whale fatalities due to fishing gear. (The
agency has little control over the shipping industry.)
</P>
<P>
	   In the last two years, however, little has changed to improve the right
whale's plight, said Sharon Young, a marine mammal consultant with the Humane
Society of the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   Young, Mayo and others who devote their lives to right whales submitted a
series of proposed regulations to the NMFS committee last month.
</P>
<P>
	   "Those regulations would absolutely close down the commercial fishery," said
Bonnie Spinazzola, executive director of the Atlantic Offshore Lobsterman's
Association.
</P>
<P>
	   Moreover, she said, lobstermen wouldn't comply with such "unrealistic"
regulations "and that would do no good for the whales whatsoever."
</P>
<P>
	   Among the proposals:
</P>
<P>
	   - Eliminate the vertical fishing lines used for lobster buoys and gill nets
that trap groundfish such as cod, flounder and skate.
</P>
<P>
	   - Use lighter lines that will break apart at 200 pounds or dissolve over
time if wrapped around a whale.
</P>
<P>
	   Fishermen, however, said a strong wave would break apart such a weak line.
</P>
<P>
	   - Develop gear retrieval devices, similar to automatic garage door openers,
that will rise to the surface when lobstermen are in place to pull up their
traps.
</P>
<P>
	   The ad-hoc task force set a time frame of five years.
</P>
<P>
	   "These animals are in deep trouble," Young said. "There needs to be some
action."
</P>
<P>
	   The report, she said, was meant to be a wake-up call, not a command to
fishermen to change.
</P>
<P>
	   Fishermen aren't seeing it that way.
</P>
<P>
	   "The problem is that the technology is not available," said Dick Allen, a
Rhode Island lobsterman.
</P>
<P>
	   One Portsmouth, N.H., fisherman, who wouldn't give his name, said whale
entanglement isn't serious enough to burden fishermen with more new regulations.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's the problem with this whole system - all the laws and regulations
that they're (imposing) on the fishermen here are based on ignorance," the
36-year-old said. "Everything they do is costing us money."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
