<HEADLINE> Official: Help Latin American Poor  </HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE RAY ORTIZ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CANCUN, Mexico (AP) -- Poverty and corruption will continue to impede
economic growth in Latin American unless governments take much stronger steps to
help the poor, the World Bank president said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   James Wolfensohn warned the 34 ministers, who are gathered for an economic
summit in this Mexican resort town, that they cannot afford to ignore their
nations' underlying social problems.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Without addressing the issue of poverty,'' he said, ``there is no way we
can have long-term growth because social instability will kill it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Wolfensohn pointed to progress on several fronts: Life expectancy in the
region has grown to 69 years from 60 years in 1970. Literacy is at 88 percent,
and infant mortality has fallen from 84 to 31 deaths per 1,000 births.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet the ``persistent problem of poverty'' remains a challenge, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the last 20 years, the number of poor has risen by 40 million to 175
million, equaling 36 percent of the population, he said. Of those, 15 percent
live in extreme poverty, unable to afford even a basic daily diet.
</P>
<P>
	   The poverty rate is 80 percent among the region's 30 million indigenous
people, who are concentrated in Bolivia, Ecuador, Guatemala, Mexico and Peru, he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is not a record that any of us is proud of,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The region's income distribution is the worst in the world, he said, with
the poorest 20 percent earning 4.5 percent of wealth. The figure is 5.2 percent
in Africa, and 8.8 percent in Eastern Europe and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We compare very badly,'' Wolfensohn said.
</P>
<P>
	   Wolfensohn said governments must systematically work with churches,
nongovernmental organizations, trade unions and the private sector. The ``inner
resources'' of the poor also must be put to use, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   And, of course, he pointed to increased trade as one answer for the region.
</P>
<P>
	   Referring to the rioting that took place at last year's World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle, Wolfenson said, ``We must not let radicals in
Seattle scare us from the task of adjusting to globalization and giving greater
opportunities to our people.''
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, International Monetary Fund managing director Michel Camdessus
forecast a growth rate of nearly 4 percent for Latin America this year, ``almost
one point above our projections a year ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
