<HEADLINE> Prices Snag Low-cost Oil Program  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    BOSTON (AP) -- Citizens Energy, the nonprofit organization founded by Joseph
P. Kennedy II to provide low-cost heating oil to the poor, has been forced by
high oil prices to stop taking orders, the group announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   "During the last week of the heating oil crisis, we have fielded what would
be almost a month's worth of requests under normal conditions," the group said
in a statement. "As of today, Citizens Energy will be clearing a backlog of
thousands of deliveries before we take new ones on."
</P>
<P>
	   Since the beginning of January, the average retail price of a gallon of
heating oil in the region has risen from about 99 cents per gallon to more than
$1.70 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
	   Citizens' customers pay 40 cents per gallon.
</P>
<P>
	   Kennedy, a former congressman, called for increased funding for the federal
Low Income Home Energy Assistance Program, or LIHEAP, and he urged that
government require oil dealers to have minimum inventories on hand to avoid
price spikes during cold weather.
</P>
<P>
	   Citizens has helped more than 8,300 Massachusetts households receive
discounted oil this winter.
</P>
</TEXT>
