<HEADLINE> Alaska Will Oppose FTC on Merger  </HEADLINE>
    By DAN JOLING Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JUNEAU (AP) -- Alaska Gov. Tony Knowles said Thursday the state will go to
court to oppose a Federal Trade Commission decision to block the proposed merger
of BP Amoco and Arco.
</P>
<P>
	   FTC commissioners voted 3-2 on Wednesday to reject the merger and told its
staff to ask the courts to block the $30 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Knowles said that he and other top state officials had closely reviewed the
FTC position and found it to be flawed.
</P>
<P>
	   Prevailing FTC commissioners say the new company would have too much control
over Alaska oil production and that the merger could lead to higher gasoline
prices in California and other West Coast states.
</P>
<P>
	   Knowles said a merger agreement signed between the companies and the state
in December would ensure competition on the North Slope. He said there was no
indication that the merger would lead to higher West Coast gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
	   "The world market clearly drives the oil price," Knowles said.
</P>
<P>
	   Knowles said uncertainty over the merger is continuing to harm the Alaska
economy and threatening the nation's oil supply.
</P>
<P>
	   Knowles said the company that acquires the assets that BP Amoco is forced to
sell would immediately become of the country's top 10 oil producers.
</P>
<P>
	   In its decision, the FTC said BP Amoco has used Alaska oil exports to
restrict supply to the West Coast and keep prices artificially high.
</P>
<P>
	   But state Attorney General Bruce Botelho said a recent General Accounting
Office study, ordered by federal legislation that lifted the ban on export of
Alaska oil, found no effect on the California market connected to exports.
</P>
<P>
	   Botelho said the request for a preliminary injunction could be argued in the
next two or three months and a decision could follow a month after that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
