<HEADLINE> Nursing-Home Chain To Pay $175M  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Beverly Enterprises, the nation's largest nursing home
chain, has agreed to pay $175 million and relinquish 10 of its nursing homes for
defrauding Medicare, the Justice Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   It is the biggest settlement ever in a nursing home case, the department
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Arkansas-based company's California subsidiary agreed to plead guilty to
11 charges of submitting false bills to the government program between 1992 and
1998, federal prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
	   They said Beverly inflated the number of hours nurses spent caring for
Medicare patients at 10 nursing homes in California and elsewhere, and submitted
phony nurse sign-in sheets and other fabricated documents to support the bills.
</P>
<P>
	   The subsidiary, Beverly-California, which entered the guilty plea, will pay
a $5 million criminal fine. The parent company will pay $170 million in a civil
settlement -- $25 million immediately, and the rest to be deducted from Medicare
reimbursements over eight years, the government said.
</P>
<P>
	   The 10 homes to be divested are in California, Kansas, Washington, Georgia
and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   The case was brought to the government's attention by a whistle-blower,
Dominick Todarello, who filed the first legal action in 1995. He will get 17
percent of the settlement, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
	   "This case should put the nursing home industry on notice that we will use
every available tool, including criminal prosecution, to hold accountable those
institutions that care for our nation's most vulnerable citizens," Deputy
Attorney General Eric Holder said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Beverly Enterprises operates 561 skilled nursing facilities and 34 assisted
living centers nationwide, with about 53,000 patients.
</P>
<P>
	   Bevery Enterprises spokesman Dan Springer said the company is "pleased to
put this issue behind us."
</P>
<P>
	   "A small number of individuals at a few facilities chose to ignore corporate
policy and procedures and made mistakes," he said. "We as a company have
accepted full responsibility for those mistakes."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
