<DOCNO> APW20000203.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Black Box' Search Is in Ivory Coast  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- Scuba divers searched the ocean off this coastal
city Thursday for the ``black boxes'' of Kenya Airways Flight 431, which crashed
moments after takeoff this week.
</P>
<P>
	   Ivorian and French search teams detected the signals of both the flight data
recorder and the voice recorder on Wednesday and returned to the site the
following afternoon to try to recover them.
</P>
<P>
	   Divers said electronic equipment they need to carry out the dives was
interfering with the signals from the black box transmitters. The interference
was making it difficult to pinpoint the devices, they said.
</P>
<P>
	   After diving past darkness, they halted operations until the morning.
</P>
<P>
	   Kenya Airways Technical Director Steve Clarke, speaking in Nairobi, Kenya,
said wreckage of the main fuselage was in 200 feet of water, about a mile off
shore.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane, an Airbus 310 with 179 people on board, crashed just minutes
after taking off Sunday night from Felix Houphouet-Boigny International Airport
for Lagos, Nigeria. Ten people survived and 86 bodies have been recovered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
