<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diallo neighbor describes gunshots  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A Bronx neighbor of Amadou Diallo testified Thursday
she heard a sudden burst of gunfire that was broken by a brief pause on the
morning Diallo died in a hail of 41 police bullets.
<P>
	   Taking the witness stand in the murder trial of four police officers, Debbie
Rivera told the jury she heard no voices before the shooting began. The officers
claim they ordered Diallo to stop.
</P>
<P>
	   After the shooting stopped, Rivera said she peered out the window to see a
distraught man - thought by attorneys to be Officer Kenneth Boss - wearing a
baseball cap and a badge.
</P>
<P>
	   The man "took his hat and threw it in the street," then cursed, the
prosecution witness said. The defense later confronted her with an earlier
statement it said contradicted her account.
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecution appeared to use Rivera's testimony to try to show the
officers fired without warning and suggest they had an opportunity to realize
Diallo was not a threat. The officers allegedly continued pulling their triggers
even after the victim dropped to the floor of his apartment vestibule.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense contends the gunfire from the officer's rapid-fire weapons was
continuous and lasted less than 10 seconds. It also claims Diallo - who was hit
19 times - stayed upright until the shooting stopped.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial was adjourned until Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Boss, 28; Sean Carroll, 36; Edward McMellon, 27; and Richard Murphy, 27,
have pleaded innocent to second-degree murder charges in the slaying of Diallo,
22, an unarmed West African immigrant, shortly after midnight on Feb. 4, 1999.
If convicted, they face a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   The shooting of an unarmed black man by four white officers sparked enough
pretrial publicity and protests to prompt an appeals court to move the case to
Albany, where it is being televised. The jury is made up of six men and six
women; eight of the jurors are white and four are black.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense alleges Diallo provoked the shooting by lurking around his front
door, ignoring orders to halt for questioning and pulling a black object out of
his pocket; the object turned out to be a wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   The plainclothes officers were searching the neighborhood for violent
suspects at the time. They call Diallo's death a tragic mistake.
</P>
<P>
	   Other witnesses Thursday included a police lieutenant who arrived on the
scene minutes after the shooting, and one of Diallo's roommates.
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Kevin Cantwell said he rushed to Diallo's block after hearing Boss call
for "a boss and a bus" - police parlance for a supervisor and an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
	   Questioned by the defense, Cantwell described the officers as being stunned
and speechless, and the smell of gunpowder in the air. He found Carroll still
kneeling over Diallo's corpse.
</P>
<P>
	   "I said, 'Sean ... Sean ... Sean' - each time louder," Cantwell said. "He
didn't respond at all."
</P>
<P>
	   The roommate, Momodou Kujabi, said the last time he saw Diallo, the victim
was lying on their couch watching television. An hour later, police woke up
Kujabi and had him identify the body.
</P>
<P>
	   Kujabi dropped his head and gasped when prosecutor flashed Diallo's photo up
on a video screen. Sitting in the audience, Diallo's mother, Kadiatou appeared
to weep.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier, Rivera, 22, testified that she was changing her infant's diaper in
a second-floor bedroom when she noticed a burgundy car pull up the block. She
described four white men in street clothes getting out, then silently
approaching the Diallo front door "in slow motion."
</P>
<P>
	   The witness said she had moved away from the window when she said she heard
the blast. Asked to demonstrate the sound, Rivera rapidly tapped the witness
stand four or five times, paused perhaps one second, then resumed tapping
several more times.
</P>
<P>
	   On cross-examination, Rivera conceded the pause as "quick." She also
admitted that in an initial statement to police she described hearing about 30
shots in an unbroken succession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-03-00 2037 </TRAILER>
