<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate campaign rolls along; Lautenberg honored  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - It was bound to happen, after 62 years.
<P>
	   Dueling U.S. Senate candidates came up with the same gimmick, a free lunch,
on the 63rd New Jersey Chamber of Commerce train ride to Washington on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Likewise, a likely gubernatorial hopeful and a New Jersey business both
passed out miniature basketballs to the roughly 1,700 passengers on the annual
schmooze and booze cruise on rails.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm told my lunches are the best," said GOP Senate candidate James
Treffinger.
</P>
<P>
	   One lobbyist disagreed. Hoagies made by an Atlantic City sub shop and handed
out by Treffinger foe state Sen. William Gormley, R-Atlantic, were far better,
she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The sandwich debate was about as serious as it got on the four hour trek,
which started in Newark midday and climaxed here with a dinner honoring retiring
U.S. Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
	   Treffinger and Gormley, who are in a crowded Republican field to replace
Lautenberg, weren't the only politicians lobbying the crowd on the train.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Rep. Robert Franks, R-Berkeley Heights, who is also running for Senate,
and Democratic hopefuls Jon Corzine and Jim Florio, also braved the grueling
"walk to Washington."
</P>
<P>
	   Although Treffinger, the county executive in Essex County, is a train
veteran, this was his first foray as a statewide candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm having fun ... so far. Ask me again when we get to Washington," he said
soon after the train left Trenton.
</P>
<P>
	   Gormley said no serious candidate can afford to miss the chamber train.
</P>
<P>
	   "If you run statewide, you need to have a presence on the train. If not,
you're conspicuous by your absence," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Few minds will be made up so early in the campaign cycle, Gormley
acknowledged. Even competing campaign staffs have fun at the event, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The business crowd also had fun. One company brought a boom box and
delighted fellow passengers with constant Bruce Springsteen songs. On another
train, a bottle of Bushmills Irish Whiskey could be seen in the baggage rack
decorated with white Christmas lights.
</P>
<P>
	   One train novice, salesman Jed Hoban, said he volunteered for train duty to
meet possible clients from throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
	   He also hoped to corner some legislators. His company Consumer Health
Network is keeping a close eye on how state lawmakers regulate managed care,
Hoban said.
</P>
<P>
	   Lobbyist Judy Shaw escorted a client who was looking to drum up insurance
business during the upcoming legislative debate over school construction.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's no such thing as a substantive conversation here," said the
co-owner of The GluckShaw Group. "Still, this is a people business and people
feel more comfortable here."
</P>
<P>
	   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, he of the miniature basketballs, chose to sit
still and let the Senate and Congressional candidates who face elections this
year wear our their shoe leather. The next gubernatorial election isn't until
2001.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've got a seat. That's what everybody else is looking for," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cherry Hill Mayor Susan Bass Levin was another candidate giving away
trinkets. In her case, she continued a tradition of giving away candy. This
year's treat was a chocolate train.
</P>
<P>
	   "People know I'm a candidate, and they're coming up to me, offering help,
fund-raising," said Levin, who is running for Congress in the 3rd District.
"Also, they want my candy."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-03-00 2039 </TRAILER>
