<HEADLINE> Belgians Arguing in Cable Car Crash  </HEADLINE>
   By ESTES THOMPSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- The relatives of five Belgians killed when a
low-flying Marine jet sliced through ski gondola cables in Italy argued Thursday
for the right to sue the U.S. government for the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
	   The Belgians were among 20 people killed in the Feb. 3, 1998 accident.
</P>
<P>
	   Government lawyers said damages in such cases are handled exclusively under
a NATO treaty and cannot be addressed in U.S. courts.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Malcolm Howard said he would rule early next week.
</P>
<P>
	   The relatives' attorney, Torrence Armstrong, said he would seek $6 million
to $6.5 million for each of the five victims if the case went to trial.
</P>
<P>
	   None of the relatives appeared at the hearing, held on the second
anniversary of the accident in Cavalese, Italy.
</P>
<P>
	   Armstrong said the government hasn't yet compensated any of the families.
The Italian Senate in December approved up to $2 million for each, with the U.S.
government paying $1.5 million of each settlement, but Armstrong said the claims
process hasn't begun yet.
</P>
<P>
	   A military jury at Camp Lejeune acquitted the jet's pilot, Capt. Richard
Ashby, of manslaughter, but he served several months in prison and was dismissed
from the Marine Corps for helping destroy a videotape of the flight.
</P>
<P>
	   The jet's navigator, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, also was dismissed from the
Marines over the videotape. Charges were dropped against two back-seat crewmen.
</P>
</TEXT>
