<HEADLINE> German Leader: Democracy Is At Risk  </HEADLINE>
   By TONY CZUCZKA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- As Germany's Christian Democrats prepared to reveal new
details in a slush fund scandal, former Chancellor Helmut Kohl on Thursday met
with a party official who is trying to shed light on the sources of secret
campaign money.
</P>
<P>
	   ARD public television reported that Kohl traveled to party headquarters in
Bonn to talk with party general manager Willi Hausmann, who earlier quizzed
former Kohl aides about their knowledge of the web of secret accounts.
</P>
<P>
	   Results of the meeting were expected to be disclosed Friday, after Christian
Democrat leaders discuss a report by the party's former longtime tax adviser
Horst Weyrauch, who detailed how he managed the slush funds in a six-hour
session with party officials Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The party refused to comment on the reported meeting with Kohl.
</P>
<P>
	   Kohl has come under criticism for his stubborn refusal to identify the
sources of up to $1 million in anonymous campaign donations, even in the face of
party leaders' insistence that it would clear up allegations that government
favors had been sold.
</P>
<P>
	   With party leaders tightlipped, German media swirled with speculation
Thursday on the sources of the covert campaign funds. The mass-circulation Bild
Zeitung reported that Weyrauch identified at least one donor under questioning
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   And the influential Sueddeutsche Zeitung, citing party sources, identified
one donor as German media tycoon Leo Kirch in a report to appear in Friday's
editions. But the party and Kirch's spokesman both adamantly denied the report.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Neither he nor any unit of the Kirch group have made donations to Helmut
Kohl,'' said Johannes Schmitz, a spokesman for Kirch's Munich-based company,
Kirch-Gruppe.
</P>
<P>
	   Kirch already figured in the scandal after Kohl acknowledged last week that
he accepted six free flights from Kirch last year, when he was no longer
chancellor.
</P>
<P>
	   A magazine report linked the flights to Kohl's backing for a planned pay TV
venture by Kirch, Bertelsmann and Deutsche Telekom while he was in office, but
Kohl denied any connection.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, Kohl has defied his party and refused to identify the donors, saying
he promised to keep their names secret.
</P>
<P>
	   Party officials on Thursday questioned another former top Kohl aide in the
Christian Democrat headquarters in Bonn, Hans Terlinden, about his knowledge of
the secret accounts.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Germany's president warned that the scandal rocking the main
conservative party is undermining public trust in democratic institutions and
could make Germans turn to extremist parties.
</P>
<P>
	   President Johannes Rau suggested that the ``greatest shock to a major
democratic party in postwar Germany'' requires reforms to campaign finance
transparency laws.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The worst reaction would be if people turned away from politics or if
extremist forces gained support,'' Rau said in a speech in Berlin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 2047 </TRAILER>
