<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices moved higher early Friday, leading the
benchmark average to its highest level in 2 1/2 years. The dollar fell against
the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 206.78 points, or 1.05
percent, to hit 19,993.20 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Thursday, the
average closed up 207.51 points, or 1.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar was trading at 107.49 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange market,
down 0.45 yen from its level of 107.94 late Thursday and below 107.71 yen posted
late in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, the Nikkei briefly moved above the critical
20,000-point threshold for the first time since Aug. 1, 1997 as high-technology
issues were in strong demand, largely on the back of the sector's gains on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, the technology-dominated Nasdaq composite index rose 137.02
points, or 3.4 percent, to close Thursday at 4,210.98, its third-biggest point
gain. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 10.24 points to 11,013.44.
</P>
<P>
	   "With Nasdaq's gains, the big high-technology names like Sony and Advantest
had strong buy orders from the opening," said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager of
the stock division at Tokyo Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   Gainers in the first hours of trading included Matsushita Electric
Industrial, Sony, Softbank, and telecom giant NTT.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all first-section companies was up
19.05 points, or 1.10 percent, at 1,748.53. On Thursday, the index rose 17.62
points, or 1.02 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency markets, the greenback fell slightly against the euro following
the European Central Bank's decision to raise key rates, which also led the
currency to fall against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   Late Thursday, the central bank -- which adjusts interest rates to keep
inflation below 2 percent in the region -- raised its main refinancing rate to
3.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the first increase since November, when the ECB raised the rate by
half a percentage point to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Raising interest rates tends to cool off an overheated economy by making it
more expensive to borrow money. But it also has the added effect of buoying the
local currency because it increases returns on investments in euro-denominated
bonds.
</P>
<P>
	   The ECB's rate hike followed a similar interest rate increase Wednesday by
the U.S. Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders were eyeing U.S. non-farm payroll figures due out later in the day
for further clues to the greenback's moves.
</P>
<P>
	   The euro traded at 106.70 yen early Thursday, above its level of 105.21 yen
late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.8750
from its close at 1.8500 Thursday. Its price fell 0.21 point to 98.51.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 2048 </TRAILER>
