<HEADLINE> Energy America pays $280,000 to state after complaints of unclear  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A utility facing charges that its marketing
materials were unclear has agreed to pay a $280,000 settlement to the state.
<P>
	   Energy America, based in Stamford, Conn., will pay the Board of Public
Utilities $140,000 and the New Jersey Division of Consumer Affairs $140,000 for
a fund to educate consumers on energy deregulation.
</P>
<P>
	   The utility and the BPU worked out an agreement Wednesday over the charges.
The company agreed to stop doing business in New Jersey in December after the
BPU received hundreds of complaints from consumers who said that Energy America
agents went door-to-door switching them to the utility, sometimes saying they
were from Public Service Electric &AMP; Gas Co. Some also complained that the agents
recruited customers who did not speak English.
</P>
<P>
	   Energy America resumed operations in the state five weeks later, but the
45,000 customers it signed up last year were in limbo.
</P>
<P>
	   The accord gives those customers the option to back out. The company on
Wednesday agreed to hire a third-party vendor to contact those customers by mail
to let them know they can switch back.
</P>
<P>
	   The company will give the BPU videotapes of its training sessions with sales
agents over the next month; provide agents with consumer education materials and
require them to give the material to prospective customers, and limit
door-to-door solicitations to hours when customer call centers are open.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a fair and equitable agreement that enables us to continue bringing
additional energy savings to New Jersey's residential and small business
customers, while educating the general public about their choices under electric
deregulation," said Energy America President David Messer.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Herr, director of the Division of Consumer Affairs, called the payment
"a landmark settlement for a landmark prosecution."
</P>
<P>
	   "It sets a precedent on how New Jersey will be tough on energy deregulation,
and it sets a gold standard for conduct," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "At the root of this issue is there was a lot of customer confusion," said
Alex Hemerick, a spokeswoman for Energy America. "Hopefully this will eliminate
that."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
