<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UConn recruits include troubled Cheshire running back  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   STORRS, Conn. (AP) - Twenty-one high school and prep football players
have signed letters of intent to attend UConn next fall, including a former
Cheshire High School running back with a history of legal troubles.
<P>
	   Jason Dellaselva is currently on probation for trying to cover up his role
in a controversial traffic accident and ensuing domestic dispute. He was
sentenced two years probation last February and fined $501 on charges including
criminal mischief, breach of peace, interfering with police and several motor
vehicle violations.
</P>
<P>
	   The most serious charges stemmed from Dellaselva's arrest in January 1999
following a family fight at his home.
</P>
<P>
	   After being arrested, and while in the department's holding cell, police
said Dellaselva spit on the closed circuit camera and urinated on the walls,
sink and bunk, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
	   In October 1998, Dellaselva was arrested and charged with evading
responsibility, driving without an operator's license, speeding and failure to
maintain the proper lane. Dellaselva, then 17, and his girlfriend, Tiffany St.
Hillaire, then 18, were arrested after concocting a false story about who was
driving her car when it crashed following a party at which alcohol was served,
police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kyle Muncy, a spokesman for the athletic department, said the school would
have no comment on its decision to recruit Dellaselva.
</P>
<P>
	   Reached at home, Dellaselva said he didn't want to talk about his past.
</P>
<P>
	   UConn football coach Randy Edsall said Thursday he was excited by the
quality of the players who have agreed to attend UConn, which will step up to
the NCAA's Division I-A next season and play football in the Big East
Conference.
</P>
<P>
	   The four new Connecticut recruits are: Dellaselva; Davion Dixon of Hartford,
who played at Weaver High School, Tyler King of North Attleboro, Mass., who
played ball at Bishop Feehan High School in Avon Old Farms; and Sean Mulcahy of
Westport, who played at Staples High School.
</P>
<P>
	   UConn also signed eight high school standouts from the state of Florida, and
players representing the states of Massachusetts, New Jersey, New York,
Pennslyvania and Virginia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
