<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Pushing for Delaware Repeat  </HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER THORNE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- Steve Forbes began a four-day bus campaign across
Delaware on Thursday, pushing for a repeat of his 1996 primary victory and
saying New Hampshire proved ``there's nothing inevitable now.''
</P>
<P>
	   George W. Bush also was campaigning in the state, saying, ``If somebody runs
for president of the United States they need to run in all the states. I don't
think they ought to be picking and choosing what state to run in.''
</P>
<P>
	   That was aimed at GOP rival John McCain, who won the New Hampshire primary
by a big margin this week after skipping the Iowa caucuses. McCain is bypassing
Delaware as well.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain spokesman Howard Opinsky, with his candidate in South Carolina,
responded, ``I don't think a 50-state strategy is good if you can't win the
nomination. When we win the nomination, we'll be president of all 50 of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Basil Battaglia, Delaware's Republican state chairman, criticized
McCain, saying GOP candidates for president should run national campaigns, ``not
targeted appeals'' that ignore voters. ``John McCain's cafeteria-style approach
in the primaries is a wrongheaded short cut to winning the White House in
November,'' Battaglia said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Delaware's 12 delegates to the Republican convention are at stake in
Tuesday's primary.
</P>
<P>
	   Encouraged by Bush's loss to McCain on Tuesday, Forbes told a lunch crowd of
about 200 Rotary Club members that he had something in common with the Arizona
senator.
</P>
<P>
	   ``One thing I do share with Senator McCain is that the Republican
establishment is not very fond of us,'' Forbes said. ``I am an independent
outsider. Washington has no hooks in me.''
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes later carried that message to northern Delaware, where 153 people
traveled through snowfall to hear his conservative message at the Talleyville
Fire Hall.
</P>
<P>
	   In response to an audience question, Forbes, an abortion opponent, said he
would seek stricter federal regulation of abortion clinics, which he said are
just as dangerous as before the 1973 U.S. Supreme Court decision that legalized
abortion.
</P>
<P>
	   After New Hampshire, where he came in third, ``the polling is being put
aside,'' Forbes said. ``In this election year, there is going to be no
coronation, there is going to be no pre-appointment of presidential nominees.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, the national GOP front-runner, was greeted by the Dover High School
marching band and about 50 supporters when he landed at the Kent County Airport
in Dover.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm coming to your state and I'm going to come back to your state because
I want your vote,'' he said. ``You didn't see me skipping anything. You know
why? Because the people in this state, they're part of America. They ought to
have a voice in the process.''
</P>
<P>
	   At the Rotary lunch, Forbes returned to the same audience that heard him
speak before the primary four years ago. The group, sitting under the giant
mirrors and chandeliers of the ornate Gold Ballroom inside the Hotel du Pont,
applauded his message.
</P>
<P>
	   Frequently quoting former President Reagan, Forbes urged more military
spending, school choice and adoption of his flat federal tax plan.
</P>
<P>
	   George Harry, who heard Forbes speak to the Wilmington Rotary Club in 1996,
said many of Forbes' themes are familiar -- but said that is because many of his
ideas have been adopted by the Republican Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 2110 </TRAILER>
