<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sheriff: Fatal Fire Was Revenge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARVEY, La. (AP) -- Revenge was the motive when a man angry at being sold
phony cocaine set a suburban New Orleans apartment building on fire, killing
four children, a sheriff said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   But Jefferson Parish Sheriff Harry Lee said he does not think Whitney
Spencer, 54, intended to kill the children, ranging in age from 14 months to 7
years.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I can't imagine anybody being that mean,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
	   Spencer was booked on four counts of first-degree murder, four of attempted
first-degree murder, and one of aggravated arson in connection with Wednesday
night's blaze.
</P>
<P>
	   Deputies believe Spencer poured a flammable liquid from a soft drink bottle
and ignited it as a 10-year-old girl, one of seven children living in the
apartment, watched.
</P>
<P>
	   The 10-year-old and two others, aged 9 and 8, ran upstairs, shouting about
the fire. They hurried downstairs with their grandfather as thick smoke rose up
the stairwell.
</P>
<P>
	   They got out, but the grandfather was unable to save four others.
</P>
<P>
	   Lee said Spencer told investigators that he wanted to force Benjamin Kent,
who is in his early 20s, out of the house so he could beat him up. Spencer
accused Kent of taking $20 for what turned out to be a rock of fake cocaine, Lee
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
