<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Premiers Send Dear Jean Letter to Ottawa on Health Care
<TEXT>
<P>
	   QUEBEC (AP) -- Canada's premiers have sent Prime Minister Jean Chretien a
carefully crafted letter stressing the future of the country's health care
system is in his hands -- and checkbook.
</P>
<P>
	   The premiers ended their one-day meeting on Thursday with their ``personal
and urgent'' message to Ottawa, expecting their request for increased health
spending to be heeded in the coming federal budget.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Canadians and Quebecers share the common concern that our health system is
threatened,'' Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard said at the closing news
conference.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Right now, what is pressing, what is most urgent is a rescue operation and
the integrity of the system.''
</P>
<P>
	   The seriousness of the issue even prompted Bouchard to express some rare
confidence in the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am convinced Mr. Chretien is aware of the situation and will change his
mind,'' said Bouchard.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's about human health, it's about suffering, it's about disease,
sickness and the demand that the elected people take care of that.''
</P>
<P>
	   The leaders also briefly mentioned their support for the tax cuts Chretien
has already committed to. And they called for the government's ``immediate
attention'' in addressing the financial crisis facing farmers. ---
Muslim Man Arrested Trying To Cross Border Released From Custody
</P>
<P>
	   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- A British Columbia man was released from
U.S. custody Thursday after being held for a week without charges following his
arrest as he tried to cross the border into Washington state.
</P>
<P>
	   But Youssef Karroum, 35, was immediately rearrested by U.S. Immigration
authorities, said his lawyer Gene Grantham.
</P>
<P>
	   Immigration authorities planned to drive Karroum to the Canadian border,
Grantham said.
</P>
<P>
	   Karroum's car was ``somewhat torn apart'' by FBI officials, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They said they would try to put it back together.''
</P>
<P>
	   Karroum was detained Jan. 27 by U.S. Customs agents at the border crossing
in Blaine, Wash.
</P>
<P>
	   A U.S. magistrate judge ordered Karroum held without bail as a material
witness. A material witness can be held in order to provide testimony.
</P>
<P>
	   All records connected to Karroum's arrest, detention and release are sealed
and no further details will be released, according to the U.S. attorney
general's office in Washington state. ---
Police union calls off controversial political fundraising campaign
</P>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- Toronto's powerful police union has bowed to public
disapproval and abandoned a controversial scheme to raise cash in its bid to
defeat unfriendly politicians.
</P>
<P>
	   The union, which last week stopped selling windshield stickers as part of
the so-called True Blue campaign after police Chief David Boothby condemned the
practice, went further Thursday and halted the drive altogether. ---
Chretien Untroubled by Top Bureaucrat's Delay
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Prime Minister Jean Chretien says he doesn't mind that his
top bureaucrat did not brief him six months ago about a looming storm over
$1-billion worth of government grants.
</P>
<P>
	   Mel Cappe, the clerk of the Privy Council, was told in July about
preliminary findings of an audit at the Human Resources Department. But no
information was passed to the prime minister until Jan. 11, a week before the
audit was to be made public.
</P>
<P>
	   Chretien dismissed the delay as normal government procedure.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He's doing his job,'' the prime minister said Thursday outside a Liberal
caucus meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't want to be, I cannot be, informed of every problem in every
department every day. When they receive a problem they have to do their own
work. And when the solution is ready they come to me and I accept or do not
accept. So I'm not upset at all.''
</P>
<P>
	   The audit examined 459 job-creation, training, literacy and other grants
chosen at random from programs that together account for $1 billion a year in
federal spending.
</P>
<P>
	   It found that, in many cases, there were no adequate administrative checks
on how the money was spent or whether it achieved its objectives. ---
Bank Rate Rises, Pushing Up Consumer Borrowing Costs
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Consumer borrowing costs are going up as central banks nudge
interest rates higher to ward off troublesome inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bank of Canada raised its trendsetting interest rate by one-quarter of a
percentage point to 5.25 per cent Thursday, following the lead of the U.S.
Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
	   Major chartered banks followed, raising their prime lending rates to 6.75
per cent effective today.
</P>
<P>
	   That means mortgages and other types of credit costs will rise.
</P>
<P>
	   But economists say that won't significantly damage consumer confidence or
slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
	   Canada's rate hike came one day after the Fed increased its federal funds
rate by one-quarter of a percentage point to 5.75 per cent. It cited an
overheated American economy and the risk of inflation. ---
Budget Likely on Feb. 28, Chretien Suggests
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- The prime minister broke with tradition Thursday and
announced the date of the federal budget to a crowd of reporters. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The budget is exactly Monday in three weeks from now, or four weeks,''
Jean Chretien said following the Liberal government's two-day caucus.
</P>
<P>
	   That would make it Monday, Feb. 28. Or Monday, March 6. But March 6 is
unlikely, since Parliament is not scheduled to sit that week.
</P>
<P>
	   The budget date is usually announced by the finance minister inside the
House of Commons. But guessing when Finance Minister Paul Martin will table his
hasn't been difficult -- five of six have been in February.
</P>
<P>
	   Scott Reid, a spokesman in Martin's office, would not comment on specifics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We'll make a formal announcement in due course,'' Reid said. ``But I think
that you can do the math as suggested by the prime minister on your own quite
fully.''
</P>
<P>
	   Chretien's office declined comment. ---
Alliance Opponents Say a No Committee Doesn't Exist in Referendum
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Grassroots Reformers have been duped if they think there will
be Yes and No campaigns in an upcoming referendum on merging the party into a
larger coalition, say opponents of the Canadian Alliance.
</P>
<P>
	   Reform officials have told the rank and file there would be committees set
up to provide a balanced debate over the proposed merger.
</P>
<P>
	   But that's news to those supposedly running the No camp.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruce Stubbs, named as a chairman the No committee by the party, said he was
told only days before a weekend Reform assembly that there would be room for two
formal campaigns in the referendum debate.
</P>
<P>
	   Reformers are scheduled to vote on adopting the policies and constitution of
the proposed Canadian Alliance over the next month. A two-thirds vote in favor
would fold Reform into the new organization.
</P>
<P>
	   But Stubbs and other members of GUARD, Grassroots Reformers Against Reform's
Demise, said they refuse to participate in any sort of campaign committee --
particularly since they won't get any funding for it.
</P>
<P>
	   They say the playing field is already skewed in favor of the Canadian
Alliance since Reform Leader Preston Manning and other MPs and staffers have
been able to use party resources to promote it. ---
Canada Post Policy Angers Those Who Want Queen Mother on Stamp
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Bruce Knapp is so furious that Canada isn't honoring the
Queen Mother's 100th birthday with a stamp he's encouraging Canadians write
their MPs.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's outrageous to me,'' says Knapp, 81, of Peterborough, Ontario
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a totally unique situation -- please God that she live -- she will
be 100 years old.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Queen Mother's centennial birthday is on Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stamps for 2000, announced in December, rural mailboxes, a church and
the Pacific loon, among other images, have won over the Queen Mother for a spot
on Canadians' envelopes and stamp collectors' notebooks. ``I'm not advocating
replacing any of them,'' John Aimers, of the Monarchist League of Canada, said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If it's a question that the post office can only do so many in a year, I
would think that the loon and or the mailboxes could be postponed.''
</P>
