<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates Boosted in Early Runs  </HEADLINE>
   By EUN-KYUNG KIM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The contestants in these beauty contests don't wear
sashes or tiaras, and there's nothing even close to a swimsuit competition. The
prizes don't carry any glamour, just a little momentum for the competitors -- if
they're lucky.
</P>
<P>
	   In the world of politics, beauty contests are presidential primaries or
straw polls that allow voters to express their opinions but have nothing to do
with the delegate selection process. A political beauty pageant in Delaware this
weekend is an example.
</P>
<P>
	   The state's Democratic Party is having a primary Saturday but won't actually
allocate its 22 delegates until March 27 caucuses held throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We still believe the primary is a way to gauge public opinion and we're
asking Democrats to participate,'' said Jim Purcell, executive director of
Delaware's Democratic party. ``And being that it is a few days after New
Hampshire, it may have a little more bearing than people think.''
</P>
<P>
	   Or it may not.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's really been no history that beauty contests and straw polls have
been president makers,'' said Allan Lichtman, a presidential historian at
American University. ``If you look at the history of presidential nominations,
the front-runners almost always get nominated.''
</P>
<P>
	   Beauty contest participants are usually second-tier candidates hoping to
gain a little publicity to boost a sagging campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Republican Steve Forbes, trailing far behind George W. Bush, nearly tied the
front-runner in an Alaska Republican presidential straw poll last week. The
publisher made several campaign trips to Alaska prior to the nonbinding contest,
while Bush and rival Sen. John McCain did not show up.
</P>
<P>
	   Curt Achberger, executive director of Alaska's Republican Party, said the
state holds the straw poll to grab attention it wouldn't receive otherwise.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Alaska gets forgotten a lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Front-runners generally tend to ignore beauty contests, since they have
nothing to gain in the way of delegates, said Barbara Norrander, a political
science professor at the University of Arizona. Lesser-known candidates often
participate to get name recognition without having to compete against major
candidates with deeper pockets.
</P>
<P>
	   Because of a front-loaded election calendar this year, nominees for both
parties should be known by the end of March. Last year's resulting scramble for
earlier dates -- and increased influence -- on the 2000 calendar resulted in a
number of beauty contests.
</P>
<P>
	   Washington state Democrats, for example, have scheduled a beauty contest
primary for Feb. 29 -- but won't allocate their delegates until a week later.
</P>
<P>
	   In Arizona and Michigan, taxpayers will pay for a Feb. 22 presidential
primary in which only Republicans can participate. State Democrats instead will
hold party-run contests the following month because of a national rule that
allows only Iowa and New Hampshire to hold caucuses or primaries before March 7
without penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's no question that having a caucus run by the state party is going
to cost us some money,'' said Dennis Denno, a spokesman for Michigan Democrats.
``But we're trying to make sure that, in the end, it's a better product.''
</P>
<P>
	   Norrander wondered how Bill Bradley would try to gain momentum in the runup
to the March 7 contests after his loss Tuesday in New Hampshire's Democratic
primary.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He might end up looking around for a beauty contest,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 2147 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UConn recruits include troubled Cheshire running back  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   STORRS, Conn. (AP) - Twenty-one high school and prep football players
have signed letters of intent to attend UConn next fall, including a former
Cheshire High School running back with a history of legal troubles.
<P>
	   Jason Dellaselva is currently on probation for trying to cover up his role
in a controversial traffic accident and ensuing domestic dispute. He was
sentenced two years probation last February and fined $501 on charges including
criminal mischief, breach of peace, interfering with police and several motor
vehicle violations.
</P>
<P>
	   The most serious charges stemmed from Dellaselva's arrest in January 1999
following a family fight at his home.
</P>
<P>
	   After being arrested, and while in the department's holding cell, police
said Dellaselva spit on the closed circuit camera and urinated on the walls,
sink and bunk, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
	   In October 1998, Dellaselva was arrested and charged with evading
responsibility, driving without an operator's license, speeding and failure to
maintain the proper lane. Dellaselva, then 17, and his girlfriend, Tiffany St.
Hillaire, then 18, were arrested after concocting a false story about who was
driving her car when it crashed following a party at which alcohol was served,
police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kyle Muncy, a spokesman for the athletic department, said the school would
have no comment on its decision to recruit Dellaselva.
</P>
<P>
	   Reached at home, Dellaselva said he didn't want to talk about his past.
</P>
<P>
	   UConn football coach Randy Edsall said Thursday he was excited by the
quality of the players who have agreed to attend UConn, which will step up to
the NCAA's Division I-A next season and play football in the Big East
Conference.
</P>
<P>
	   The four new Connecticut recruits are: Dellaselva; Davion Dixon of Hartford,
who played at Weaver High School, Tyler King of North Attleboro, Mass., who
played at Bishop Feehan High School there, before playing prep school football
at Avon Old Farms; and Sean Mulcahy of Westport, who played at Staples High
School.
</P>
<P>
	   UConn also signed eight high school standouts from the state of Florida, and
players representing the states of Massachusetts, New Jersey, New York,
Pennslyvania and Virginia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
