<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Gives Birth To Triplets, Again  </HEADLINE>
   By KATHY GAMBRELL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Think triplets are a challenge? Try two sets.
</P>
<P>
	   Think that's difficult? Try giving birth to all six children before you're
20.
</P>
<P>
	   A Maryland woman this week gave birth to triplets for the second time in
less than two years, defying odds of about one in 50 million, hospital officials
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Crystal Cornick, 19, gave birth at 35 weeks to Ariel, Tyler and Tyree on
Tuesday at the University of Maryland Hospital. The babies weighed from 3 pounds
14 ounces to 5 pounds.
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike many instances of unusual multiple births, Cornick did not use
fertility drugs for either pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
	   Just as remarkably, said Ira Gewolb, director of neonatology at the
University of Maryland Hospital for Children, Cornick delivered both sets
virtually at full term. She carried all six babies for 35 weeks -- and all were
delivered naturally.
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview from her hospital room, Cornick said she and her fiance,
Richard Williams, 22, have been overwhelmed by the international attention.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm still in shock,'' Cornick said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cornick was attending Goucher College where she had majored in economics and
is planning on a career as a financial analyst. Williams had attended Baltimore
Community College, but had to leave to take a job as a truck driver, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cornick said she was planning to take a year off from school to find day
care for her older triplets when she discovered she was pregnant again.
</P>
<P>
	   Cornick said her mother will be with her, as well as Williams' parents.
</P>
<P>
	   Cornick said her pastor also helped calm her after she suddenly went from
childless to the mother of six in under two years.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He said your children are a blessing and you should feel lucky to have
them, because some people can't have children,'' she said. ``That kind of put me
at ease.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
