<HEADLINE> Baby Clothes Recalled  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Wisconsin company is recalling about 9,800 baby garments
because of rose-shaped buttons that can detach, posing a choking hazard to young
children.
</P>
<P>
	   Shopko Stores Inc. of Green Bay, Wis., has received one report of a button
found in a child's mouth, but no injuries were reported, the Consumer Product
Safety Commission said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The recalled Peek-A-Babe one-piece coveralls, and two-piece, babydoll-style
top and legging sets are 100 percent cotton garments sold in sizes 0-3M to 24M.
Writing on the collar labels includes, ``MADE IN CHINA'' and ``Peek-A-Babe.''
</P>
<P>
	   The coverall tops are made of a plush, peach-colored knit fabric and have
three cream-colored, rose-shaped buttons attached to the front.
</P>
<P>
	   The babydoll tops are made of a plush, cream-colored knit fabric and have
three peach- colored, rose-shaped buttons attached to the front.
</P>
<P>
	   Shopko stores nationwide sold these garments from June 1999 through October
1999 for between $8 and $15.
</P>
<P>
	   The safety commission advises consumers to immediately stop using the baby
clothes and return them to Shopko for a refund.
</P>
<P>
	   For more information, consumers can call Shopko at 1-800-791-7333 between 9
a.m. and 6 p.m. EST Monday through Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
