<HEADLINE> Accused carjacker of trooper's cruiser and second vehicle arrested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A 29-year-old Union County man has been arrested on
charges that he carjacked a State Police cruiser and another vehicle on the New
Jersey Turnpike during a snowstorm last month, State Police said Thursday.
<P>
	   Tyrone Montgomery, of Hillside, is being held in the Essex County Jail on
$100,000 bail after being charged with aggravated assault of a police officer,
two counts of carjacking, plus receiving stolen property and weapons and other
charges.
</P>
<P>
	   State Police Sgt. Timothy Vanak thought he was helping a motorist stranded
in the snow along the turnpike in Hamilton Township, Mercer County, on Jan. 25
when he came upon Montgomery, who was a suspect in an armed robbery that had
occurred 2 1/2 hours earlier at the James Fenimore Cooper service area on the
turnpike in Mount Laurel.
</P>
<P>
	   Police say Montgomery was placed in the rear of an unmarked trooper car when
Vanak called for a second trooper. When the second trooper arrived, Vanak got
out of his car and left the man inside. Montgomery jumped behind the wheel and
took off, police say. Vanak jumped into the back seat to try to stop Montgomery,
but he shoved a gun in Vanak's face. The trooper later jumped out of the moving
car.
</P>
<P>
	   However, the cruiser later slid off the road. Police say Montgomery then
commandeered a minivan at gunpoint from two good Samaritans who stopped to help
him.
</P>
<P>
	   State Police spokesman John Hagerty said Montgomery remains a suspect in the
Mount Laurel armed robbery but has not been charged. He said he is also under
suspicion for crimes in a "number of other police jurisdictions throughout north
Jersey."
</P>
</TEXT>
