<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beach Memorial for Alaska Air Crash  </HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTINE HANLEY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORT HUENEME, Calif. (AP) -- With most of the 88 passengers and crew still
missing with the sunken wreckage of Alaska Flight 261, friends and relatives
gathered Thursday for a subdued memorial, wading into the water and strolling
along a beach.
</P>
<P>
	   The group of about 200 met midday inside the Point Mugu Naval Air Weapons
Station in a remote area out of view of Monday's crash site off the Southern
California coast.
</P>
<P>
	   Some friends and family members cradled bouquets of white roses and baby's
breath in their arms on the way to the beach. Others carried white carton boxes
filled with a lunch, sunscreen, tissues and pen and paper.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The purpose of it is to allow them to ... either keep a journal, write a
note and leave it or maybe communicate their feelings to each another,'' said
Barbara Jean, a Red Cross worker, who helped organize three of the buses from
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   Red Cross spokesman Chris Thomas said the trip was ``one step in the
recovery process.'' Reporters were kept out of the military compound, which is a
few miles from Port Hueneme.
</P>
<P>
	   At the base, a few mourners roamed the base's shore alone, some clustered in
small groups and others waded into the chilly, Pacific waters.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearby, a bright orange Coast Guard helicopter dropped flowers and
photographs of the dead into the shimmering waters where the plane corkscrewed
then nose-dived. Searchers have recovered only four bodies.
</P>
<P>
	   Alaska Airlines employees and National Transportation Safety Board officials
helped arrange the caravan to the private site with the Red Cross. California
Highway Patrol motorcycles and patrol cars escorting the six buses to the base.
</P>
<P>
	   Alaska Airlines employees traveled separately to a beach near the crash
site, where they laid flowers and grabbed one another's arms as they walked in
the sand.
</P>
<P>
	   Across the country, the airline, which retired Flight 261, held a minute of
silence for the victims. The employees stopped working at 4:36 p.m., near the
time of the crash. At Burbank Airport, employees held hands in a large circle on
the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
	   A local pastor and business owners held a public memorial later in the day
at Port Hueneme Pier, where a few hundred residents placed balloons, flowers and
candles at the base of three palm trees. The group prayed and sang ``Ave Maria''
and ``Time to Say Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want to pray for the family and friends who lost loved ones, and we
want to give people in the community who are dealing with their own mortality a
process to grieve, too,'' said the Rev. Tracy Cook of Park View Baptist Church
in Port Hueneme.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 2217 </TRAILER>
