<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain, Bush Debate Leadership  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SUMTER, S.C. (AP) -- John McCain and George W. Bush battled Thursday for
support from South Carolina's large military population, each casting himself as
best qualified to command the nation's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
	   A new poll suggested that Bush's big lead in South Carolina surveys may have
vanished after McCain's win in New Hampshire. McCain, campaigning in high
spirits, shrugged off the Zogby poll figures suggesting the race is now very
close, saying, ``The polls will bounce up and down.''
</P>
<P>
	   Internal polling by McCain's camp suggests a deadheat, while Bush pollsters
say the Texas governor maintains a double-digit lead, although the margin is
shrinking.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was more serious about the prospect of leading the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am fully prepared to be commander in chief,'' McCain, a former Navy
pilot and Vietnam prisoner of war, told an audience outside a waterfront home in
Beaufort. ``I do not need on-the-job training.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, campaigning later with Reps. Lindsey Graham and Mark Sanford in
Charleston near the decommissioned aircraft carrier USS Yorktown, said ``the
world is still a dangerous place'' and cited tensions with terrorists and in
Iraq, North Korea and China. He talked about improving military benefits and
said ``there's no more patriotic state than South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, meanwhile, showed off endorsements from a parade of veterans' groups,
Medal of Honor winners and retired generals. And the Texas governor made a
pointed reference to McCain as potential leader, saying, ``There is a big
difference between being somebody who had a distinguished military record and
being someone who's trying to lead the country.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush sharpened his rhetoric against McCain on several fronts two days after
the Arizona senator trounced him in the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
	   ``For somebody who's talking about campaign funding reform ... I'm going to
let him explain how ... his receiving people in front of his committee who have
been contributing to his campaign is consistent,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   For the first time, the Texas governor also criticized McCain by name for
running a TV ad in South Carolina in which the senator says the difference
between the other GOP candidates and him is that ``I won't take every last dime
of the surplus and spend it on tax cuts that mostly benefit the wealthy.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, who would mandate that $2 trillion in payroll taxes destined for the
Social Security trust fund over the next 10 years not be borrowed for other
purposes, said the ad was ``Washington-style politics.'' McCain responded that
Bush is clearly not setting aside enough to protect the system, and said he
would target 62 percent of the surplus to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain also came under fire Thursday from rival Alan Keyes, who criticized
what he described as McCain's wavering stance on abortion. McCain said he
opposes abortion, but would make exceptions for cases of rape, incest or when
the mother's life is at risk.
</P>
<P>
	   ``John McCain is not pro-life, and any pro-life person who casts a vote for
John McCain betrays the principles the Republican Party espouses,'' Keyes told
about 500 people at Newberry College in Newberry, S.C.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush leveled his criticism of McCain after a star-spangled campaign
appearance at the Sumter Courthouse, just down the road from Shaw Air Force
Base.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want our future military to be lighter, more lethal, more agile, harder
to find,'' Bush said. ``We have the opportunity to redefine how war is fought
and won.''
</P>
<P>
	   He also pledged to reduce bureaucracy in veterans' affairs, saying, ``We're
not going to have lines of people who served our country asking, 'What about
me?'''
</P>
<P>
	   One Bush supporter was Adm. Thomas Moorer, who served as chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff during the Nixon administration. Another was Thomas Burch
Jr., chairman of the National Vietnam and Gulf War Veterans Coalition.
</P>
<P>
	   Burch said of McCain: ``He came home and forgot us.'' Afterward, Burch said
the senator hadn't supported his group's efforts on Agent Orange, Gulf War
Syndrome and support for families of soldiers missing in action.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain fired back that some other veterans' groups have backed him and given
him their highest awards.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Have I fooled the veterans' organizations, or is there a little
foolishness going on here?'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   Later Thursday, his campaign released a statement from veterans who support
McCain, asking Bush to repudiate Burch's comments. The campaign also noted that
McCain had raised more than $1 million over the Internet since his New Hampshire
victory.
</P>
<P>
	   ``John McCain has earned the support of thousands of veterans for his years
of service to our nation and to welfare of our veterans,'' said Orson Swindle, a
former Vietnam POW. ``He has stood at the forefront of nearly every serious
effort to preserve our nation's commitment to our veterans.''
</P>
<P>
	   And McCain and his staff seemed to relish the idea of a campaign
concentrating on veterans' issues, where he has focused much of his early South
Carolina campaigning.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Why don't we have a real good debate on national security and foreign
policy, any time?'' McCain said, while riding in the back of his bus.
</P>
<P>
	   As he cruised down the highways of coastal South Carolina, he chortled at
editorial cartoons that lampooned Bush's description of the New Hampshire loss
as ``a bump in the road.''
</P>
<P>
	   In his arguments that he is more qualified than McCain, Bush has pointed out
that 33 of McCain's Republican Senate colleagues -- including local favorite
Strom Thurmond -- have endorsed Bush. The same is true of most of the nation's
Republican governors.
</P>
<P>
	   During both days in South Carolina, Bush said the McCain camp had succeeded
in misdefining him for New Hampshire voters -- something he vowed to not let
happen in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All of the sudden in the course of the debate, I'm tagged as the guy who's
kind of a Washington guy,'' Bush said. ``I'm not going to let that happen to me
in South Carolina, because the reality is he is the person who's been the
Washington insider.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE -- AP Writer Will Lester contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
