<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nissan Issues Profit Warning  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Troubled automaker Nissan Motor Co. warned its consolidated
operating profit for the fiscal year ending March 31 is likely to fall short of
its projections because of sluggish domestic sales.
</P>
<P>
	   The company did not provide figures, but said an official revision of its
profit projection is expected in March or later.
</P>
<P>
	   In November, Nissan was projecting $832 million (90 billion yen) in
consolidated operating profit on sales of $58 billion (6.2 trillion yen) for the
current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
	   But Nissan's domestic sales plunged 14.4 percent to 773,602 in the 1999
calendar year.
</P>
<P>
	   The company, in a statement Wednesday, blamed "increased competition and a
poor Nissan model mix" for the decline in sales.
</P>
<P>
	   The warning comes as Nissan, Japan's second-largest automaker, has been
working to slash costs and return to profitability. The company is undergoing a
restructuring undertaken when Renault SA of France bought a 36.8 percent stake
earlier this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
