<DOCNO> APW20000203.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Rebounds on Interest Rate Hike  </HEADLINE>
    By HANS GREIMEL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The beleaguered euro rebounded sharply after
European interest rates were raised one-quarter percentage point Thursday, but
the central bank's president said the weak currency was just one contributing
factor in the inflation-fighting move.
</P>
<P>
	   The euro climbed to 98.95 cents in late trading Thursday in New York from
97.57 cents Wednesday and the record low of 96.68 cents reached during European
trading on Tuesday. The strong bounce came in part because many analysts did not
expect the European Central Bank to act so quickly to raise rates.
</P>
<P>
	   Even with its surge, the euro remained nearly 17 percent below the high it
reached on its debut Jan. 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   The euro's slide was one of the factors stoking inflation fears because it
made imported goods more expensive to the 11 European nations that share the
euro as a common currency.
</P>
<P>
	   But Wim Duisenberg, the president of the European Central Bank, said there
were several factors behind the decision to raise rates and attempt to cool
inflationary pressures. A recovering economy, higher oil prices and an increase
in the amount of money in circulation, all added to pressures that push up
prices.
</P>
<P>
	   "Inflation rates are now approaching higher levels than expected earlier,"
Duisenberg warned. "In order to maintain price stability, monetary policy needs
to act in a forward-looking manner."
</P>
<P>
	   In response, the bank -- which adjusts interest rates in an attempt to keep
the region's economy growing while holding inflation below 2 percent -- raised
its main refinancing rate to 3.25 percent. It was the first increase since
November, when the ECB raised the rate by half a percentage point to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Raising interest rates tends to cool off an overheated economy by making it
more expensive to borrow money. But it also has the added effect of buoying the
local currency because it increases returns on investments in euro-denominated
bonds.
</P>
<P>
	   The European Central Bank's rate increase followed a similar interest rate
increase Wednesday by the U.S. Federal Reserve Board, dashing expectations that
the year-old ECB would hold off so it wouldn't be seen as mimicking its American
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Duisenberg said for the first time that the euro's weakness
against the dollar was troubling because it threatens to spur inflation, which
is forecast at 1.5 percent for 2000 in the countries using the euro.
</P>
<P>
	   Bankers estimate that every 10-percent loss in the euro's value increases
inflation by as much as 0.5 percentage points. The euro has already shed 16
percent of its worth since being launched at $1.16 on Jan. 1, 1999, and on
Tuesday the fledgling currency bottoming out at an all-time low of $0.9668.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, economists said the rate hike of only a quarter point will likely
have little long-term impact on the value of the euro.
</P>
<P>
	   "The weakness of the euro is a function of the strength of the U.S. economy,
not a function of how weak the European economy is," said Peter Dixon, an
economist with Commmerzbank in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
	   In the countries using the euro, the economy is expected to grow around 3
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, however, the United States entered its longest economic
expansion ever -- 107 straight months of growth, with 1999 marking the third
straight year with annual growth of 4 percent or more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 2258 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
