<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guilty Plea in Indiana Sex Case  </HEADLINE>
   By RICK CALLAHAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The former head of the State Excise Police was booked
Thursday after he agreed to plead guilty to charges stemming from his acceptance
of sex, drinks and dinners from the owner of two Indianapolis strip clubs,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gene Honeycutt, who enforced Indiana's alcoholic beverage laws until he
resigned in October, reached a deal under which he agreed to plead guilty to a
felony count of ghost employment and a misdemeanor count of official misconduct.
</P>
<P>
	   If a judge accepts the plea deal, Honeycutt could be sentenced to up to
three years in prison and a $10,000 fine on the ghost employment count and one
year in prison and a $5,000 fine on the official misconduct charge.
</P>
<P>
	   After the booking, Honeycutt was released on his own recognizance. He is
scheduled for an initial hearing March 17.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutor Scott Newman said his office's ongoing investigation found
Honeycutt essentially created a group within the excise agency for after-hours
carousing at topless bars.
</P>
<P>
	   Newman said Honeycutt, 47, committed ghost employment when he encouraged
on-duty members of the Special Investigations Unit he formed early last year to
accompany him to two strip clubs for socializing, drinks, dinner and sex with
the club's female employees.
</P>
<P>
	   The official misconduct charge arose from Honeycutt's violation of state law
by accepting gratuities.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In short, they were not being paid by the taxpayers to have private booze
and sex parties with strippers on the taxpayer's time and the bar owner's
dime,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Honeycutt said in a statement he reached the plea agreement with prosecutors
to accept responsibility for his actions.
</P>
<P>
	   ``However, I must make it clear that, at no time during my tenure, did I, my
staff, or any other member of the Alcoholic Beverage Commission give favorable
treatment to any specific bar owner or permit holder,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
