<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Spill Damages Bolivia  </HEADLINE>
   By PETER McFARREN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) -- An oil spill in an Andean river flowing from
Bolivia's Lake Titicaca has killed wildlife and is hurting hundreds of Indian
farmers who depend on the river, the government said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Clean up crews were trying to contain damage from the spill, which occurred
Sunday when a flash flood broke a crude oil pipeline. Hundreds of barrels of oil
spilled into the Desaguadero River that flows into Lake Poopo.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, dead birds and fish could be see along the river shores, which
were covered with a layer of oil.
</P>
<P>
	   Aymara Indians in the region depend on the river for fishing, for their
drinking water and as a source of crop irrigation for farming.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This ecological disaster could have serious consequences for us since we
rely on the river for our food and water,'' said Julio Ticona, whose farm
touches river shores.
</P>
<P>
	   The government has deployed military and civil defense personnel to help mop
up oil. Cleanup equipment was expected to arrived from the Unites States.
</P>
<P>
	   The government sent investigators to the area, 100 miles south of La Paz, to
determine the exact amount of oil that spilled, the areas affected and what can
be done to contain the damage.
</P>
<P>
	   Minister of Sustainable Development Erick Reyes Villa said the government is
considering fining the pipeline operator, saying it did not notify the
government about the oil spill until 24 hours after it had occurred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
