<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-03 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Asks To Preserve Tropics  </HEADLINE>
   By SONYA ROSS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saying too many of the world's life forms are threatened
by logging and deforestation, President Clinton is asking Congress for $150
million to help preserve tropical forests in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
	   The president's budget plan for fiscal 2001 sets aside $150 million for a
Greening the Globe initiative to help more than 60 countries in Africa, Asia and
Latin America conserve forests that are home to a diverse range of life forms --
and that are now threatened by logging or other activities. That figure
represents an 88 percent increase over funding in the current budget.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House planned to announced the initiative Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposal could help countries like Indonesia, the leading exporter of
tropical timber and home to about 10 percent of the world's primate species, or
Bolivia, where deforestation is a threat to the biological diversity of the
Amazon.
</P>
<P>
	   Tropical forests support more than half of the planet's life forms. But they
are disappearing at a rate of more than 50 acres a minute due to activity such
as illegal logging or deliberate land clearing for agriculture. That means about
100 different species are lost each day.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Tropical forests continue to be destroyed at a disturbing rate,'' said
George Frampton, acting chairman of the White House Council on Environmental
Quality. ``The president feels strongly that the United States should do more to
stem this loss and to help developing countries strengthen their economies by
preserving their forests.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's plan was cheered by conservationists who say it would encourage
other nations and private entities to take up the cause.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If the government states that this is a priority and invests more in it,
it sends a strong message to private donors, that they're doing the right thing,
and it catalyzes further investment,'' said Russ Mittermeier, president of
Conservation International.
</P>
<P>
	   Under Clinton's plan, $100 million would go to U.S. Agency for International
Development forest conservation programs. An additional $37 million would be
used to reduce the debt of developing nations that commit to investing local
currency in forest conservation.
</P>
<P>
	   A further $10 million would go into Forest Service research into forest fire
prevention and $3 million would be used to fund Fish and Wildlife Service
efforts to protect endangered elephants, tigers and rhinos in Asia and Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   The president also will propose a new venture by USAID and National
Aeronautics and Space Administration to compile satellite maps of tropical
forests and monitor changes in them from outer space.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-03-00 2349 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000203.0326 </DOCNO>
